('callypalace', 'Cally Palace', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/callypalace#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 54.870225, -4.182448, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'callypalace', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000e7e104a6d3ba10c0af946588636f4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Cally Palace Golf Club, set within the grounds of the historic Cally Palace Hotel in Dumfries and Galloway, is a parkland course renowned for its scenic beauty and well-maintained layout. The course features gently undulating fairways, mature trees, and strategically placed bunkers, providing a challenge for golfers of all skill levels.  The layout includes a variety of holes, with tactical par fives, strategic par fours, and accurate par threes requiring thoughtful shot-making. Elevation changes and natural water features enhance both the strategic complexity and the visual appeal of the round. While beginners will find it approachable, experienced golfers are rewarded for precision and strategic planning.  Cally Palace has hosted regional competitions and enjoys a reputation for a welcoming and community-focused atmosphere. Its location within the historic estate offers stunning vistas of the surrounding countryside, blending heritage, natural beauty, and golf. The combination of classic parkland design, strategic challenge, and picturesque setting makes Cally Palace Golf Club a memorable and enjoyable Scottish golfing experience.', ''),
('cambuslang', 'Cambuslang', 'https://cambuslanggolf.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.823940, -4.163061, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000021037976f9a610c0e1eeacdd76e94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Founded in 1892, Cambuslang Golf Club sits on the south-eastern edge of Glasgow and offers a compact but characterful parkland test. The course measures just over 5,800 yards and is defined by tree-lined fairways, small greens and subtle elevation changes that place a premium on accuracy rather than power. Tight driving corridors mean the course rewards thoughtful positioning, and several holes play longer than their yardage due to gentle climbs.\r\n\r\nThe club has strong historical roots, with early course design input from local professionals before later refinements shaped the current layout. Although it has not hosted major professional championships, Cambuslang has long been respected in Lanarkshire golf circles and has produced a number of accomplished county players.\r\n\r\nIts setting provides attractive views toward the Clyde Valley, and the routing flows naturally across rolling terrain. The closing stretch is particularly demanding, with approach shots requiring precision into well-guarded greens. Cambuslang\'s charm lies in its traditional feel-unpretentious, strategic and walkable-making it a favourite for golfers who appreciate classic club golf rather than modern resort presentation.', ''),
('cameronhouse', 'Cameron House - Carrick', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/cameronhouse#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/cameronhouse#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 56.039160, -4.637160, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'cameronhouse', 1, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000000647c9ab738c12c0dba7e33103054c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Carrick at Cameron House is a modern championship-style course set on the southern shores of Loch Lomond. Designed by Doug Carrick and opened in 2007, it stretches to over 7,000 yards and blends parkland and heathland characteristics with dramatic lochside holes.\r\n\r\nThe front nine winds through mature woodland and rising ground, demanding accurate driving and offering elevated views across the water. The back nine is more open and exposed, bringing wind into play and culminating in a memorable run of holes along Loch Lomond itself. The par-3 14th and par-4 18th are particularly striking, with the loch forming a constant visual and strategic presence.\r\n\r\nWhile it has not hosted major professional events, the course has become one of Scotland\'s most recognisable resort layouts and a frequent venue for corporate and high-profile amateur competitions. Conditioning is typically excellent, and the expansive practice facilities add to its championship credentials.\r\n\r\nThe Carrick delivers a contrasting experience to traditional links-long, scenic and varied-yet still rooted in strategic design. Its combination of modern shaping, water hazards and natural elevation changes makes it both visually spectacular and a stern test for low-handicap golfers.', ''),
('cameronhousewee', 'Cameron House - Wee Demon', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/cameronhouse#/course/3', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 56.039160, -4.637160, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'cameronhouse', 3, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000000647c9ab738c12c0dba7e33103054c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Wee Demon is a compact nine-hole course at Cameron House, also designed by Doug Carrick. Though short in length, it is far from a simple pitch-and-putt. Built to championship standards with immaculate conditioning, it emphasises precision iron play and imaginative short-game recovery.\r\n\r\nThe layout features cleverly contoured greens, strategically placed bunkers and several water hazards that demand accurate distance control. Holes vary in length and angle, encouraging players to use a full range of wedges and short irons. The closing hole, played toward the Cameron House complex, offers a scenic finish with subtle slopes that test putting nerve.\r\n\r\nPrimarily intended as an introduction to golf for resort guests and families, the Wee Demon has also become a popular warm-up course for those tackling the Carrick. Its design reflects modern short-course philosophy-fast to play, visually appealing and strategically engaging.\r\n\r\nDespite its modest yardage, the course can challenge accomplished players while remaining accessible to beginners. The emphasis on shot-making and green reading makes it an ideal complement to the longer championship layout nearby, offering a relaxed yet thoughtfully designed golfing experience.', ''),
('campsie', 'Campsie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/campsie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/campsie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.982194, -4.197270, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'campsie', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000007ced992501ca10c0e9297288b8fd4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Set on the lower slopes of the Campsie Fells, Campsie Golf Club offers a scenic moorland-parkland hybrid that enjoys panoramic views across the Kelvin Valley. The course plays just under 6,000 yards but features significant elevation changes, making club selection and course management crucial.\r\n\r\nThe layout moves naturally across undulating terrain, with several holes playing uphill into plateau greens that demand precise approaches. Tree-lined sections contrast with more open moorland holes where wind becomes a factor. The variety keeps the round engaging and visually rewarding.\r\n\r\nFounded in 1898, the club reflects the character of traditional Scottish golf-modest in length yet strategically sound. While it has not hosted major championships, it has long been a respected venue for local competitions and county fixtures.\r\n\r\nThe closing holes are particularly memorable, with elevated tees providing sweeping views of the surrounding hills. Campsie\'s strength lies in its sense of place: a peaceful, rural setting combined with a thoughtful routing that maximises natural contours. It is a course that rewards patience, accurate iron play and an appreciation of Scotland\'s inland landscapes.', ''),
('canmore', 'Canmore', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/canmore#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/canmore#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.082954, -3.457696, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'canmore', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000083143c855ca90bc04489963c9e0a4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Canmore Golf Club in Dunfermline is a classic parkland course laid out across gently rolling terrain. Established in 1914, it was influenced by prominent Scottish design principles of the era, with later refinements enhancing its strategic bunkering and green complexes.\r\n\r\nThe course measures around 6,400 yards and is known for its tree-lined fairways and well-protected greens. Accuracy from the tee is essential, as overhanging branches and subtle doglegs place a premium on positioning. The greens are typically fast and contoured, rewarding confident putting.\r\n\r\nCanmore has hosted numerous regional amateur events and is highly regarded within Fife golf. While it lacks the coastal drama of nearby links, it compensates with immaculate conditioning and a strong emphasis on shot-making.\r\n\r\nThe layout builds steadily, with a demanding closing stretch that requires precise approaches into raised greens. Its welcoming atmosphere and strategic design make it popular with both members and visitors. Canmore exemplifies traditional Scottish parkland golf-challenging without being overly long, and rich in subtle design features that reward thoughtful play.', ''),
('caprington', 'Caprington', 'https://www.capringtongolfclub.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.586305, -4.507765, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000b936548cf30712c09b3dd00a0ccb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Caprington Golf Club in Kilmarnock offers a picturesque parkland test set within mature woodland and rolling countryside. Founded in 1911, the course has evolved over time to incorporate modern bunkering while retaining its traditional character.\r\n\r\nAt just over 6,000 yards, Caprington emphasises accuracy and course management. Tree-lined fairways and natural water features come into play on several holes, and the greens are noted for their subtle slopes. The opening holes ease players into the round before the course tightens, demanding precise iron play.\r\n\r\nThe club has hosted Ayrshire county events and is well regarded for its friendly atmosphere and consistent conditioning. Its setting near Caprington Castle adds to the sense of history and place.\r\n\r\nThe closing stretch is particularly strong, with a challenging par-4 that requires a well-placed tee shot to set up an approach over a burn. Caprington\'s charm lies in its balance-playable for higher handicaps yet strategically engaging for better golfers. It is a fine example of inland Ayrshire golf, combining natural beauty with thoughtful design.', ''),
('cardrona', 'Cardrona', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/cardrona#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/cardrona#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.639814, -3.106697, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'cardrona', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000087a6ecf483da08c0f0c2d66ce5d14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Cardrona Golf Course, near Peebles in the Scottish Borders, is a modern parkland layout designed by Dave Thomas. Opened in 2001, it stretches to over 6,800 yards and occupies a scenic position along the River Tweed.\r\n\r\nWide fairways and large greens give it a resort-style feel, but strategic bunkering and water hazards provide a solid test. The river comes into play on several holes, most notably on the closing stretch where risk-reward decisions are required.\r\n\r\nCardrona has hosted regional professional and amateur events and is known for its excellent practice facilities. The layout offers generous landing areas from the tee, making it accessible to higher handicaps, while the length and green complexes challenge low-handicap players.\r\n\r\nThe surrounding hills create a dramatic backdrop, and the course\'s modern shaping contrasts with the more traditional layouts found elsewhere in the Borders. Cardrona is a contemporary Scottish course that blends playability with championship aspirations, delivering a visually striking and enjoyable round.', ''),
('cardross', 'Cardross', 'https://www.cardrossgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.cardrossgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.966492, -4.645847, 0, 2114, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000fce07cea589512c03eec8502b6fb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Cardross Golf Club, overlooking the River Clyde, is a scenic moorland-parkland course with sweeping views toward the Argyll hills. Founded in 1895, it has undergone several redesigns, most notably by James Braid, whose influence is evident in the strategic bunkering and elevated greens.\r\n\r\nThe course measures around 6,200 yards and is defined by its undulating terrain and exposed hillside holes where wind plays a significant role. The routing climbs steadily in the early stages before reaching higher ground that offers panoramic vistas.\r\n\r\nCardross has a strong reputation in Dunbartonshire golf and regularly hosts county competitions. The greens are a particular feature-small, firm and subtly contoured, requiring accurate approaches.\r\n\r\nThe back nine is more open and demanding, with several long par-4s that test both distance and control. Cardross combines natural beauty with classic design principles, providing a rewarding challenge that feels both traditional and distinctive.', ''),
('carluke', 'Carluke', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/carluke#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/carluke#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.732969, -3.864518, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'carluke', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000376dc66988ea0ec0acfd9dedd1dd4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Carluke Golf Club is a traditional inland course set across rolling farmland in South Lanarkshire. Established in 1908, it reflects early 20th-century Scottish design, with a straightforward routing that makes excellent use of natural contours.\r\n\r\nMeasuring just under 6,000 yards, the course relies on strategic bunkering and sloping greens rather than length for its defence. Several holes play uphill, adding effective yardage and testing club selection. Tree-lined fairways and occasional water hazards provide variety throughout the round.\r\n\r\nCarluke has hosted numerous local and county events and is known for its welcoming atmosphere. The greens are typically well maintained and feature subtle breaks that reward careful reading.\r\n\r\nThe closing holes form a strong finish, with a demanding par-4 requiring both accuracy and distance. Carluke\'s appeal lies in its honest, traditional challenge-fair, enjoyable and rooted in the character of Scottish club golf.', ''),
('carnegie', 'Carnegie Links - Skibo Castle', 'https://www.carnegieclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.873007, -4.131437, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000faefc16b978610c0ec1681b1beef4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Carnegie Links at Skibo Castle is a private championship course set within the grounds of the exclusive Skibo estate in the Highlands. Designed by Tom Watson, it opened in 2006 and blends links-style shaping with inland terrain.\r\n\r\nThe course stretches to over 7,000 yards and features wide fairways, large undulating greens and deep revetted bunkers. While technically inland, its sandy soil and fescue grasses create a links-like playing experience. Several holes run alongside the Dornoch Firth, offering spectacular coastal views.\r\n\r\nSkibo is owned by the Carnegie Club, whose members have included high-profile figures from business and entertainment. The course is maintained to an exceptional standard and has hosted exclusive member tournaments and corporate events.\r\n\r\nThe design encourages strategic shot-making, with multiple angles into greens and risk-reward options from the tee. Carnegie Links combines luxury surroundings with a thoughtful, modern interpretation of links golf, making it one of Scotland\'s most distinctive private courses.', ''),
('carnoustie', 'Carnoustie - Championship', 'https://booking.carnoustie.com/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'carnoustie', '', 'mon,tue,wed,thu,fri,sat,sun', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.492281, -2.729476, 1, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'a', 0xe6100000010100000034bc5983f7d505c099b85510033f4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'The Championship Course at Carnoustie is one of the world\'s most revered links, famed for its uncompromising difficulty. Originally laid out by Old Tom Morris and later refined by James Braid, it stretches to over 7,400 yards and is renowned for its narrow fairways, penal bunkering and the winding Barry Burn.\r\n\r\nCarnoustie has hosted multiple Open Championships, including the dramatic 1999 victory of Paul Lawrie and the famous collapse of Jean van de Velde at the 72nd hole. It also staged the 2018 Open won by Francesco Molinari.\r\n\r\nEvery hole demands precision, with little margin for error. The closing stretch from the 14th onward is among the most demanding in championship golf, culminating in the iconic par-4 18th, where the Barry Burn threatens any approach.\r\n\r\nCarnoustie\'s reputation as \"Carnasty\" reflects its relentless test. Firm fairways, deep bunkers and ever-present wind combine to challenge even the world\'s best players. It is a pure, traditional links that rewards accuracy, patience and strategic thinking.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/Jm3iUap0Q90?si=lW-QSiQizW2fwPr4'),
('carnoustiebuddon', 'Carnoustie - Buddon', 'https://booking.carnoustie.com/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'carnoustie', '', 'mon,tue,wed,thu,fri,sat,sun', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.492281, -2.729476, 4, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'c', 0xe6100000010100000034bc5983f7d505c099b85510033f4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'The Buddon Course at Carnoustie provides a contrasting experience to the Championship layout. Originally designed by James Braid, it is shorter and more forgiving, measuring just over 6,100 yards.\r\n\r\nWider fairways and fewer penal hazards make it more accessible, yet it retains a links character with firm turf and coastal winds. Several holes run parallel to the Championship Course, offering similar vistas without the same severity.\r\n\r\nThe Buddon is popular for visiting golfers seeking a Carnoustie experience at a more playable level. It has hosted numerous amateur events and qualifying competitions.\r\n\r\nStrategic bunkering and well-placed greens ensure it remains engaging for skilled players, while its forgiving nature makes it enjoyable for higher handicaps. It serves as an excellent introduction to links golf and complements the more demanding Championship Course.', ''),
('carnoustieburnside', 'Carnoustie - Burnside', 'https://booking.carnoustie.com/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'carnoustie', '', 'mon,tue,wed,thu,fri,sat,sun', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.492281, -2.729476, 2, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe6100000010100000034bc5983f7d505c099b85510033f4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'The Burnside Course, also associated with James Braid, is the shortest of the three Carnoustie layouts but rich in character. Measuring under 6,000 yards, it offers a traditional links challenge with tight fairways and well-defended greens.\r\n\r\nThe Barry Burn comes into play on several holes, adding strategic interest. Despite its modest length, the course demands accuracy from the tee and precise iron play. It has hosted Open Championship qualifying in the past, highlighting its quality.\r\n\r\nThe Burnside\'s intimate scale and classic design make it a favourite among purists. It provides a stern test for low-handicap players while remaining manageable for others. As part of the Carnoustie complex, it offers a historic and authentic links experience.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/feJcktLyFFo?si=odofQ-rz76ynyvST'),
('carnwath', 'Carnwath', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/carnwath#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/carnwath#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.700712, -3.637950, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'carnwath', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000098dd9387851a0dc017f549eeb0d94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Carnwath Golf Club is a traditional inland course in South Lanarkshire, founded in 1907. The layout spans gently undulating farmland and measures just under 6,000 yards.\r\n\r\nTree-lined fairways and small greens place emphasis on accuracy and short-game skill. Several holes feature subtle doglegs and well-placed bunkers that reward strategic positioning. The course has hosted local and county competitions and is known for its friendly atmosphere.\r\n\r\nCarnwath\'s strength lies in its playability and traditional character. It offers a fair challenge for all abilities while maintaining the feel of classic Scottish club golf.', ''),
('carradale', 'Carradale', 'https://www.carradalegolf.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.carradalegolf.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 55.588856, -5.465109, 0, 2125, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000124da08845dc15c0d50627a25fcb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Carradale Golf Club on the Kintyre peninsula is a charming nine-hole links overlooking the Kilbrannan Sound. Founded in 1906, it occupies natural seaside terrain with sandy soil, rolling fairways and coastal winds.\r\n\r\nThe course is short but strategic, with small greens and natural hazards. Spectacular views of Arran enhance the experience, and the peaceful setting gives it a remote, traditional feel.\r\n\r\nCarradale embodies the spirit of rural Scottish links golf-simple, scenic and rooted in natural landscape.', ''),
('carrbridge', 'Carrbridge', 'https://carrbridgegolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://carrbridgegolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.287188, -3.812921, 0, 2126, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000059daa9b9dc800ec0dee68d93c2a44c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', '\r\nCarrbridge Golf Club in the Highlands is a delightful nine-hole heathland-moorland hybrid. Established in 1929, it features undulating fairways, heather-lined rough and fast greens.\r\n\r\nThough short, it requires precise shot-making and thoughtful club selection. The surrounding pine forests and mountain views create a tranquil atmosphere.\r\n\r\nCarrbridge is known for its immaculate conditioning and welcoming club culture, offering a memorable Highland golfing experience.', ''),
('carrickknowe', 'Carrick Knowe', 'https://www.edinburghleisure.co.uk/activities/golf/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'edinburgh', '', 55.938386, -3.255667, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000da54dd239b0b0ac01b834e081df84b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Carrick Knowe, located in Edinburgh, is a well-established parkland course dating from 1929. The layout features tree-lined fairways, strategic bunkering and gently contoured greens.\r\n\r\nIt has hosted regional amateur events and is respected for its consistent conditioning. The course rewards accurate driving and careful approach play.\r\n\r\nIts urban setting contrasts with its peaceful atmosphere, making it a popular venue for city golfers.', ''),
('castledouglas', 'Castle Douglas', 'https://cdgolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'masters', 'masters', '', 'south', 'No', 54.941703, -3.935203, 0, 0, 'unknown system', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000fdf7e0b54b7b0fc0c5c551b989784b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Castle Douglas Golf Club is a scenic moorland course in Dumfries and Galloway. Founded in 1899, it sits on elevated ground overlooking Carlingwark Loch.\r\n\r\nThe layout features undulating fairways, gorse-lined rough and firm greens. Wind is a constant factor, adding to the challenge. The course has hosted county events and is known for its natural beauty.', ''),
('castlepark', 'Castle Park', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/castlepark#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/castlepark#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.888283, -2.722338, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'castlepark', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000af43352559c705c0e04be141b3f14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Castle Park in Giffnock is a traditional parkland course established in 1910. Tree-lined fairways and well-placed bunkers define the layout, while subtle elevation changes add variety.\r\n\r\nIt has a strong reputation in Glasgow golf and regularly hosts local competitions. The greens are a particular highlight, offering a true and testing surface.', ''),
('cathcartcastle', 'Cathcart Castle', 'https://www.cathcartcastle.net/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.786942, -4.294354, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000082c98d226b2d11c0a7ecf483bae44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Cathcart Castle Golf Club, founded in 1895, is a historic parkland course on Glasgow\'s south side. The layout incorporates mature woodland, rolling terrain and strategically placed bunkers.\r\n\r\nThe club has hosted numerous regional events and is known for its strong competitive history. The course demands accuracy from the tee and precise iron play into well-guarded greens.\r\n\r\nCathcart Castle combines tradition, strategic design and a welcoming atmosphere, making it one of Glasgow\'s most respected member clubs.', ''),
('cathkinbraes', 'Cathkin Braes', 'https://cathkinbraesgolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.798306, -4.208037, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000008b6ebda607d510c0ac1919e42ee64b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Cathkin Braes Golf Club, established in 1888, holds the distinction of being the oldest golf course in Glasgow still on its original site. Its foundation began when three friends saw potential in the rolling moorland around Carmunnock, transforming farmland into a rudimentary 9hole layout that would evolve over the next century. The club expanded to a full 18 holes in 1906 and later invited famed architect James Braid to make improvements in the 1920s - his influence is still evident in the strategic bunkering and routing.\r\n\r\nThe course itself plays just over 6,200 yards from the back tees, a par71 moorland test that is relatively flat but deceptively tricky. Treelined fairways flank many holes, and the par3 fifth requires an intimidating carry over water to a wellprotected green. Wide panoramic views stretch north toward the Campsie Hills and the Highlands, with glimpses of Arran on a clear day.\r\n\r\nBeyond history and scenic charm, Cathkin Braes boasts a proud tradition of fostering talent, producing successful amateur competitors over the decades. The clubhouse today offers welcoming facilities, blending rich heritage with a vibrant modern club spirit.', ''),
('cawder', 'Cawder - Championship', 'https://cawder.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://cawder.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.926299, -4.226984, 5163, 0, '', '', 'cawder', 1076, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000006edc627e6ee810c0a4a833f790f64b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Championship Course at Cawder Golf Club is a classic parkland layout just north of Glasgow, renowned for its James Braid design pedigree and rich golfing tradition. Designed by fivetime Open Champion and celebrated architect James Braid, this 18hole course stretches about 6,280 yards and plays to a par of 70 from the white tees - a length that demands thoughtful strategy over brute distance.\r\n\r\nSet on the expansive Cawder Estate alongside the River Kelvin and the ancient route of the Antonine Wall, the Championship Course blends mature treelined fairways with sweeping parkland vistas toward the Campsie Hills. Braid\'s influence is clear in the wellprotected greens and strategic bunkering; the stretch from holes 13 to 16 is even affectionately nicknamed the course\'s own \"Amen Corner.\"\r\n\r\nCawder has hosted serious competition too - the Championship layout was the venue for the Bowring Ladies Scottish Open in 1987 and 1988, adding a notable chapter to its competitive history.\r\n\r\nVisitors will also appreciate the elegant 18thcentury clubhouse, replete with original features overlooking the closing green, making the end of your round as memorable as the test itself.', ''),
('cawderkeir', 'Cawder - Keir', 'https://cawder.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'clubv1', '', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 55.926299, -4.226984, 5162, 0, '', '', 'cawder', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000006edc627e6ee810c0a4a833f790f64b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Keir Course at Cawder Golf Club offers a contrasting round to its Championship sibling, combining a slightly shorter layout with thoughtful strategy and picturesque views over the surrounding countryside. Also influenced by James Braid, this par68 parkland course measures about 5,870 yards, making it a favourite for friendly rounds and relaxed society play.\r\n\r\nUnlike many parkland courses that rely solely on length, Keir rewards precision and intelligent thinking. Its wellbunkered greens and gentle elevation changes require accurate play from tee to green, and the routing near the River Kelvin creates a notably peaceful playing experience. Though shorter, the course doesn\'t feel insubstantial - small hazards and subtle contours ensure every shot matters.\r\n\r\nThe historic clubhouse, an 18thcentury building with vaulted ceilings and classic architecture, overlooks the Keir\'s finishing hole. Many golfers appreciate finishing their round here, soaking in the views and relaxed atmosphere that defines this part of Cawder Golf Club. Whether you\'re warming up before the Championship course or enjoying a standalone round, Keir offers a delightful blend of charm, challenge and Scottish parkland character.\r\n', '');
