('cawdorcastle', 'Cawdor Castle', 'https://www.cawdorcastle.com/cawdor-attractions/golf-at-cawdor-castle/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.524302, -3.925905, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000809f71e140680fc01b9df3531cc34c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Perched within the historic grounds of Cawdor Castle near Nairn in the Scottish Highlands, the Cawdor Castle Golf Course offers a relaxed and scenic 9hole parkland experience steeped in heritage. The course has been in play since the mid1970s, offering visitors a charming and approachable round framed by ancient woodlands and the castle\'s storied gardens - part of an estate that\'s been home to the Cawdor family for over 600 years.\r\n\r\nDespite its modest scale - roughly 1,400 yards at par 32 - the layout provides enjoyable variety for golfers of all levels. Narrower fairways and wellpositioned greens invite thoughtful shot shaping, while the tranquil Highland surroundings create a memorable atmosphere that blends nature and sporting tradition. The course\'s relatively short length makes it perfect as a warmup for longer rounds nearby or a relaxed game during a castle visit.\r\n\r\nCawdor Castle itself is a major highlight: a medieval tower house built in the 14th century, embedded in Scottish history, legend and literature, and unique in retaining its connection to the original family. Playing here feels like stepping into that living heritage, with golf woven into centuries of Highland culture.', ''),
('charleton', 'Charleton', 'https://charleton.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.223058, -2.863849, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000005c751daa29e906c03b8e1f2a8d1c4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Set on the stunning East Neuk coastline of Fife near Colinsburgh, Charleton Golf Club blends classic parkland golf with exceptional coastal views over the Firth of Forth. The 18hole, par72 layout stretches just over 6,400 yards and is known for its broad fairways, wellcontoured greens and strategic bunkering that reward thoughtful planning over sheer length.\r\n\r\nOpened in 1994 and designed by John Salves, Charleton stands out for the panoramic vistas it offers from many tees - particularly on elevated holes where the Forth estuary provides a constantly shifting backdrop. While not a traditional links, its parkland character incorporates enough variety to be engaging for all handicaps.\r\n\r\nThe surrounding estate, anchored by the historic Charleton House - a stately building with architectural roots reaching back to William Adam - adds a sense of place and heritage to the round. Golf here feels like part of the wider landscape, with panoramic seaside views complementing the course\'s natural contours.\r\n\r\nVisitors will find ample hospitality both at the clubhouse and within the broader estate, which includes lodges and outdoor amenities. Charleton continues to build its reputation as one of Fife\'s more enjoyable parkland tests - memorable as much for its setting as its golf.\r\n', ''),
('clober', 'Clober', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/clober#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/clober#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.949093, -4.333141, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'clober', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000b3d30fea225511c067ee21e17bf94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Nestled in the leafy suburb of Milngavie just outside Glasgow, Clober Golf Club offers an inviting parkland course that\'s both accessible and strategically interesting. The layout plays about 4,960 yards with a par of 66, making it shorter than many traditional courses but playing significantly above its yardage thanks to undulating fairways, interesting elevation changes and subtle green complexes.\r\n\r\nWhat sets Clober apart is its strong connection to golf history - the club\'s Honorary President is Sandy Lyle MBE, the celebrated Open and Masters champion whose uncle, George Lyle, was the course designer. This familial link to one of Scotland\'s most successful golfers of the modern era gives the club unique character and a proud place within local golfing circles.\r\n\r\nThe routing at Clober is thoughtful, looping through mature woodland and open parkland that challenge accuracy off the tee and short iron precision into wellguarded greens. Though compact, the course uses elevation and tight angles to keep each hole fresh and demanding.\r\n\r\nClub spirit is strong, with a welcoming atmosphere and social calendar that complements the testing yet enjoyable nature of the golf. Clober proves that a shorter course can still deliver strategic depth, natural beauty, and a true sense of club tradition.', ''),
('cluny', 'Cluny', 'https://www.clunyactivities.co.uk/golf/', '', 'Yes', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', 'No', 56.155963, -3.214389, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000027fa7c9411b709c06a317898f6134c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in rural Fife on the grounds of the Cluny Estate, the Cluny Golf Course is a friendly and accessible ninehole golf facility that showcases the gentle natural beauty of the surrounding countryside. Designed with leisure golfers in mind, this par32 course is well suited to families, beginners and those seeking a relaxed round in scenic surroundings.\r\n\r\nCluny is less about championship aspirations and more about pure enjoyment of the game and the landscape. The compact layout weaves through undulating terrain with a focus on playability, encouraging golfers to enjoy every shot without the intimidation of longer championship layouts. The openness of the course allows panoramic views across the fields and distant hills, contributing to its peaceful, welcoming character.\r\n\r\nDespite its simplicity, the course has strategic features - from gentle doglegs to thoughtfully placed bunkers and subtle green breaks - that will keep players engaged and wanting to return. Its rural Fife location also makes it a pleasant stop for countryside golf tours and casual weekend outings.\r\n\r\nCluny exemplifies the charm of Scottish golf at its most accessible - a lowpressure, scenic round where enjoyment is the primary goal, supported by wellmaintained fairways and a friendly club community.', ''),
('clydebankdistrict', 'Clydebank District', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/clydebankdistrict#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/clydebankdistrict#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.923440, -4.394350, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'clydebankdistrict', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000ddb5847cd09311c0bce82b4833f64b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Clydebank & District Golf Club is a mature parkland layout on the outskirts of Clydebank, providing a traditional inland golf experience just a short drive from Glasgow. With a course rating around 68 and measuring just over 5,800 yards, it plays as a fair test for players of a wide range of handicaps - demanding accuracy and thoughtful course management. \r\n\r\nThe routing here meanders through spacious parkland terrain, featuring treelined fairways, wellplaced bunkers and subtle elevation changes that add interest without overwhelming the golfer. The course\'s green complexes are typically true and receptive, encouraging crisp approaches and careful putting. \r\n\r\nWhile Clydebank & District hasn\'t hosted highprofile tournaments, it enjoys a loyal membership and active competition calendar - a hallmark of Scotland\'s strong club golf culture. The clubhouse acts as a social hub after play, offering hearty hospitality and a welcoming atmosphere. \r\n\r\nWhat makes this course particularly appealing is its accessibility for city golfers seeking a quick yet rewarding round close to Glasgow, without sacrificing the sense of quiet countryside that makes inland courses so enjoyable. ', ''),
('cochranecastle', 'Cochrane Castle', 'https://cochranecastle.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://cochranecastle.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 55.820334, -4.519972, 0, 2144, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000c5573b8a731412c000e65ab400e94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Cochrane Castle Golf Club in Johnstone, Renfrewshire, is an established parkland course dating from 1895, set on the historic Craigston estate. Originally laid out by noted professional Charlie Hunter, who succeeded Old Tom Morris at Prestwick, the course blends classic Victorian golfing traditions with modern strategic design. Over the years the layout has been adapted and refined, including contributions from James Braid in the mid20th century, giving the course a blend of oldschool routing and strategic bunkering that still challenges golfers today.\r\n\r\nThe 18hole, par71 layout stretches to just over 6,190 yards from the back tees, with elevated fairways offering broad views over the Campsie Fells and Ben Lomond. Mature trees, subtle elevation changes and wellplaced bunkers demand accuracy off the tee and thoughtful approaches into the greens. The greens themselves reward careful putting and reading - a hallmark of traditional Scottish parkland.\r\n\r\nCochrane Castle hosts a busy open competition calendar throughout the season, including senior, mixed and scratch events that attract competitive club golfers from across central Scotland.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse, warm and welcoming, serves as a social hub where members and visitors reflect on rounds with views over the final greens. This blend of history, challenge and generous hospitality makes Cochrane Castle a respected test in the Glasgow area.', ''),
('colonsay', 'Colonsay', 'https://visitcolonsay.co.uk/about/golf', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 56.065156, -6.243964, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000fa9ae5b2d1f918c0b091240857084c40, 'links', 'No', 'The golf course on the Isle of Colonsay is a unique Scottish links laid out on natural machair (short grass growing in sandy soil) on the west coast of this small Hebridean island. While the club\'s formal founding dates from around 1930, golf is believed to have been played on these windswept fairways as early as 1775, making it one of the oldest continuous golfing traditions in Scotland.\r\n\r\nThe 18hole links measures a modest 4,752 yards from the championship tees and features a distinctive routing that blends seamlessly into its coastal environment. With no traditional bunkers, the course\'s only hazards are those created by nature - sheep scrapes, rabbit holes and burn crossings - which have given this course its character and charm.\r\n\r\nTwo sandy Hebridean bays frame the western edge of the layout, offering dramatic views and a constant sense of place that is rare even among Scotland\'s finest seaside courses. Local club tournaments and the annual Colonsay Open AllComers event draw islanders and visitors alike for a day of relaxed competition amid stunning scenery.\r\n\r\nColonsay\'s golf is as much about experience as score: expect unpredictable winds, an intimate sense of isolation and the opportunity to play a game in its most elemental form, surrounded by sea, sky and Shetland sheep.\r\n', ''),
('colvend', 'Colvend', 'https://www.colvendgolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'masters', '', '', 'south', 'No', 54.876510, -3.737650, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000bb270f0bb5e60dc0f94ecc7a31704b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Situated on the Solway Coast overlooking sweeping views towards the Cumbrian Fells and the Isle of Man, Colvend Golf Club blends classic parkland beauty with strategic variety. The club was founded in 1905, originally as a ninehole course designed by the esteemed Willie Fernie. Later expansions and redesigns by architect Dave Thomas - and further refinements by John Souter in the late 1990s and 2000s - have developed Colvend into a challenging 18hole, par69 course that rewards both bold strategy and tactical precision.\r\n\r\nColvend\'s routing takes golfers through rolling fairways, treelined corridors and around several water features that can come into play on key holes. The original nine holes are noted for their small, wellguarded greens, while the later additions bring additional length and subtle elevation changes.\r\n\r\nOne of the standout holes is the par3 8th, where a precise tee shot over a natural hazard is required to find the receptive green - a true test of focus and shortiron accuracy. \r\n\r\nThe course\'s Scenic Solway location makes it particularly special on calm mornings when reflections of distant hills are cast across the water.\r\n\r\nColvend combines classic design pedigree with a welcoming club culture. Its competitive calendar and scenic marshals of dunes and firth views offer a memorable day of golf in southwest Scotland.\r\n', ''),
('colvillepark', 'Colville Park', 'https://colvilleparkgc.co.uk/', '', 'Yes', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 55.801474, -3.981767, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000015562aa8a8da0fc0124c35b396e64b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Colville Park Golf Club in Motherwell is a fascinating testament to the historical link between Scotlands heavy industry and its sporting culture. The course was originally gifted to the employees of the Dalzell Iron and Steel Works by the Colville family in 1923, intended as a recreational haven for the local steelworkers. While it began as a modest 9-hole layout designed by David Adams, its rapid success led to a transformation. The legendary James Braid was commissioned just two years later to extend and refine the course into the 18-hole parkland masterpiece enjoyed today.\r\n\r\nThe course is characterized by its lush, mature trees and strategic bunkering-a Braid hallmark-that requires a thoughtful approach rather than raw power. Over the decades, it has served as a competitive hub for the Lanarkshire amateur scene, and its membership has included notable local sporting figures, such as the former Motherwell and Scotland footballer Willie Redpath, who was a prominent club champion. Playing Colville Park today offers a polished and professional experience that remains deeply rooted in its community-focused, industrial origins.', ''),
('comrie', 'Comrie', 'https://comriegolf.cw.sct.dotgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://comriegolf.cw.sct.dotgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.378218, -3.986022, 0, 2148, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000941799805fe30fc017618a7269304c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Nestled in the \"gateway to the Highlands,\" Comrie Golf Club is a stunning 9-hole course that captures the quintessential charm of Perthshire golf. Established in 1891 on the Laggan Braes, the course offers a sense of total immersion in nature, with the fairways rising and falling against a backdrop of rugged hills and the Strathearn Valley. In the 1920s, the club sought the expertise of James Braid to modernize the layout. Braid utilized the dramatic, undulating topography to ensure no two holes are remotely alike, creating a routing that feels both organic and intensely tactical.\r\n\r\nComrie is widely regarded by golf architecture enthusiasts as one of the finest 9-hole tracks in the country, maintaining Braids original vision with remarkable fidelity. The greens are notoriously small and well-guarded, demanding precision on the approach. While it is a tranquil \"village\" club, it has a spirited history of local competition and has been a favorite retreat for visitors who appreciate the \"slow-golf\" movement. The absence of heavy tree-lining on several holes provides a links-like feel, where the wind and the slopes are the primary defenders of par.', ''),
('corrie', 'Corrie', 'https://www.corriegolfclub.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 55.663358, -5.161812, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000c366800bb2a514c01ec539eae8d44b40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'Nestled in the picturesque village of Sannox on the Isle of Arran, Corrie Golf Club is one of Scotland\'s charming ninehole courses, dating back to 1892. Set against the dramatic backdrop of Glen Sannox and sweeping coastal views, this small but characterful layout offers a unique golfing experience where rugged Highland scenery meets classic Scottish golfing tradition.\r\n\r\nAlthough compact - typically playing as a par62 over 18 holes using the ninehole routing twice - Corrie demands accuracy and imagination. Its greens are known for being small and tricky to read, and the variety of hole lengths keeps each loop fresh for returning players. \r\n\r\nThe course\'s atmosphere is wonderfully relaxed; there\'s no strict tee booking and the dress code reflects the informal spirit of island golf. Many players enjoy the flexibility to turn up and play, especially during quieter mornings and late afternoons.\r\n\r\nThe setting here is the star attraction: views across the sea and neighbouring islands, complemented by the rugged hills of Arran, make this a truly scenic round. Corrie is a course where golfers relish the sense of adventure and camaraderie that comes with playing Scottish golf in its purest, most welcoming form.\r\n', ''),
('covesea', 'Covesea', 'https://covesealinks.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.720589, -3.357605, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b1169f0260dc0ac0bd6da6423cdc4c40, 'links', 'No', 'Covesea Links, located near Lossiemouth in Moray, is a classic Scottish links course that combines coastal winds, firm fairways and fine seaside terrain into an accessible yet strategic round. While it doesn\'t have the length of championship routes farther east, its seaside location beside sandy dunes and crashing waves brings authentic links character to every hole.\r\n\r\nPlayed on gently undulating ground typical of Moray coast layouts, Covesea\'s routing makes the most of natural features. Firm turf encourages ground play, while strategically placed bunkers, dunes and subtle hollows challenge shotshaping and course management. The wind can be a significant factor, ensuring that even shorter holes feel strategic and engaging.([Reddit][9]) Its approachable nature and seaside scenery make Covesea a favourite among golfers seeking the links experience without the intimidation of longer, more demanding courses.\r\n\r\nAlthough it has not hosted major professional championships, Covesea is beloved by locals and visitors alike for its relaxed links charm. Playing here is often part of wider golf tours of the Moray coast, with views of the North Sea and coastal wildlife adding to the experience. The welcoming atmosphere and true links feel make Covesea a standout option for seaside golf in northern Scotland.\r\n', ''),
('cowal', 'Cowal', 'https://www.cowalgolfclub.online/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 55.963079, -4.919971, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000dc12b9e00cae13c0713b342c46fb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Perched above the scenic Firth of Clyde in Dunoon, Cowal Golf Club is a classic Scottish parkland course with historic roots. Established in 1891 and designed by legendary architect James S. Braid, it combines beautifully matured parkland terrain with outstanding water views over the Clyde estuary, the Isle of Bute and, on clear days, even Ailsa Craig.\r\n\r\nOriginally laid out as an 18hole course, Cowal today challenges golfers over approximately 6,000 yards with a par that tests thoughtful decisionmaking more than sheer power. Its mature tree lines, raised tees and wellconditioned greens reward precise driving and careful approaches - often with the breath of coastal winds to influence club choice.\r\n\r\nThroughout its history, Cowal has been a respected stop on Scotland\'s Tartan Tour, hosting the Western Ferries ProAm and nurturing talented players, including Honorary Member Lorne Kelly, who represented Great Britain & Ireland in Walker Cup play.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse overlooks the Clyde, offering panoramic views and a strong social atmosphere. Cowal exemplifies classic parkland architecture with Scottish flair - blending tradition, challenge, and impressive scenery. Whether you\'re visiting via ferry from Gourock or driving around the peninsula, it\'s a course that encapsulates Scottish golf\'s blend of natural splendor and strategic design.\r\n', ''),
('cowdenbeath', 'Cowdenbeath', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/cowdenbeath#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/cowdenbeath#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.113888, -3.336461, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'cowdenbeath', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000002009fb7612b10ac014b4c9e1930e4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Cowdenbeath Golf Club in Fife is a modern parkland layout with roots in the late 20th century. The course was established after work began on an initial nine holes in 1988 on the old Dora Coal mine site, and the full 18hole facility opened in 1991. Expanded further, the full 18hole layout was officially opened in 1996 by Sir Michael Bonallack, the influential former Secretary of The Royal and Ancient Golf Club and champion of amateur golf.\r\n\r\nToday Cowdenbeath plays to about 6,207 yards with a par of 71 from the back tees, providing a balanced test that suits a wide range of golfers. Its fairways and greens are typical of wellconditioned Fife parkland, requiring accuracy from the tee and thoughtful approaches to complex greens framed by strategic bunkers and woodland edges.\r\n\r\nThough not a historic links venue like some nearby Fife coast courses, Cowdenbeath\'s relatively recent creation and thoughtful design give it a distinct identity - a modern inland challenge rooted in central Scottish golfing tradition. Its competitive fixtures draw local and visiting golfers alike, with the clubhouse providing a relaxed social hub postround.\r\n\r\nAs a member of the local golf community with modern amenities and welcoming foliage, Cowdenbeath demonstrates how contemporary courses complement Scotland\'s deep golfing heritage.', ''),
('cowglen', 'Cowglen', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/cowglen#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/cowglen#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.819448, -4.319785, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'cowglen', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000650113b8754711c0e5620cace3e84b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Cowglen Golf Club, located on the southern edge of Glasgow, provides a wellconditioned and thoughtfully designed parkland test popular with both local members and visiting groups. Featuring a traditional 18hole layout through mature tree lines and gently rolling terrain, Cowglen rewards consistency and accuracy throughout the round.\r\n\r\nAlthough the course is not among Scotland\'s oldest, it has built a reputation for excellent playing conditions and comprehensive practice facilities, making it popular for societies and group visits. Its greens are typically well maintained and receptive, while the layout includes a variety of challenges from water features to strategic bunkers.\r\n\r\nCowglen is also known for its hospitality - with a clubhouse offering quality dining and social spaces that help round out a day on the course. The club offers tailored group packages, making it a strong choice for golf outings, corporate days and events seeking a memorable yet accessible Scottish parkland experience.\r\n\r\nVisitors often highlight the friendly welcome and the value for money that this course offers close to Glasgow, while club competitions and member events add vibrancy and community to the playing experience.\r\n', ''),
('craggan', 'Craggan', 'https://www.cairngormsactivities.co.uk/golf', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.313250, -3.628754, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000005ed5592db0070dc06abc749318a84c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Craggan Golf Course, situated near Aviemore within the Cairngorms National Park, offers an entirely different atmosphere: it is the embodiment of Highland \"mountain-style\" golf. Often referred to as the Craggan Outdoors course, this 9-hole par-three and par-four layout is celebrated for its accessibility and its breathtaking panoramic views of the Spey Valley and the distant peaks. Unlike the formal championship tracks nearby, Craggan was designed to provide an inclusive and fun experience that highlights the natural beauty of the moorland and heather.\r\n\r\nThe course is particularly famous for its relaxed \"Highland vibe,\" making it a popular choice for families and those looking for a quick, scenic round after a day of hiking or skiing. While it hasn\'t hosted the major professional tours, it is a staple of the local Highland Golf Trail and is frequently visited by those seeking a more intimate connection to the landscape. The layout rewards short-game skill, with several holes requiring shots over natural water features and through native vegetation. It is a place where the focus is on the environment and the joy of the game, proving that a course doesn\'t need 18 holes to leave a lasting impression.\r\n', ''),
('craibstone', 'Craibstone', 'https://craibstone.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://craibstone.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.183009, -2.230880, 0, 0, '', '', 'craibstone', 1987, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000062670a9dd7d801c0d4efc2d66c974c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Craibstone Golf Course, situated just north of Aberdeen, is a popular parkland layout set amid rolling farmland typical of northeast Scotland\'s inland courses. With a routing that blends mature trees, gently undulating fairways and wellplaced bunkers, Craibstone provides a strategic test that emphasizes accuracy and thoughtful planning from tee to green.\r\n', ''),
('Craigentinny', 'Craigentinny', 'https://www.edinburghleisure.co.uk/venues/craigentinny-golf-course/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'edinburgh', '', 55.964721, -3.138613, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000005167ee21e11b09c0d8614cfa7bfb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Craigentinny Golf Club, set on the eastern edge of Edinburgh, is a classic parkland course known for its welcoming atmosphere and enjoyable strategic test. Established in the early 20th century, the layout plays just over 6,200 yards with a par around 70, and combines wellconditioned fairways with a variety of bunker placements and thoughtful green complexes.\r\n\r\nOne of the defining features is its openness - tree cover is modest, allowing prevailing winds off the nearby Firth of Forth to influence club choice and shot shape. Several holes demand accuracy off the tee to avoid fairway bunkers and rough that can complicate approaches. The par3 12th and par4 16th both require precise iron play to wellguarded greens, while the final stretch provides a solid closing challenge.\r\n\r\nCraigentinny has a strong club culture and hosts competitive local fixtures throughout the season. Although not a venue for major professional tournaments, it has long been a favourite for society golf and visitors seeking a quality round within easy reach of central Edinburgh. The clubhouse reflects that welcoming spirit, offering postround food and drink where members and guests alike gather to share stories from the day.\r\n', ''),
('CraigieHill', 'CraigieHill', 'https://www.craigiehill.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.385629, -3.455699, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000002a8f6e8445a50bc0d1b1834a5c314c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'CraigieHill Golf Club in Ayrshire is a hidden gem - a traditional inland course that rewards thoughtful play over power. Founded in 1895, its routing gently winds through rolling terrain with treelined fairways and subtly contoured greens that make club selection and approach shots key to scoring well.\r\n\r\nThe course measures around 6,000 yards, playing to a par of 70. While modest in length, its strength lies in strategic variety. Holes like the testing par4 7th and the wellbunkered par3 14th challenge accuracy and shotshaping, demanding players think their way around each hole rather than simply bombing drives. The finish builds with a pair of strong closing par4s where good driving and precise iron play are rewarded.\r\n\r\nCraigieHill hasn\'t been a venue for major championships, but it has hosted numerous Ayrshire county competitions and is wellregarded within regional golf circles for its consistent conditioning and welcoming club culture. The clubhouse embodies the feel of a traditional Scottish club - unpretentious, friendly and focused on good golf and good company.\r\n', ''),
('Craigieknowes', 'Craigieknowes', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'edinburgh', '', 54.888313, -3.806599, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000f3e32f2dea730ec04ace893db4714b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Craigieknowes Golf Club, located near Paisley, offers golfers a classic parkland round with wellmaintained fairways, mature trees and a mixture of strategic holes that test various parts of your game. The course plays just over 6,000 yards with a par around 70, and its routing makes full use of the gently undulating terrain.\r\n\r\nSeveral holes require wellplaced tee shots to avoid natural hazards and mature trees, while approach shots to often sloping greens demand precision. The stretch through holes 1012 is particularly noteworthy, with a rewarding dogleg par5 and a tricky midlength par4 that both call for thoughtful decisionmaking.\r\n\r\nThough Craigieknowes is primarily a strong club course without a history of hosting professional tournaments, it has a vibrant competition calendar and active membership. Local open events attract society golfers and visitors looking for a scenic and strategic inland round within easy reach of Glasgow.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse overlooks key holes and offers a welcoming social environment. Golfers appreciate the course\'s blend of playable parkland with enough challenge to test all levels - a testament to the understated charm of Scotland\'s inland club golf.\r\n', ''),
('Craigielaw', 'Craigielaw', 'https://www.craigielawgolfclub.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'eastlothian', '', 56.007514, -2.876958, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000007cb94f8e020407c08e210038f6004c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Craigielaw Golf Club sits south of North Berwick and offers a classic Scottish parkland test just off the East Lothian coast. While the area is better known for its celebrated links courses, Craigielaw provides a contrasting inland experience with a strategic layout, mature trees, and consistently excellent conditioning.\r\n\r\nThe course measures around 6,300 yards with a par of 71, and its routing features gently undulating fairways framed by trees and natural hazards. A number of holes play along ridges and hollows, bringing subtle elevation changes into play. Notably, the par5 6th requires a wellplaced drive to set up a riskreward second, while the par3 12th\'s elevated tee shot tests club selection and nerve.\r\n\r\nCraigielaw has a strong local reputation rather than a national tournament pedigree, although it hosts regional competitions and society events throughout the season. Its proximity to several worldclass links courses makes it a popular warmup round for visitors exploring East Lothian golf.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse offers panoramic views over the course and distant coastal landscapes, creating a relaxed and convivial gathering spot after play. Craigielaw\'s blend of classic parkland character, strategic variety and scenic setting makes it a rewarding test for golfers of all abilities.', ''),
('craigmillarpark', 'Craigmillar Park', 'https://www.craigmillarpark.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.921360, -3.179373, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.craigmillarpark.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000008448861c5b6f09c0d9ebdd1feff54b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Craigmillar Park Golf Club occupies a leafy parkland site within Edinburgh\'s suburbs, offering an 18hole challenge that\'s both strategic and accessible. The course features mature tree lines, wellplaced bunkers and greens that reward accurate approach play.\r\n\r\nAt around 6,000 yards with a par of 69/70 (depending on tees), Craigmillar Park isn\'t about raw distance; it\'s about controlling the ball and navigating the course thoughtfully. Several par4s require wellplaced tee shots to set up advantageous angles into greens protected by bunkers and slopes. The par3 8th is one of its standout holes, demanding a precise midiron into a tightly guarded green.\r\n\r\nCraigmillar Park has strong ties to Edinburgh golf traditions, with a busy competition schedule throughout the summer and a welcoming club culture. While it hasn\'t hosted professional events, it is a regular fixture for society golf and county foursomes.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse sits adjacent to the final green, providing a social hub with food and drink where members and visitors recount their best shots and near misses. It\'s a course that encapsulates the spirit of traditional Scottish parkland golf - tactical, friendly and rooted in community.', ''),
('Craignure', 'Craignure', 'https://craignuregolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 56.481774, -5.729899, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000004c88b9a46aeb16c014083bc5aa3d4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Craignure Golf Club is a delightful ninehole course on the Isle of Mull, positioned in a striking Highland setting with views across Loch Na Cuilche toward the Morvern peninsula. The layout strikes a lovely balance between scenery and strategic golf - offering holes that use elevation changes, natural hazards and Highland breezes to keep each loop engaging.\r\n\r\nAlthough relatively short in length, Craignure\'s routing feels generous and varied, with several holes playing uphill or around natural features that demand thoughtful club choice. The par3 4th is a highlight; elevated tees frame distant lochs and mountains, reminding players of the dramatic backdrop against which they tee off.\r\n\r\nWhile it hasn\'t hosted major events - nor does it aim to - Craignure is treasured by locals and visiting golfers alike for its character and scenic beauty. The island location means golf here often includes seals, birds and Highland landscapes as part of the experience.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse captures that relaxed island spirit, with welcoming hospitality and an atmosphere that encourages lingering after your round. Craignure is a great example of Scotland\'s smaller courses where natural beauty and friendly club culture create a memorable day of golf.', ''),
('crailbalcomie', 'Crail - Balcomie', 'https://crailgolfingsociety.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.280829, -2.594027, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe6100000010100000027874f3a91c004c05a626534f2234c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Crail\'s Balcomie Links is one of the great classic East Neuk layouts near the historic fishing village of Crail. Designed by Old Tom Morris in the late 19th century, Balcomie is often celebrated as one of the purest representations of traditional Scottish links golf - open, windswept and shaped by the sea breeze off the Firth of Forth.\r\n\r\nThe course stretches just over 6,700 yards, with gently rolling fairways, deep dunes and firm surfaces that reward ground play and creative shotmaking. Several holes near the coastline - especially the par4 16th and par4 17th - offer dramatic views of the North Sea, while the double green shared by the 17th and 18th typifies the routing ingenuity of classic links design.\r\n\r\nBalcomie has never hosted The Open, but it has a storied history within Scottish amateur golf and is revered on the \"Links Trail\" alongside nearby courses like Elie and St Andrews. Competitive club events and open tournaments attract golfers seeking authentic seaside links at its best.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse overlooks the North Sea, and the overall experience feels timeless: firm fairways, coastal winds and strategic design reward skill, imagination and respect for links heritage - making Balcomie a mustplay link in Scotland.', ''),
('crailcraighead', 'Crail - Craighead', 'https://crailgolfingsociety.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.280829, -2.594027, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000027874f3a91c004c05a626534f2234c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'Just across from Balcomie, Craighead Links offers a distinct but complementary links experience at Crail. Designed in the early 20th century and later refined, Craighead plays slightly shorter than its neighbour but with more undulating dunes and tighter corridors that demand shaping and control.\r\n\r\nCraighead\'s routing is firm and fast, with fairways that encourage runup shots and greens that can be subtle and challenging to read. Holes like the par4 9th and par5 13th reward thoughtful routing and bold decisionmaking, especially in gusty conditions where wind becomes a factor.\r\n\r\nThis course hasn\'t hosted national championships, but it\'s highly respected on the East Neuk links circuit and draws golfers keen to experience two contrasting links at the same club. The back nine, with a series of holes nestled amid low dunes and natural hollows, showcases Scotland\'s classic seaside terrain.\r\n\r\nLike Balcomie, Craighead sits beside the North Sea, and views of sandhills and seascapes are constant companions. The clubhouse serves both courses, fostering a welcoming atmosphere where stories of waves, wind and wellplaced shots are shared long after play.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/jK539ayKnnA?si=3FoRzjrmpWV1GKBa'),
('Crichton', 'Crichton', 'https://www.crichtongolfclub.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'south', '', 55.054997, -3.594105, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000e21e4b1fbac00cc0663046240a874b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Crichton Golf Club, located near Dumfries, is a charming 9-hole parkland course set amid gently rolling countryside. Originally founded in the early 20th century, the course has matured into a test of accuracy and strategy rather than length, playing around 2,800 yards for 9 holes (5,600 yards when doubled for a full 18).\r\n\r\nThe course benefits from tree-lined fairways, strategic bunkering, and subtly contoured greens that require careful approach play. Holes 4 and 7 are particularly notable, with slight elevation changes adding challenge and character. Despite its modest scale, the layout demands focus from tee to green, rewarding golfers who think their way around.\r\n\r\nCrichton has not hosted major professional tournaments but maintains a vibrant local competition calendar, including club championships and society events. The friendly clubhouse atmosphere reflects the community spirit of Scottish golf, making it accessible to both beginners and experienced players. The scenic surroundings - with glimpses of the River Nith valley - enhance the round, giving a relaxed yet engaging golfing experience.', ''),
('crieffgolf', 'Crieff - Ferntower', 'https://crieff.intelligentgolf.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.383615, -3.824909, 1, 0, '', 'https://crieff.intelligentgolf.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000009468c9e369990ec0a5a0db4b1a314c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Ferntower Golf Club, just outside Crieff, is a historic Scottish course designed in 1897 by the renowned architect Old Tom Morris. Set amidst the rolling Perthshire countryside, it combines natural beauty with classic parkland strategy, measuring around 6,000 yards with a par of 70.\r\n\r\nThe layout features tree-lined fairways, small but challenging greens, and several signature holes that test accuracy and course management. The par-4 9th and par-5 18th are highlights, requiring precise drives and thoughtful approach shots to avoid strategically placed bunkers. Ferntower also offers panoramic views of the Grampian foothills, giving a sense of Highland grandeur.\r\n\r\nWhile it hasn\'t hosted major professional tournaments, Ferntower remains central to Perthshire amateur golf. Its traditional clubhouse provides hospitality and a strong community atmosphere, offering members and visitors alike a welcoming environment to reflect on their round. Ferntower demonstrates classic Scottish parkland charm, blending scenic landscapes with a strategically rewarding test of golf.', ''),
('crieffgolfdornock', 'Crieff - Dornock', 'https://crieff.intelligentgolf.co.uk/visitorbooking/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'intelligent', '', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.383615, -3.824909, 282, 0, '', 'https://crieff.intelligentgolf.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000009468c9e369990ec0a5a0db4b1a314c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dornock Golf Club, near Crieff, is a smaller, friendly 9-hole course set in scenic Perthshire farmland. Established in the early 1900s, Dornock provides an approachable layout with tree-lined fairways, gentle undulations, and greens that reward accurate iron play.\r\n\r\nPlaying approximately 2,700 yards for 9 holes (5,400 yards over 18), Dornock emphasizes strategy over distance. Key holes include the par-3 4th, which requires precision to avoid a small, well-bunkered green, and the finishing par-5 9th, which offers risk-reward opportunities for long hitters.\r\n\r\nThough it has not hosted professional competitions, Dornock maintains a lively local tournament schedule, supporting amateur competitions and society days. Its welcoming clubhouse reflects the community spirit of Scottish golf, making it ideal for beginners, families, and casual players. The combination of natural beauty, approachable design, and friendly environment makes Dornock a highlight of local Perthshire golf.', ''),
('crowwood', 'Crow Wood', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/crowwood#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/crowwood#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.901022, -4.118772, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'crowwood', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000d8b8fe5d9f7910c0fe7c5bb054f34b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Crow Wood Golf Club, near Falkirk, is a parkland course famous for blending accessibility with strategic depth. The 18-hole layout measures around 6,100 yards and plays to a par of 70, featuring wide fairways, tree-lined corridors, and subtly contoured greens.\r\n\r\nThe course offers a mix of short par-4s and longer par-5s, with holes like the 12th requiring well-placed drives to avoid hazards, and the 16th challenging golfers with a subtle dogleg around mature trees. Crow Wood is known for its consistent conditioning and variety of teeing options, catering to players of all abilities.\r\n\r\nWhile it has not hosted major professional events, Crow Wood has a strong local competition calendar, including club championships and society days. Its clubhouse is a social hub, offering excellent hospitality with views over the closing holes. Crow Wood embodies the essence of Scottish parkland golf: approachable, enjoyable, and strategically engaging.', ''),
('crudenbay', 'Cruden Bay', 'https://crudenbaygolfclub.co.uk/visitors/green-fees/', 'https://crudenbaygolfclub.co.uk/visitors/green-fees/', 'No', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', 'mon,tue,wed,thu,fri,sat,sun', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.408336, -1.861509, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'crudenbay', 1, 1, 'a', 0xe61000000101000000c95a43a9bdc8fdbfc5e3a25a44b44c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Cruden Bay Golf Club, in Aberdeenshire, is a legendary seaside links course dating from 1899. Designed by Tom Morris Jr., it features firm, fast fairways, deep bunkers, and natural dunes, stretching approximately 6,500 yards with a par of 71.\r\n\r\nThe course has a rich history and has hosted prestigious amateur competitions, including the Scottish Amateur Championship, while also being praised for its natural beauty and strategic design. Signature holes include the par-3 4th, requiring an accurate tee shot over dunes, and the long par-5 13th, which demands precision off the tee and clever course management.\r\n\r\nCruden Bay\'s setting offers sweeping views of the North Sea, with ever-changing coastal winds adding a challenging element to every round. The clubhouse provides traditional Scottish hospitality, reflecting the course\'s heritage and welcoming visitors from around the world. Cruden Bay remains a must-play links experience in northeast Scotland.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/Z7dqTwsSexo?si=tfkUGHq32F3h0GC2'),
('crudenbayso', 'Cruden Bay - St Olaf', 'https://crudenbaygolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'aberdeen', '', 57.413466, -1.863304, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'c', 0xe610000001010000008318e8da17d0fdbf04013274ecb44c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'St Olaf, part of the Cruden Bay Golf Club complex, is a 9-hole course designed to complement the main links. Slightly shorter, it provides a more relaxed round while retaining classic links characteristics, including sandy dunes, firm fairways, and small challenging greens.\r\n\r\nThe course is ideal for warm-ups or casual play, offering views across the North Sea and Cruden Bay village. Despite its smaller size, it features strategic holes, including the par-4 5th, which requires precise placement off the tee to navigate natural dunes.\r\n\r\nWhile St Olaf hasn\'t hosted major tournaments, it contributes to Cruden Bay\'s reputation as a destination golf venue. Its proximity to the main clubhouse ensures players benefit from the same hospitality and scenic setting as the championship course, making it perfect for visitors seeking a short, enjoyable round with authentic Scottish links character.', ''),
('Culcrieff', 'Culcrieff', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.388517, -3.844420, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000e1b4e0455fc10ec05378d0ecba314c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Culcrieff Golf Club, near Crieff, is a traditional 9-hole parkland course set amidst the rolling Perthshire countryside. Playing approximately 2,800 yards (doubled for a full 18), it provides a friendly and accessible layout that challenges golfers through tree-lined fairways and subtly undulating greens.\r\n\r\nKey holes include the par-3 5th, with a well-bunkered green, and the finishing par-5 9th, offering a risk-reward opportunity for longer hitters. Culcrieff has a strong club culture, hosting local competitions and society events, and is especially popular with families and amateur golfers seeking a scenic yet manageable course.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse reflects the warmth of Scottish golf tradition, offering hospitality and a welcoming atmosphere. Its combination of approachable design, natural beauty, and community focus makes Culcrieff a quintessential small Scottish parkland course.', ''),
('cullenlinks', 'Cullen Links', 'https://cullenlinks.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://cullenlinks.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.695460, -2.842515, 0, 0, '', '', 'cullenlinks', 520, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000931d1b8178bd06c08cd651d504d94c40, 'links', 'No', 'Cullen Links, located in Moray, is a picturesque seaside course with a long history dating to the early 1900s. While smaller than championship links, it provides a traditional Scottish golfing experience with coastal winds, firm fairways, and challenging greens.\r\n\r\nThe layout offers strategic interest through undulating fairways and small bunkered greens. Holes such as the par-3 6th and par-4 12th demand accuracy and careful reading of the wind. The course plays around 6,000 yards with a par of 70, making it approachable yet rewarding.\r\n\r\nThough Cullen Links has not hosted professional tournaments, it is a cherished local gem with a friendly community atmosphere. Its seaside setting offers panoramic views across the Moray Firth, and the clubhouse provides a welcoming space for golfers to relax and enjoy the scenic surroundings after a round.', ''),
('cupar', 'Cupar', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/cupar#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/cupar#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.319299, -3.013716, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'cupar', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000009b745b22171c08c0a05225cade284c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Cupar Golf Club, in Fife, is an inland parkland course dating from 1871. It stretches approximately 6,400 yards with a par of 71 and features mature trees, strategic bunkering, and subtle elevation changes.\r\n\r\nThe course emphasizes accuracy and strategy, with standout holes including the par-4 7th and par-5 14th, which require careful club selection. Cupar has a rich history in Fife amateur golf and regularly hosts regional competitions and open events.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse offers classic Scottish hospitality, and the course\'s central location makes it accessible for visitors exploring Fife\'s golf region. Cupar blends history, challenge, and natural beauty, representing traditional parkland golf in eastern Scotland.', '');
