('dumbarton', 'Dumbarton', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dumbarton#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.953997, -4.570354, 0, 0, '', '', '', 1029, 'dumbarton', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000369204e10a4812c0b6bddd921cfa4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dumbarton Golf Club, near Glasgow, is a mature parkland course dating back to 1895. Measuring roughly 6,000 yards with a par of 70, it offers tree-lined fairways, strategically placed bunkers, and subtle green undulations.\r\n\r\nThe par-4 9th and par-5 17th are notable holes, demanding accurate tee shots and thoughtful approaches. Dumbarton hosts a strong schedule of local competitions, society days, and amateur events, fostering a welcoming golfing community.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse provides hospitality and panoramic views over key holes. Dumbarton exemplifies classic inland Scottish parkland golf: accessible, strategic, and steeped in local tradition.', ''),
('dumfriesandcounty', 'Dumfries and County', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dumfriesandcounty#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dumfriesandcounty#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'south', 'Yes', 55.080560, -3.601510, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dumfriesandcounty', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000056bc9179e4cf0cc0d1ae42ca4f8a4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dumfries and County Golf Club, in Dumfries, is a parkland course established in 1885, featuring 18 holes across rolling countryside. Playing around 6,100 yards with a par of 71, it combines strategic challenges with scenic beauty.\r\n\r\nThe course includes tree-lined fairways, water hazards, and subtle elevation changes, with holes like the par-4 10th and par-5 18th testing accuracy and decision-making. Dumfries and County hosts local competitions and society days, maintaining a vibrant amateur golf scene.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse offers a welcoming social environment. The course represents classic Scottish parkland tradition, balancing strategic golf with natural beauty in southwest Scotland.\r\n', ''),
('dumfriesandgalloway', 'Dumfries and Galloway', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dumfriesandgalloway#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dumfriesandgalloway#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'south', 'Yes', 55.065340, -3.626200, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dumfriesandgalloway', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000a60a462575020dc0718fa50f5d884b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dumfries and Galloway Golf Club, near Dumfries, is a historic parkland course dating to 1882. It plays roughly 6,200 yards with a par of 70, featuring mature trees, strategic bunkering, and subtly contoured greens.\r\n\r\nKey holes include the par-3 6th and par-4 16th, requiring precision and careful course management. The club hosts local competitions, society days, and amateur championships.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse provides hospitality and a social hub for members and visitors. This course blends tradition, challenge, and scenic parkland surroundings, representing the best of inland Scottish golf.', ''),
('Dunaverty', 'Dunaverty', 'https://www.dunavertygolfclub.com/index.htm', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 55.312679, -5.644815, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000087e123624a9416c0b0928fdd05a84b40, 'links', 'No', 'Dunaverty Golf Club, located on the Kintyre Peninsula, is a charming 9-hole course set amid scenic coastal and Highland surroundings. While modest in size, measuring roughly 2,700 yards for 9 holes (or 5,400 yards if played twice for a full 18), it offers a strategic and enjoyable challenge for golfers of all abilities.\r\n\r\nThe course combines gently undulating fairways, natural hazards, and mature trees, creating variety despite its shorter layout. Holes such as the par-3 4th and par-5 7th stand out, requiring precise tee shots and careful approaches to navigate bunkers and sloping greens. The design emphasizes accuracy and thoughtful course management over sheer distance, making it ideal for both beginners and experienced golfers seeking a tactical test.\r\n\r\nDunaverty maintains a strong local club culture, hosting amateur competitions, society days, and friendly inter-club matches. The clubhouse provides a welcoming environment, with views across the course and surrounding countryside.\r\n\r\nWhat sets Dunaverty apart is its natural beauty and peaceful location: golfers often enjoy panoramic views of Kintyre hills and the nearby coastline. Though smaller than many Scottish courses, it delivers an authentic and rewarding inland parkland experience, reflecting the charm and community spirit of Scotland\'s smaller clubs.', ''),
('dunbar', 'Dunbar', 'https://www.dunbargolfclub.com/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 55.997828, -2.499275, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.dunbargolfclub.com', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000e6ae25e483fe03c03c84f1d3b8ff4b40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Dunbar Golf Club, in East Lothian, is a celebrated links course designed by Tom Morris in the late 19th century. Stretching around 6,400 yards with a par of 70, it features undulating fairways, deep bunkers, and firm greens, all set against dramatic views of the North Sea.\r\n\r\nThe course is strategic in nature, requiring precise shot-making and careful consideration of coastal winds. Signature holes include the par-4 12th, which demands accuracy off the tee, and the par-5 17th, offering a risk-reward decision along the dunes. Dunbar has hosted regional amateur tournaments and is a popular stop for visiting links enthusiasts exploring the East Lothian coast.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse offers panoramic views over the course and the sea, with a welcoming atmosphere. Dunbar exemplifies classic Scottish links, blending history, challenge, and natural beauty in a memorable golfing experience.', ''),
('dunblanenew', 'Dunblane New', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunblanenew#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunblanenew#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.179627, -3.954564, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dunblanenew', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000f5824f73f2a20fc0433d7d04fe164c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dunblane New Golf Club, near Stirling, is a mature parkland course offering a balanced mix of challenge and accessibility. Measuring around 6,100 yards with a par of 70, it features tree-lined fairways, strategically placed bunkers, and subtly contoured greens.\r\n\r\nKey holes include the par-4 9th and par-5 18th, where precise drives and thoughtful approaches are rewarded. The course has a strong community focus, hosting local competitions, society days, and junior events.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse provides hospitality and scenic views over the surrounding countryside. Dunblane New embodies classic Scottish parkland design, emphasizing accuracy, strategic thinking, and enjoyable play for golfers of all abilities.', ''),
('dundasparks', 'Dundas Parks', 'https://dundasparks.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://dundasparks.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.973763, -3.407916, 0, 0, '', '', 'dundasparks', 299, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000001fbc7669430bc005871744a4fc4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dundas Parks Golf Club, located near Falkirk, is a modern 18-hole parkland course set in well-maintained, gently rolling terrain. Measuring approximately 6,200 yards with a par of 71, it features tree-lined fairways, bunkers, and water hazards that provide both challenge and variety.\r\n\r\nThe par-4 10th and par-5 16th are standout holes, offering risk-reward opportunities and requiring thoughtful navigation. Dundas Parks hosts local competitions, society events, and junior golf programs, fostering a vibrant club culture.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse offers welcoming hospitality and views over key holes. Dundas Parks exemplifies modern inland Scottish parkland golf: strategic, scenic, and accessible for players of all levels.', ''),
('dundonald', 'Dundonald', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dundonald#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dundonald#/course/1', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.584086, -4.654881, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dundonald', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000004c16f71f999e12c096067e54c3ca4b40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Dundonald Links is a modern masterpiece that feels as though it has been carved out of the Ayrshire coast for centuries. Though a course existed on this site as far back as 1911designed by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Ferniethe layout as it stands today is the work of acclaimed architect Kyle Phillips. Phillips, known for his work at Kingsbarns, was commissioned in 2003 to create a championship-standard links that could hold its own against the historic giants of the region. He succeeded spectacularly, blending rugged undulations with the classic coastal aesthetic.\r\n\r\nThe course has quickly become a heavyweight on the professional circuit. It has hosted the Scottish Open on multiple occasions, most notably in 2017 when Rafa Cabrera-Bello took the title, as well as the Trust Golf Women\'s Scottish Open. Unlike many flat links, Dundonald features significant elevation changes and is framed by pockets of pine trees, giving it a unique visual identity. The resort recently underwent a 25 million upgrade, adding luxury lodges and a world-class clubhouse, ensuring that the off-course experience matches the quality of the pristine, gorse-lined fairways.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/BhXBUG2pqtg?si=OoUhgKbQLoE72dKa'),
('dunechthousegolfclub', 'Dunecht House', 'https://www.dunechthousegolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.dunechthousegolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.161030, -2.413260, 0, 2212, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000aef545425b4e03c062d68ba19c944c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Tucked away in the heart of Aberdeenshire, Dunecht House offers a truly exclusive and intimate golfing experience. This is a private nine-hole parkland gem located within the sprawling estate of Dunecht House, a magnificent 19th-century mansion. Founded in 1920, the club was originally intended for the enjoyment of the estate\'s owners and their guests, and it retains that \"secret garden\" atmosphere to this day. It is a course that rewards precision over power, winding through mature Scottish woodland that provides both shelter and a stern test of accuracy.\r\n\r\nWhile many courses in the region shout for attention, Dunecht House whispers. It is a favorite among locals who appreciate its tranquil setting and the breathtaking views of the Aberdeenshire countryside. The layout has stood the test of time with very few changes, preserving the original vision of a gentleman\'s sporting retreat. Membership remains limited, which means those lucky enough to play here often feel as though they have the entire estate to themselves. It is the quintessential example of traditional Scottish parkland golfunpretentious, naturally beautiful, and deeply rooted in its local history.', ''),
('dunfermline', 'Dunfermline', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunfermline#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunfermline#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.058637, -3.505713, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dunfermline', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000e04be141b30b0cc0f3aace6a81074c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Dunfermline Golf Club, often referred to as Pitfirrane, is steeped in a level of history that few clubs can match. The club was founded in 1887, but it moved to its current home at Pitfirrane Estate in 1953. The centerpiece of the property is the spectacular Pitfirrane Castle, which serves as the clubhouse; parts of this Category A listed building date back to the 15th century. Walking into the 19th hole here feels more like entering a museum than a locker room, providing a sense of gravitas to every round.\r\n\r\nThe 18-hole parkland course was designed by the esteemed J.R. Stutt, a prolific Scottish architect who worked alongside James Braid. Stutt utilized the natural undulations of the Fife landscape to create a testing layout that features no fewer than five par-fives. The signature 18th hole, \"Halkett\'s Hame\" is a grueling 480-yard finish that requires nerves of steel to conclude a round. Notable for its impeccably manicured fairways and fast greens, the course has long been a venue for regional qualifying events and amateur championships, consistently proving that it remains a formidable test for golfers of all skill levels.', ''),
('dunfermlinepitfirrane', 'Dunfermline - Halkett', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunfermline#/course/3', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunfermline#/course/3', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.058637, -3.505713, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dunfermline', 3, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000e04be141b30b0cc0f3aace6a81074c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'While the main 18-hole course draws the crowds, the Halkett Course offers a more intimate and technical experience within the same historic estate. This 9-hole, par-3 executive course is a hidden gem for those looking to sharpen their short game or enjoy a brisk round in the \"Footsteps of Kings.\" Legend has it that King James VI and King Charles I both enjoyed golf on these grounds while staying at nearby Dunfermline Palace, lending the course a regal pedigree that belies its modest 1,074-yard length.\r\n\r\nThe Halkett Course is meticulously maintained to the same high standards as its larger sibling but presents its own set of challenges. Though it lacks sand bunkers, the course is heavily protected by a phalanx of mature, ancient trees that require pinpoint accuracy off the tee. Each hole demands a soft touch and careful club selection, making it a favorite for juniors, beginners, and low-handicappers alike. It serves as a tranquil sanctuary where the modern game meets centuries of Scottish heritage, all under the watchful eye of the imposing Pitfirrane Castle.', ''),
('dunkeldbirnam', 'Dunkeld and Birnam', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunkeldbirnam#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunkeldbirnam#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.570837, -3.569972, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dunkeldbirnam', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f015dd7a4d8f0cc0622cd32f11494c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Highland Perthshire is home to some of the most scenic golf in the world, and Dunkeld and Birnam is arguably its crown jewel. The club\'s origins trace back to 1892, with the original nine holes laid out by the legendary Old Tom Morris. While the course moved to its current hillside location in 1922, the spirit of \"The Grand Old Man of Golf\" still permeates the atmosphere. The official opening of the new site was a grand affair, conducted by Her Grace, The Duchess of Atholl, cementing the club\'s prestigious local standing.\r\n\r\nIn 2000, the course was expanded to 18 holes, with the newer section running alongside the Loch of Lowes. This expansion added a parkland dimension to the original heathland character, creating a fascinating \"game of two halves.\" The elevation changes provide spectacular vistas of the Tay Valley and the historic town of Dunkeld. It is a course where you are just as likely to spot an osprey or a deer as you are to make a birdie. The layout is quirky and charismatic, demanding creative shot-making rather than brute force, making it a must-visit for those who value character in course design.', ''),
('dunnikier', 'Dunnikier', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunnikier#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunnikier#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.139963, -3.163416, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dunnikier', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000024253d0cad4e09c035d3bd4eea114c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dunnikier Park is a delightful parkland course situated on the northern outskirts of Kirkcaldy. Designed by the Paisley-based architect John Stutt and opened in 1963, the course was part of a post-war movement to provide high-quality golf to the local community. Stutt\'s design philosophy is evident here: he used the natural contours of the parkland to create a fair but demanding test. The course is famously well-wooded, with mature trees lining almost every fairway, requiring players to be strategic with their off-the-tee placement.\r\n\r\nOver the years, Dunnikier has built a reputation for its friendly, inclusive atmosphere. While it hasn\'t hosted the major professional opens of its coastal neighbors, it is a frequent host of Fife Golf Association events and has nurtured many talented local amateurs. The layout is particularly known for its challenging finish, where the final few holes can easily ruin a good scorecard. It offers a peaceful escape from the nearby town, providing a lush, green sanctuary that feels far removed from the bustle of modern life. It is the kind of course that rewards the \"thinking golfer\" who knows when to take a risk and when to play safe.', ''),
('Dunning', 'Dunning', 'https://www.dunninggolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.313464, -3.590110, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000002a5778978bb80cc0973c9e961f284c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The village of Dunning is home to a quintessential nine-hole course that captures the heart of Scottish village golf. Established in 1906, the course is located in the shadow of the historic St. Serf\'s Church, where the 12th-century tower looms over the fairways. The layout was designed by the prolific Tom Dunn, an architect who was instrumental in the spread of golf across the UK in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Dunn\'s signature stylefunctional, natural, and accessibleis perfectly preserved in this scenic Perthshire valley.\r\n\r\nDunning is unique because it features two burns (the Dunning Burn and the Dewar Burn) that meander through the property, coming into play on several holes. Despite being a nine-hole layout, the club offers 18 separate tee positions, allowing for a varied second loop. It is a course that emphasizes the \"short game\" with small, tricky greens that require a deft touch. Famous for its warm hospitality, the club is a favorite for those touring the Gleneagles area who want a quick, charming round that highlights the beauty of the Ochil Hills without the championship price tag.', ''),
('duns', 'Duns', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/duns#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/duns#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 56.387868, -3.457551, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'duns', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000004b04aa7f10a90bc01c959ba8a5314c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Set in the rolling hills of the Scottish Borders, Duns Golf Club is a hidden gem that offers a peaceful, panoramic golfing experience. The club was founded in 1894, but the course was redesigned and extended to its current 18-hole layout in the 1920s by the legendary James Braid. Braid\'s influence is unmistakable, particularly in the way the course utilizes the natural slopes of Hardens Hill to create challenging lies and strategic bunkering. The elevation provides views that on a clear day stretch across the Merse to the Cheviot Hills in England.\r\n\r\nDuns is often described as a \"course of two halves.\" The lower holes are relatively flat and parkland in nature, while the upper holes transition into a more rugged, moorland environment. This variety keeps the golfer engaged from start to finish. One of the club\'s most famous honorary members was the legendary Formula 1 champion Jim Clark, who hailed from the area. The club maintains a memorial to him, and the sense of local pride is palpable. It is a welcoming, traditional club that provides a rigorous but fair test of golf in one of Scotland\'s most underrated regions.', '');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('Durness', 'Durness', 'https://www.durnessgolfclub.org/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 58.576366, -4.772935, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002cbccb457c1713c05f43705cc6494d40, 'links', 'No', 'Durness Golf Club is widely regarded as one of the most bucket-list-worthy nine-hole courses in the world. Located in the far northwest Highlands, it is the most north-westerly course on the British mainland. It was remarkably designed and built in 1988 by three local enthusiasts-Lachie Ross, Ian Morrison, and Francis Keith-who saw the potential in the stunning limestone machair land. The result is a course that looks like it was designed by nature itself, with dramatic cliff-top views of Balnakeil Bay and the North Atlantic Ocean.\r\n\r\nThe signature 9th hole (or 18th, if playing twice) is a heart-stopping par-three that requires a shot across a yawning Atlantic chasm to a green perched on the cliffs. It is frequently cited as one of the most extraordinary holes in golf. While it lacks the \"famous architect\" pedigree of other courses, its sheer beauty and isolation have made it a cult favorite among international golf travelers. The course is maintained by a small, dedicated team, and the \"honesty box\" for green fees adds to the feeling of being at the very edge of the world.', ''),
('eastermoffat', 'Easter Moffat', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eastermoffat#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eastermoffat#/course/1', 'No', 'Yes', '', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 55.871143, -3.916913, 0, 0, 'no opens', '', '', 0, '', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000ce37a27bd6550fc0d591239d81ef4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in Lanarkshire, Easter Moffat Golf Club is a grand parkland course with a history dating back to 1922. The club\'s focal point is its stunning clubhousea Grade B listed mansion built in 1838. The transition from the historic elegance of the house to the lush green fairways sets a sophisticated tone for the day. Originally a nine-hole course, it was extended to 18 holes following the Second World War, with the layout evolving over the decades into the polished, championship-style course it is today.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its wide fairways and large, undulating greens, which are often cited as some of the best-conditioned in the county. It sits on a high plateau, offering views across the Monklands and towards the Campsie Fells. While it provides a stern test for the low-handicapper, its fair layout makes it accessible for the casual player as well. Easter Moffat has long been a pillar of the Lanarkshire golf scene, frequently hosting county championships and producing several notable amateur players who have gone on to represent Scotland on the national stage.', ''),
('eastkilbride', 'East Kilbride', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eastkilbride#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eastkilbride#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.783138, -4.156448, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'eastkilbride', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000033198ee733a010c09f20b1dd3de44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'East Kilbride Golf Club represents the modern face of Scottish parkland golf. While the club was founded in 1900, it moved to its current location at Nerston in the late 1960s to accommodate the development of the \"New Town.\" The course was designed by the well-known architect Fred Hawtree, whose family firm is one of the oldest in the business. Hawtree\'s design at East Kilbride is a masterclass in modern parkland architecture, featuring strategic bunkering, water hazards, and a variety of tree species that have now matured to provide a true sense of enclosure.\r\n\r\nOne of the club\'s most famous former members was Jack McLean, a three-time Scottish Amateur Champion in the 1930s who also reached the final of the US Amateur. His legacy continues to inspire the competitive spirit of the club today. The course is a frequent host of West of Scotland PGA events and is renowned for its excellent drainage, meaning it remains playable when other nearby courses are struggling with the Scottish weather. With a sleek, modern clubhouse opened in 2011, it remains one of the most popular and professional clubs in the central belt.', ''),
('eastrenfrewshire', 'East Renfrewshire', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eastrenfrewshire#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eastrenfrewshire#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 55.755356, -4.367871, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'eastrenfrewshire', 1, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000005796e82cb37811c02f6b6281afe04b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'High on the moors above the village of Newton Mearns sits East Renfrewshire Golf Club, a course that breathes with the legacy of the \"Great Triumvirate.\" Established in 1922, the layout was designed by the five-time Open Champion James Braid. Braid was a master of using natural hazards, and here he utilized the rugged moorland terrain, rocky outcrops, and sweeping elevation changes to create a course that feels far more remote than its proximity to Glasgow suggests. On a clear day, the views from the highest points of the course stretch across the Clyde Valley to the peaks of Ben Lomond and the Southern Highlands.\r\n\r\nThe club has a rich history of hosting prestigious events, including the Scottish Professional Championship and the Scottish Youths\' Championship. Its most famous \"member\" in spirit is arguably Braid himself, as the course remains one of the purest examples of his design philosophy in the West of Scotland. The holes are characterized by their strategic demand; Braid\'s bunkering forces players to choose between the aggressive line and the safe play. With its lush, springy turf and challenging wind conditions, it offers a stern but fair test that has remained largely unchanged for over a century.', ''),
('edzell', 'Edzell', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/edzell#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/edzell#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.799834, -2.661234, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'edzell', 1, 1, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000af06280d354a05c04b1de4f560664c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Edzell Golf Club is often described as one of the most aesthetically pleasing inland courses in Scotland. Situated at the gateway to the Grampian Mountains, the course was originally laid out in 1895 by Bob Simpson, the legendary clubmaker from Elie. However, it was a redesign in the 1930s by James Braid that truly elevated Edzell to its current status. The \"Old Course\" is a sophisticated blend of parkland and heathland, framed by majestic Scots pines and silver birches that provide a vibrant backdrop through the changing seasons.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its immaculate conditioning and its historic \"Arch\" which marks the entrance to the village and the club. One of the most notable tournaments held here was the Scottish Girls\' Championship, reflecting the club\'s long-standing commitment to nurturing young talent. The layout is renowned for its consistency, with greens that are famously true and fast. It is a course that requires precision rather than power, particularly on the stretch of holes that run alongside the West Water river, where the margin for error is slim but the rewards for a well-placed drive are immense.', ''),
('edzell9', 'Edzell - West Water', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/edzell9#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.805762, -2.653815, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'edzell9', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000ec12d55b033b05c0062e8f3523674c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'While the Old Course at Edzell takes much of the spotlight, the West Water course is a vital and distinct part of the club\'s identity. Opened in 2001, this 9-hole layout was designed by Graeme Webster, one of Scotland\'s most respected modern architects. Webster\'s task was to create a course that complemented the historic Old Course while offering a different kind of challenge. The West Water is shorter and perhaps more \"player-friendly\" for high handicappers, but it is by no means a pushover, featuring modern bunkering and undulating greens that require a sharp short game.\r\n\r\nThe course takes its name from the river that borders the property, and the sound of rushing water provides a serene soundtrack to the round. It is an ideal venue for those looking for a quicker game or for members wishing to sharpen their iron play before tackling the longer 18-hole layout. Despite its relatively young age, the West Water has matured quickly, with the planting of thousands of native trees helping it blend seamlessly into the ancient landscape of the Angus glens. It represents the club\'s forward-thinking approach, ensuring that golf at Edzell remains accessible and varied for all generations.', ''),
('elderslie', 'Elderslie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/elderslie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/elderslie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 55.833948, -4.472302, 0, 0, 'no data', '', '', 0, 'elderslie', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000007157af22a3e311c04548ddcebeea4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Elderslie Golf Club, located just outside Paisley, holds a unique place in golfing history as the home club of James Braid during the time he was designing some of his most famous layouts. Although Braid didn\'t design the original course (which was laid out by the club\'s first professional), he lived nearby and frequently offered his expertise on improvements. The course as it stands today is a lush, rolling parkland paradise that provides a surprisingly quiet escape from the industrial heartlands of Renfrewshire.\r\n\r\nThe club is perhaps most famous for the Elderslie Trophy, a prestigious amateur event that has seen many future professionals compete over its challenging 6,100 yards. The terrain is characterized by \"whins\" (gorse) and mature woodland, with several blind shots that require local knowledgeor at least a very trusty yardage book. The 6th hole, \"The Monument\" is a highlight, offering views of the Wallace Monument in nearby Elderslie, the birthplace of Scottish hero William Wallace. It is a friendly, traditional club that prides itself on a warm \"19th hole\" welcome and a course that is always presented in championship condition.', ''),
('elgin', 'Elgin', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/elgin#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/elgin#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.627887, -3.315695, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'elgin', 1, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000f415a4198b860ac0b24ae9995ed04c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Elgin Golf Club is widely considered the finest inland course in the north of Scotland. Located in the heart of \"Whisky Country\" the club moved to its current site at Hardhillock in 1906. The course was originally designed by Peter McArthur, but like many of the greats, it saw significant refinement by James Braid. It is a classic heathland layout, sitting on a bed of free-draining sandy soil that allows for firm, fast playing conditions year-round. The fairways are lined with thick gorse and heather, making a straight drive an absolute necessity.\r\n\r\nElgin has a long history of hosting top-tier amateur events, including the Northern Open and various Scottish Golf national championships. The club has produced a number of high-profile players, and the level of local competition is notoriously high. The signature par-three 5th hole, played over a valley to a plateau green, is one of the most photographed in Moray. After a round, many golfers take advantage of the club\'s proximity to some of Scotland\'s most famous distilleries, making Elgin a central pillar of any Highland golf tour that values tradition and a high-quality test of skill.', ''),
('elie', 'Elie', 'https://elie.intelligentgolf.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.190112, -2.836491, 0, 0, '', 'https://elie.intelligentgolf.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000cb2f833122b106c0e0490b9755184c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'To play Elie is to step back in time. Formally known as The Golf House Club, golf has been played on this stunning piece of Fife coastline since the 16th century. The course reached its current 18-hole form in 1895 with the help of Old Tom Morris and James Braid, the latter of whom was born in the adjacent village of Earlsferry. Elie is unique among world-class courses because it has no par-fives and only two par-threes; however, its collection of long, testing par-fours, many of which are played over blind ridges, makes it a formidable challenge.\r\n\r\nThe most famous feature of Elie is the submarine periscope located in the starter\'s hut. Because the opening tee shot is played over a hill, the starter uses the periscope (salvaged from HMS Excalibur) to ensure the fairway is clear. Famous members include Braid himself and the legendary Sir Michael Bonallack, one of the most decorated amateurs in history. The course is a pure links, with firm turf, hidden pot bunkers, and the ever-present wind from the Firth of Forth. It is a \"member\'s club\" in the truest sense, exuding an air of understated elegance and historical significance that few places can match.', ''),
('eliesportsclub', 'Elie Sports Club', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/elie#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.191463, -2.827599, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'elie', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000529e7939ec9e06c070b20ddc81184c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located just inland from the famous links of the Golf House Club, the Elie Sports Club (formerly the Elie Relief Course) offers a more relaxed, community-focused golfing experience. This 9-hole course is the perfect antidote to the high-pressure environment of championship links golf. It was designed to provide a space for beginners, juniors, and families to enjoy the game in the same coastal air as its more famous neighbor but without the intimidating length or the periscope-guarded blind shots.\r\n\r\nThe Sports Club is part of a larger facility that includes tennis and bowling, making it a hub of activity in the East Neuk of Fife. Despite its shorter length, the course is beautifully maintained and features many of the same links characteristicssandy soil and coastal breezesthat define Fife golf. It is a particularly popular spot for \"warm-up\" rounds or for golfers who want to enjoy a morning game before a afternoon of sightseeing in the historic fishing villages nearby. It serves as a vital nursery for the next generation of Scottish golfers, maintaining the inclusive spirit that has kept the game alive in Fife for centuries.', ''),
('elmwood', 'Elmwood', 'https://www.elmwoodgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.elmwoodgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 56.298290, -3.049250, 0, 2571, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000be9f1a2fdd6408c0a75ce15d2e264c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Elmwood Golf, situated near Cupar in Fife, is a fascinating modern addition to the Scottish golf scene. Opened in the mid-1990s, it was designed by Graeme Webster and serves a dual purpose: it is both a popular public pay-and-play course and a key training facility for SRUC (Scotland\'s Rural College). Because it is used to train the next generation of greenkeepers and golf managers, the course is often in \"textbook\" condition, serving as a living classroom for sustainable turf management and modern course design.\r\n\r\nThe layout is a modern parkland-style course that makes clever use of environmentally friendly features, such as wildflower meadows and wetlands, which provide a rich habitat for local wildlife. It is not an overly long course, but the bunkering is strategic, and the greens are known for being remarkably smooth and receptive. Elmwood has hosted various PGA pro-ams and regional qualifying events, earning a reputation as a high-quality facility that punches well above its weight. It is perhaps the best place in Fife to see the future of the Scottish golf industry in action while enjoying a fun, accessible round of golf.', ''),
('eriska', 'Isle of Eriska', 'https://www.eriska-hotel.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 56.532936, -5.412279, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000724f57772ca615c0376e313f37444c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Isle of Eriska offers what is arguably the most exclusive and picturesque short-course experience in the British Isles. Located on a private 300-acre island off the west coast of Scotland near Oban, the 9-hole course is part of the world-renowned Isle of Eriska Hotel and Spa. The course was designed by Howard Swan and is intended to provide a luxury recreational experience for guests of the estate. It is a \"hidden\" course in the most literal sense, accessible only by a private bridge that connects the island to the mainland.\r\n\r\nThe holes wind through ancient woodland and along the rugged shoreline, offering views of Loch Linnhe and the Morvern mountains that are nothing short of cinematic. While it is a shorter course, the island\'s terrain provides natural defenses, with rocky outcrops and the sea breeze adding to the difficulty. It is a favorite haunt of celebrities and high-profile guests seeking total privacy. Playing here is less about the scorecard and more about the atmospherethe scent of wild garlic in the air, the sight of golden eagles overhead, and the absolute silence that comes with playing on your own private island.', ''),
('erskine', 'Erskine', 'https://erskine.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://erskine.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.921585, -4.488157, 0, 0, '', '', 'erskine', 392, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000ff40b96ddff311c0f9bd4d7ff6f54b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Erskine Golf Club is a powerhouse of West of Scotland golf, located on the banks of the River Clyde with views across to the Kilpatrick Hills. Founded in 1904, the course was redesigned in the late 1920s by the legendary duo of James Braid and Willie Gaudin. The result is a premier parkland course that blends traditional design with the scale and drama of the Clyde estuary. The course is famously divided by the Bishopton-to-Erskine road, with the holes on either side offering slightly different charactersone more wooded and sheltered, the other more open to the elements.\r\n\r\nThe club has a storied history of hosting major championships, including the Scottish Professional Championship and the British Seniors\' Championship. Its quality is such that it has long been used as a final qualifying venue for the Open Championship when it is held at nearby Royal Troon or Prestwick. Famous members have included several titans of Scottish industry, and the club maintains a high standard of etiquette and tradition. With its massive mature trees, deep bunkers, and slick greens, Erskine remains one of the most respected and physically demanding parkland tests in the country.', ''),
('eyemouth', 'Eyemouth', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eyemouth#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eyemouth#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 55.867214, -2.079868, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'eyemouth', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000b5f97fd591a300c011514cde00ef4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Eyemouth Golf Club offers a heart-pounding experience on the Berwickshire coast that rivals the most famous cliff-top courses in the world. Originally a 9-hole course founded in 1894, it was extended to 18 holes in 1997 by architect William Swan. The modern layout is a spectacular hybrid of rolling parkland and \"extreme\" coastal golf. It is most famous for its 6th hole, \"A\' v weel\" which was once voted Britain\'s most extraordinary golf hole. This par-three requires a daunting 160-plus yard carry over a deep, churning Atlantic inlet known as \"Gull\'s Nest\" to a green perched on a jagged promontory.\r\n\r\nThe course is a regular host of the Scottish Borders Open and is a favorite for visitors seeking a visual spectacle. Beyond the terrifying carries over the sea, the course offers panoramic views that stretch toward the Bass Rock in the north and Holy Island in the south. The wind is the primary defender here; on a calm day, the course is a delight of manicured turf, but when the North Sea gales blow, it becomes a survival test. It is a bold, modern links-style experience that emphasizes the raw, rugged beauty of Scotland\'s eastern coastline.', ''),
('fairmontKittocks', 'Fairmont - Kittocks', 'https://www.fairmont.com/en/hotels/st-andrews/fairmont-st-andrews/golf.html', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.320903, -2.730651, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000004c512e8d5fd805c01a18795913294c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'The Kittocks course at the Fairmont St Andrews resort is a sprawling, modern masterpiece that commands the clifftops just outside the \"Home of Golf.\" Originally a collaboration between Bruce Devlin and the legendary Gene Sarazen, the course was later refined by Gary Stephenson. It is named after the Kittocks Den, a natural ravine that meanders through the property. The design is American in scalefeaturing large, undulating greens and expansive bunkersbut Scottish in soul, with fescue grasses and breathtaking views of the St Andrews skyline and the Eden Estuary.\r\n\r\nKittocks has hosted several prestigious events, including the Scottish Senior Open and EuroPro Tour events. One of its most famous features is the double green shared by the 14th and 17th holes, a nod to the historic Old Course nearby. The closing stretch is particularly dramatic, with the 17th hole running precariously along the very edge of the cliffs. It offers a more rugged, \"wilder\" feel than its sister course, the Torrance, and provides a stern test of ball-striking, especially when the wind whips off the North Sea.', ''),
('fairmonttorrance', 'Fairmont - Torrance', 'https://www.fairmont.com/en/hotels/st-andrews/fairmont-st-andrews/golf.html', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.320903, -2.730651, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000004c512e8d5fd805c01a18795913294c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'The Torrance Course, the Kittocks\' sister at the Fairmont resort, was originally designed by the late, great Ryder Cup legend Sam Torrance. It was later extensively remodeled by Gary Stephenson to give it a more traditional Scottish links character. Torrance\'s vision was to create a walking-friendly course that felt like a classic links despite its clifftop location. This was achieved by adding revetted bunkering and undulating fairways that encourage the \"ground game\" so vital to Scottish golf.\r\n\r\nThe Torrance has a high-profile tournament pedigree, having served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship and hosting the DP World Tour\'s Hero Open. It is a challenging par-72 that demands strategic thinking; Sam Torrance himself was known as a master tactician, and his course reflects that, with subtle risks and rewards built into every hole. With the iconic Fairmont hotel looming in the background and the sea stretching out to the horizon, it offers a luxury golfing experience that blends modern amenities with the timeless challenge of coastal golf.', ''),
('falkirk', 'Falkirk', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/falkirk#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/falkirk#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.010231, -3.826269, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'falkirk', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000c896e5eb329c0ec0e333d93f4f014c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Known locally as \"Carmuirs\" Falkirk Golf Club is one of the premier parkland venues in Central Scotland. Founded in 1922, the course was laid out by the prolific James Braid, whose influence is evident in the clever use of the natural landscape and the strategic bunkering that protects the greens. The course is characterized by its lush, mature woodland and remarkably consistent playing surfaces. It serves as a green oasis in an area otherwise known for its industrial heritage, providing a peaceful and highly scenic round of golf.\r\n\r\nThe club has long been a hub for competitive amateur golf, frequently hosting the Stirlingshire County Championships. Its layout is famously fair; there are few \"tricky\" holes, but the length and the tightness of the tree-lined fairways require a disciplined approach. The signature 14th hole, a par-three across a valley, is often cited as the most beautiful on the course. Famous for its friendly membership and an active social scene, Falkirk remains a traditional Scottish club that prides itself on maintaining Braid\'s original design principles while providing a modern, high-quality experience for its members and visitors.', ''),
('falkirkantonine', 'Falkirk - Antonine', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.010231, -3.826269, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'falkirk', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000c896e5eb329c0ec0e333d93f4f014c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located on the outskirts of the village of Bonnybridge, the Antonine course (part of the Falkirk Golf Club ecosystem but distinct in character) is steeped in ancient history. The course takes its name from the Antonine Wall, the Roman Empire\'s northernmost frontier, which runs directly through the property. Playing here is as much a history lesson as it is a sporting challenge; several fairways are literally built over the remains of the Roman turf fortifications. This historical significance gives the course a unique atmosphere that few other venues in the world can match.\r\n\r\nThe layout is a hilly, demanding parkland course that provides spectacular views across the Forth Valley to the Ochil Hills. While it may not have the championship length of some neighbors, its defenses lie in its elevation changes and tricky, sloping greens. It is a course that favors the accurate iron player over the long hitter. Because of its unique location, it is a frequent stop for \"golf historians\" who want to walk the same ground as the Roman legions while trying to save par. It is a charming, community-focused club that offers a rugged and memorable Scottish golfing experience.', ''),
('falkirktryst', 'Falkirk Tryst', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/falkirktryst#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/falkirktryst#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.030543, -3.820600, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'falkirktryst', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000e3c798bb96900ec0950f41d5e8034c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Falkirk Tryst Golf Club, located in Larbert, occupies a site of immense historical importance. Long before golf was played here, the land hosted the \"Great Tryst\"the largest cattle fair in Scotlandand was also the site of the Battle of Falkirk (1746). The golf club was established in 1885, making it one of the oldest in the region. The course was originally a 9-hole layout but was expanded to 18 in the early 20th century, with contributions from the legendary James Braid, who refined the bunkering and green complexes to modern standards.\r\n\r\nTryst is a unique \"inland links\" style course, built on sandy, free-draining soil that allows for firm, fast-running fairways even in the depths of winter. This makes it a popular choice for year-round golf. The course has a long-standing association with the PGA and has hosted many regional professional events over the decades. Its most famous member is likely the former Ryder Cup player and successful commentator Ken Brown, who honed his creative game on these very fairways. The layout is relatively flat, making it a pleasant walk, but the strategic placement of Braid\'s bunkers ensures that a good score is never easily earned.', ''),
('falkland', 'Falkland', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/falkland#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.255178, -3.201499, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'falkland', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000e469f981ab9c09c0505436aca9204c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Falkland Golf Club is a delightful 9-hole parkland course situated in the shadow of the historic Falkland Palace, the former country residence of the Stuart monarchs. Founded in 1902, the course is a classic example of a \"village\" clubunpretentious, welcoming, and deeply integrated into the local community. The layout was designed by the members themselves, and over the century, it has matured into a scenic and testing little course. The backdrop of the Lomond Hills provides a dramatic and ever-changing landscape for the golfer.\r\n\r\nWhile it lacks the \"famous architect\" branding, Falkland makes up for it with sheer charm and tricky, small greens. The course is known for being remarkably well-kept by a dedicated team of locals. It is a favorite for those who enjoy the \"short game\" as the yardage is modest but the margin for error around the greens is slim. Many visitors combine a round here with a trip to the nearby Palace, making it a perfect day out for those who love Scottish history as much as they love the game of golf. It is the quintessential Fife hidden gem.', ''),
('fereneze', 'Fereneze', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/fereneze#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/fereneze#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.805533, -4.414612, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'fereneze', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000da1d520c90a811c0a46c91b41be74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Perched high on the hills overlooking Barrhead, Fereneze Golf Club offers some of the most spectacular panoramic views in the West of Scotland. On a clear day, golfers can see as far as the Arran hills, Ben Lomond, and the city of Glasgow shimmering in the distance. The club was founded in 1904, and the course is a rugged, moorland layout that tests both your stamina and your shot-making. The terrain is undulating and natural, with gorse, heather, and rocky outcrops providing the main hazards.\r\n\r\nThe course was designed by Willie Fernie, the 1883 Open Champion, who specialized in creating layouts that worked with the natural \"lie of the land.\" Fereneze is famous for its steep inclinesthere are several holes where you\'ll need your \"mountain legs\"but the reward is the exhilaration of hitting shots from elevated tees into the valley below. The club has a reputation for producing tough, resilient golfers and has hosted various Renfrewshire county events. It is a course that doesn\'t rely on artificial features; instead, it uses the raw, windswept beauty of the Scottish moors to provide a timeless challenge.', ''),
('forbesofkingennie', 'Forbes of Kingennie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/forbesofkingennie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/forbesofkingennie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.514634, -2.846959, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'forbesofkingennie', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000446cb07092c606c070b4e386df414c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Forbes of Kingennie, located near Dundee, is a modern 9-hole course that feels more like a private estate retreat than a traditional golf club. Opened in 2007, it was designed by Ian Rae as part of a luxury resort that includes fishing lochs and holiday lodges. The design is unique, featuring \"USGA-spec\" greens that are exceptionally large and undulating, providing a level of green-side challenge rarely found on 9-hole courses. It is a highly visual course, with water hazards and manicured bunkers that wouldn\'t look out of place on a professional tour.\r\n\r\nThe resort has gained fame beyond golf, partly due to its owner, Mike Forbes, a well-known local entrepreneur. The course has become a popular venue for the Scottish Hickory Championship, where players use pre-1935 wooden-shafted clubs to tackle the modern layouta fascinating clash of eras. Despite its short length, the course is no pushover; the elevation changes and frequent water features require precise club selection. It is widely regarded as one of the best-conditioned short courses in the country, making it a perfect spot for a high-quality, quick round in a beautiful Angus setting.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/ndkB1kgx4vg?si=JwmFlgDCFNnQQ1oj'),
('forfar', 'Forfar', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/forfar#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/forfar#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.652824, -2.896393, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'forfar', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000019e8da17d02b07c09f05a1bc8f534c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Forfar Golf Club holds a special place in the history of golf architecture: it was the first course in the world to be designed from its inception as an 18-hole layout. Founded in 1871, the course was laid out by the legendary Old Tom Morris. However, the site\'s topography is its most famous featurethe \"rig and furrow\" patterns left by medieval farming are still visible today. These natural ridges create a unique, undulating fairway surface that provides a variety of unpredictable lies, making it a fascinating tactical challenge.\r\n\r\nIn the 1920s, the course was updated by James Braid, who added his signature bunkering to Old Tom\'s original routing. Forfar is a classic heathland course, lined with Scots pine and carpeted in heather. It has hosted many major amateur events, including the Scottish Boys\' Championship. The club is proud of its heritage, and the clubhouse is a treasure trove of early golfing memorabilia. The layout is a stern test of ball-striking, as the narrow fairways and firm, fast greens require both power and finesse. Forfar remains a \"must-play\" for anyone interested in the evolution of golf course design.', ''),
('forres', 'Forres', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/forres#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/forres#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.603161, -3.621988, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'forres', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000001c0934d8d4f90cc0809c306134cd4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Forres Golf Club is a beautifully manicured parkland course that sits on the sunny Moray coast. Originally established in 1889, the course was significantly redesigned by the legendary James Braid and Willie Park Jr., two of the most influential names in the history of the game. The result is a layout that provides a stern but fair challenge, characterized by its narrow, tree-lined fairways and exceptionally smooth greens. The course is famously well-protected from the elements by the surrounding dense woodland, making it a pleasant retreat even when the coastal winds are whipping across the nearby Moray Firth.\r\n\r\nThe club has a rich tournament history, having hosted the Scottish Professional Championship and the Northern Open. One of its most famous members is the former Ryder Cup player Harry Bannerman, who represented Great Britain & Ireland in 1971. The signature hole is the 16th, aptly named \"Pond\" which requires a nerve-wracking approach over water to a well-guarded green. Forres is frequently cited as one of the best-value courses in the north of Scotland, offering a championship-quality experience in a tranquil, hospitable Highland setting.', ''),
('ForresterParkResort', 'Forrester Park Resort', 'https://www.forresterparkresort.com/golf/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.066201, -3.532865, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000de76a1b94e430cc033fb3c4679084c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located near Dunfermline in the Kingdom of Fife, Forrester Park Resort is a modern parkland course that has quickly established itself as a premier destination for both casual and competitive golfers. Opened in 1999, the course was designed by Robert Sandow and is set within 350 acres of rolling countryside. Unlike the ancient links nearby, Forrester Park offers a contemporary challenge with wide, undulating fairways and large, multi-tiered greens that demand a high level of putting skill.\r\n\r\nThe resort is known for its excellent practice facilities and its luxurious clubhouse, making it a popular choice for corporate events and society outings. The layout features several water hazards and strategically placed bunkers that require careful navigation. While it doesn\'t boast the centuries-old history of some of its Fife neighbors, it has become a staple of the local golf scene and is a regular host of the Fife PGA Professional Championship. It is the perfect example of a modern Scottish golf resortaccessible, high-quality, and designed to provide an enjoyable experience for players of all ability levels.', ''),
('FortAugustus', 'Fort Augustus', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.137150, -4.689712, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000090a2cedc43c212c0bd5296218e914c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Fort Augustus Golf Club is arguably the most scenic 9-hole course in the Scottish Highlands. Tucked away at the southern tip of Loch Ness, the course was established in 1924 and was designed by Harry Shapland Coltthe man responsible for masterpieces like Muirfield and Royal Portrush. To have a Colt-designed course in such a remote and beautiful location is a rare treat. The layout is a classic heathland style, featuring thick gorse, heather, and some of the most breathtaking views of the Great Glen you will ever encounter.\r\n\r\nThe course is famously challenging due to its hilly terrain and \"wild\" feel; it isn\'t uncommon to share the fairways with local sheep or deer. Despite its short length, Colt\'s strategic genius is evident in the green placements and the way the natural slopes are used to defend par. It is a traditional \"honesty box\" club that embodies the soul of Highland golf. For any golfer traveling the North Coast 500 or visiting Loch Ness, a stop at Fort Augustus is a mandatory pilgrimage to experience one of the world\'s most famous architects working on a miniature, natural canvas.', ''),
('fortrose', 'Fortrose and Rosemarkie', 'https://www.brsgolf.com/fortrose/visitor_home.php', 'https://www.brsgolf.com/fortrose/visitor_home.php', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.578077, -4.104405, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'fortrose', 1, 0, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000d027f224e96a10c0efc8586dfec94c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Situated on the Chanonry Peninsula, Fortrose and Rosemarkie Golf Club is the 15th oldest club in the world. This is a pure links experience on a narrow strip of land that juts out into the Moray Firth. The course was redesigned in 1932 by James Braid, who made ingenious use of the restricted space to create a layout that feels much larger than it is. The course is surrounded by water on three sides, and the Chanonry Lighthouse serves as a stunning backdrop. It is also one of the best places in the world to spot bottlenose dolphins playing in the surf just yards from the fairways.\r\n\r\nThe club has received numerous accolades, including being named \"Scotland\'s Best Golfing Experience\" in its category. Its most famous member is likely the former British Amateur Champion Alan Affleck. The course is notorious for its small, firm greens and the encroaching gorse that penalizes any wayward shot. The wind is a constant factor here, shifting direction as you loop around the peninsula. It is a rugged, historic, and utterly unique links that provides one of the most memorable rounds of golf in the Highlands.', ''),
('fortwilliam', 'Fort William', 'https://fortwilliam.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://fortwilliam.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'highlands', 'No', 56.801850, -5.134291, 0, 0, 'no data', '', 'fortwilliam', 8299, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000ab967494838914c018265305a3664c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located at the foot of Ben Nevis, Britain\'s highest mountain, Fort William Golf Club offers a playing environment that is quite literally overshadowed by greatness. The course was opened in 1974 and provides a classic Highland parkland experience. The fairways wind through mature trees and over peat moorland, with the massive granite face of the mountain providing a constant, dramatic reference point. Because of its location in the \"Outdoor Capital of the UK\" the course is built to handle the high rainfall of the region, featuring excellent drainage and lush, green turf.\r\n\r\nWhile it is a relatively young club, it has become a central part of the Highland golfing community. The layout is relatively flat, making it an easy walk, but the challenge comes from the various mountain streams that crisscross the course and the unpredictable winds coming off the surrounding peaks. It is a popular spot for tourists who want to combine a morning hike up the mountain with an afternoon round of golf. The hospitality at the 19th hole is legendary, reflecting the warm, welcoming spirit of the Lochaber region.', ''),
('Foulford', 'Foulford', 'https://foulfordinn.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.419848, -3.787054, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000e57cb1f7e24b0ec040a54a94bd354c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Foulford, located near Cowdenbeath in Fife, is a charming and somewhat eccentric 9-hole course that offers a glimpse into the industrial-meets-rural history of the region. While it may not have the pedigree of the \"Open\" venues nearby, Foulford is a beloved local institution known for its quirky layout and undulating greens. It is a parkland course that requires a \"target golf\" approach, as the small greens are often tucked away behind natural hillocks or protected by mature trees.\r\n\r\nThe course is a testament to the passion of local golfers who have maintained it for generations. It offers a relaxed, unpretentious atmosphere where the focus is firmly on the fun of the game. It is particularly well-suited for beginners or those looking for a quick, low-stress round. What it lacks in championship length, it makes up for in character; every hole feels unique, and the rolling Fife countryside provides a pleasant, pastoral backdrop. It is the kind of course where you can focus on your game without the pressure of a crowded tee sheet, making it a true community gem.', ''),
('fraserburgh', 'Fraseburgh - Corbiehill', 'https://fraserburghgolfclub.org/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://fraserburghgolfclub.org/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.677330, -1.994960, 2060, 2262, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe6100000010100000025404d2d5bebffbfc24cdbbfb2d64c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Fraserburgh Golf Club is the 7th oldest club in the world and the oldest in the North East of Scotland. The Corbiehill course is a high-octane links experience that was redesigned by James Braid in 1922. It is a \"raw\" links, meaning the land hasn\'t been overly manicured, preserving the massive sand dunes and natural hollows that make Scottish coastal golf so famous. The course features significant elevation changes, with many tees perched high atop dunes, offering views across the North Sea toward Norway.\r\n\r\nThe club has hosted numerous prestigious events, including the Scottish Area Team Championships. Despite its incredible history and architectural pedigree, Fraserburgh remains one of the most underrated links in Scotland. It is often described as \"Braid\'s best-kept secret.\" The layout is punishing for those who can\'t control their ball flight in the wind, but it is immensely rewarding for those who enjoy creative shot-making. With its towering dunes and classic pot bunkers, Corbiehill is a masterclass in traditional links design that every serious golfer should experience at least once.', ''),
('fraserburghrosehill', 'Fraserburgh - Rosehill', 'https://fraserburghgolfclub.org/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.677330, -1.994960, 2061, 2262, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000025404d2d5bebffbfc24cdbbfb2d64c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Rosehill course at Fraserburgh serves as the perfect companion to its older, more intimidating brother, Corbiehill. This 9-hole layout offers a gentler introduction to links golf, making it an ideal spot for juniors, seniors, and those looking for a more casual round. While it lacks the massive dunes of Corbiehill, it still possesses the firm, sandy turf and coastal breezes that define the region. It is beautifully maintained to the same high standards as the main course, ensuring a quality playing surface year-round.\r\n\r\nRosehill is often used by members as a \"warm-up\" or for a quick evening game when time is short. The layout is relatively flat and easy to walk, but the small, well-protected greens still require a deft touch. It is a vital part of the club\'s identity, helping to foster a welcoming and inclusive environment for all ages. Playing Rosehill allows you to soak in the historic atmosphere of one of the world\'s oldest golf clubs without the physical and mental demands of the championship layout, making it a delightful addition to any visit to the Buchan coast.', ''),
('Gairloch', 'Gairloch', 'https://gairlochgolfclub.co.uk/index.html#', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.716994, -5.683642, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000029b000a60cbc16c0d0b69a75c6db4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Gairloch Golf Club is a stunning 9-hole course located on the edge of a white sandy beach in the Northwest Highlands. Established in 1898, the course offers some of the most beautiful views in the world, stretching across the Minch to the Isle of Skye and the Outer Hebrides. The layout is a hybrid of links and heathland, with the salt-spray from the Atlantic often reaching the fairways. It is a natural course in every sense of the word, with the routing dictated by the rugged coastal terrain.\r\n\r\nThe club is a community-run gem, and the sense of local pride is evident in the warm welcome every visitor receives. The 9th hole is a standout, requiring a shot over the corner of the beach to reach the green. While it hasn\'t hosted major professional tournaments, it is a favorite for \"golf adventurers\" seeking the most remote and scenic courses in Scotland. It is a place where time slows down, and the only distractions are the sound of the waves and the occasional sighting of a sea eagle. Gairloch is the epitome of the \"hidden Highland gem.\"', ''),
('galashiels', 'Galashiels', 'https://www.galashielsgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.621111, -2.803650, 0, 2264, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000076711b0de06d06c0ca17b49080cf4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Galashiels Golf Club, known locally as \"Ladhope\" is a classic Scottish Borders hill course. Founded in 1884, the layout was refined by the great James Braid, who was a master at utilizing steep terrain to create interesting golfing challenges. The course is built on the side of a hill, meaning you will rarely have a flat lie, and your \"mountain legs\" will definitely be tested. The reward for the climb is a set of panoramic views over the town of Galashiels and the surrounding Eildon Hills that are nothing short of spectacular.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its lush fairways and tricky, sloping greens that require a lot of local knowledge to read correctly. Galashiels has produced many fine amateur players over the years and remains a competitive hub in the Borders golf scene. The 5th hole, \"The Pulpit\" is a famous test, requiring a precise drive from a high elevated tee. It is a traditional, friendly club that prides itself on being a \"true test of golf and fitness.\" For those who enjoy the rugged beauty of the Borders and the challenge of moorland golf, Galashiels is an essential stop.', ''),
('gandkgc', 'Garmouth and Kingston', 'https://gandkgc.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://gandkgc.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.666845, -3.102549, 0, 0, '', '', 'gandkgc', 2312, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000068e6c93505d208c025404d2d5bd54c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Garmouth and Kingston Golf Club is a fascinating coastal course situated where the River Spey meets the Moray Firth. Originally a 9-hole course founded in 1923, it was extended to a full 18 holes by the legendary James Braid in the 1930s. Braid\'s ability to work with natural terrain is on full display here; the course is built on a series of raised beaches and shingle banks, providing a firm, fast-playing surface that is quintessentially Scottish. The proximity to the river means that the local topography is constantly shifting, giving the course a raw, organic feel.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its challenging wind conditions and small, tricky greens. While it may not have the international fame of nearby Lossiemouth, it is a favorite for those who appreciate traditional, unpretentious golf. The club has a strong local following and is often used for Moray County events. One of the highlights of a round here is the wildlife; the area is a haven for ospreys and seals. It is a peaceful, scenic layout that offers a genuine links-style challenge without the crowds, making it one of the best-kept secrets on the Moray coast.', '');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('GatehouseofFleet', 'Gatehouse of Fleet', 'https://www.gatehousegolfclub.com/website/index.php', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'south', '', 54.889370, -4.181159, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000001781b1be81b910c092054ce0d6714b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in the breathtaking Galloway Forest Park, Gatehouse of Fleet is a 9-hole parkland course that defines \"hidden gem.\" Established in 1921, the course was laid out on the hills overlooking the Fleet estuary, offering views that stretch toward the Isle of Man on a clear day. The layout is natural and rugged, featuring stone dykes, gorse, and significant elevation changes. It is a course that doesn\'t rely on manicured perfection; instead, it embraces the wild beauty of the Dumfries and Galloway countryside.\r\n\r\nThe club is a community-run facility that prides itself on its accessibility and friendliness. While it doesn\'t boast a celebrity architect, the routing is clever, making excellent use of the sloping terrain to create holes that play much longer than their yardage. The small clubhouse is the heart of the village\'s sporting life, and the \"honesty box\" system for visitors adds to the traditional charm. It is the perfect spot for a quiet, contemplative round of golf, where the only sound is the wind through the trees and the distant bleating of sheep.', ''),
('giffordgc', 'Gifford', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/giffordgc#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/giffordgc#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.895914, -2.760667, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'giffordgc', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000e52b8194d81506c0a703594fadf24b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Gifford Golf Club is widely regarded as one of the best 9-hole courses in the UK. Located in the heart of East Lothianthe \"Cradle of Golf\"it was founded in 1904 and designed by the local professional Tom Anderson. Gifford offers a parkland experience that rivals the quality of the famous links nearby. The course is characterized by its lush, manicured fairways and exceptionally fast, true greens. It feels more like a private estate than a public course, with mature trees and the Lammermuir Hills providing a stunning backdrop.\r\n\r\nThe club has a reputation for being a \"golfer\'s golf club\" focusing on the quality of the playing surface above all else. Famous members of the local community have long frequented these fairways, and the club maintains a high standard of etiquette. Despite having only nine holes, the separate tee positions for the second loop provide a fresh perspective on every hole. Gifford is often used as a \"breather\" for golfers tackling the grueling links of Muirfield and North Berwick, offering a tranquil and refined alternative that still demands precise shot-making.', ''),
('girvan', 'Girvan', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/gsacarrick#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.247314, -4.858642, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'gsacarrick', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000005ce333d93f6f13c0e6eb32fca79f4b40, 'links', 'No', 'Girvan Golf Club is a unique hybrid course that provides two distinct golfing experiences in one round. The front nine is a pure links, running alongside the Firth of Clyde with spectacular views of Ailsa Craig, while the back nine moves inland to a lush parkland setting. The course was originally designed by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie, and his influence remains in the strategic layout of the coastal holes. The \"links half\" is exposed to the elements, requiring low-trajectory shots to navigate the sea breeze.\r\n\r\nGirvan has a strong connection to the professional game through its proximity to Turnberry. It has often been used as a practice ground for professionals visiting the region. The course is famously compact, meaning that accuracy is far more important than power. The transition from the sandy, wind-swept turf of the first nine to the sheltered, tree-lined fairways of the second is a fascinating tactical challenge. It is a friendly, municipal-run course that offers championship-standard views and a varied test of golf at a fraction of the cost of its more famous neighbors.', ''),
('glasgow', 'Glasgow Gailes', 'https://www.brsgolf.com/glasgow/visitor_home.php', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.596021, -4.664101, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'glasgow', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000adf6b0170aa812c0575d876a4acc4b40, 'links', 'No', 'Glasgow Gailes is a titan of Scottish golf. Owned by Glasgow Golf Club (the 9th oldest in the world), this pure links course was redesigned by Willie Park Jr. in 1912. It is a classic \"out and back\" layout, characterized by its thick heather, gorse, and deep pot bunkers. Gailes is a perennial Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship, a testament to its difficulty and quality. It has also hosted the Scottish Amateur Championship and the Palmer Cup, making it a bucket-list destination for any serious student of the game.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its conditioning; even in the depths of winter, the fairways are firm and the greens are lightning-fast. Famous members over the years have included many of Scotland\'s leading industrialists and champion amateurs. Unlike many links that are flat, Gailes features subtle undulations that can kick a slightly off-center drive into the punishing heather. The clubhouse is a masterclass in Edwardian elegance, offering a refined atmosphere that reflects the club\'s prestigious status. It is a pure, uncompromising test of golf that requires every club in the bag.', ''),
('gleddoch', 'Gleddoch', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/gleddoch#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.918614, -4.584087, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'gleddoch', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000034130ce71a5612c0e9d2bf2495f54b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Gleddoch Golf Club offers a modern, high-elevation parkland experience on the hills overlooking the River Clyde. The course was designed in the 1970s as part of the Gleddoch House Hotel estate, which was formerly the home of the shipping magnate Sir William Lithgow. Because of its hilltop location, the course offers some of the most expansive views in Renfrewshire, stretching toward the Erskine Bridge and the mountains of the Trossachs. It is a physically demanding course, with significant climbs and dramatic drops that make for an exhilarating round.\r\n\r\nThe layout is known for its \"resort\" style, with wide fairways and large greens, but the elevation changes and frequent wind make it a tough scoring test. Gleddoch has hosted several PGA regional events and is a popular choice for corporate golf days. The signature hole is the par-four 17th, where the tee is perched high above the fairway, requiring a drive that seems to stay in the air forever. Following a major renovation of the hotel and spa, Gleddoch has become one of the premier stay-and-play destinations in the West of Scotland, offering luxury and spectacular scenery in equal measure.', ''),
('glenbervie', 'Glenbervie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/glenbervie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/glenbervie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.039249, -3.850306, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'glenbervie', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000098bd6c3b6dcd0ec04ab3791c06054c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Glenbervie Golf Club is widely considered one of the finest parkland courses in the country. Located near Larbert, the course was designed by the legendary James Braid and opened in 1932. Braid\'s routing through the mature pine and larch forests is masterful, creating a sense of total isolation on almost every hole. The course is famously long and testing, with a \"championship\" feel that has made it a regular host of the Scottish Professional Championship and the Girls\' Home Internationals.\r\n\r\nOne of the club\'s most famous associations is with the legendary John Panton, one of Scotland\'s greatest-ever professional golfers, who served as the club\'s honorary president. The course is known for its exceptional greens, which are often cited as the truest in the region. The layout requires strategic placement off the tee to navigate the tree-lined corridors, and the bunkering is classic Braiddeep and unforgiving. Glenbervie is a \"pure\" golf club with a focused, competitive membership, offering a polished and professional experience for anyone looking to test their game on a top-tier inland layout.', ''),
('glencorse', 'Glencorse', 'https://glencorsegolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.849702, -3.200246, 0, 2280, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000103d29931a9a09c043acfe08c3ec4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Glencorse Golf Club, located in Milton Bridge near Edinburgh, is a charming and historic course that punches far above its weight. Founded in 1890, the layout was refined by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie. While it is a relatively short course by modern standards (a par-68), it is famously difficult to play to your handicap. The course is defined by the Glencorse Burn, which meanders through the property and comes into play on no fewer than ten holes, requiring constant vigilance and precise club selection.\r\n\r\nThe club\'s most famous member was the 19th-century author Robert Louis Stevenson, who spent much of his childhood in the area and is said to have enjoyed the tranquility of the Glencorse valley. The course is a lush, parkland oasis with small, undulating greens that require a deft touch. It is a frequent host of the Lothians Champion of Champions tournament. Glencorse is proof that a course doesn\'t need 7,000 yards to be a great test; its defense lies in its clever routing and the ever-present threat of the water, making it a favorite for those who value strategy over power.', ''),
('glencruitten', 'Glencruitten', 'https://www.golfoban.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.golfoban.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 56.413600, -5.450760, 0, 2281, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000003d61890794cd15c014d044d8f0344c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Known as the \"Hillside Gem of the Highlands\" Glencruitten Golf Club is located in the hills above the coastal town of Oban. The course was designed by James Braid and is a masterclass in utilizing difficult, rocky terrain. It is a short but incredibly hilly layout, featuring blind shots, dramatic elevation changes, and greens perched on rocky outcrops. While it may be physically taxing, the views over Oban Bay and the surrounding islands are worth every step.\r\n\r\nThe course\'s most famous son is the PGA Tour professional Robert MacIntyre, who grew up playing these rugged fairways and still represents the club on the world stage. MacIntyre\'s creative short game was undoubtedly forged on the tricky, sloping greens of Glencruitten. The course is characterized by its lush flora, including thousands of rhododendrons that bloom in the spring. It is a unique, charismatic course that doesn\'t fit the mold of a standard parkland or links layout; instead, it offers a purely Highland adventure that tests your imagination and your stamina in equal measure.', ''),
('gleneagleskings', 'Gleneagles - Kings', 'https://pursuits.gleneagles.com/reservations/template/21459/?', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'gleneagles', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.280540, -3.750691, 160448, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000593673486a010ec0249c16bce8234c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'The King\'s Course at Gleneagles is arguably the most famous inland course in the world. Opened in 1919 and designed by James Braid, it was intended to be a \"highland links\"-a course that played like a coastal links but was set among the dramatic peaks of the Ochil Hills. Braid\'s masterpiece is a symphony of springy turf, massive bunkers, and blind shots over ridges (the \"whins\"). It has hosted legendary events, including the first-ever unofficial Ryder Cup in 1921, as well as countless European Tour events.\r\n\r\nFamous members and visitors are too numerous to count, ranging from Hollywood royalty to world leaders. The King\'s is a grand, aristocratic layout where every hole has a name and a story. The 18th hole, \"Dun Whinny\" is one of the most iconic finishes in golf, requiring a climb up toward the majestic hotel. Following a massive restoration project to return the course to Braid\'s original vision, the fairways are wider and the bunkers more rugged, ensuring that the King\'s remains the gold standard for moorland golf and a primary reason why Gleneagles is known as a \"Golfer\'s Paradise.\"', ''),
('gleneaglespga', 'Gleneagles - PGA', 'https://pursuits.gleneagles.com/reservations/template/22053/?', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'gleneagles', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.280564, -3.750537, 160454, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000ed80eb8a19010ec0ac376a85e9234c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'The PGA Centenary Course at Gleneagles is a modern titan of the game, designed by the legendary Jack Nicklaus. Opened in 1993, it was created specifically to host the world\'s biggest stages. Nicklaus described the land as the \"finest parcel of ground in the world\" he had ever been given to work with. Unlike the older Braid designs at the resort, the PGA Centenary is an American-style \"stadium\" course, featuring large, fast greens, expansive white sand bunkers, and multiple teeing options that can stretch the course to over 7,000 yards.\r\n\r\nThis course etched its name into history as the venue for the 2014 Ryder Cup, where Europe triumphed under Paul McGinnity, and the 2019 Solheim Cup, arguably one of the most dramatic finishes in women\'s golf history. It is a course of dramatic risk and reward, particularly the par-five 18th, which has witnessed countless eagles and heartbreak alike. With the backdrop of the Perthshire mountains and the impeccable maintenance standards of the Gleneagles estate, it offers a tour-professional experience that demands power, precision, and nerves of steel.', ''),
('gleneaglesqueens', 'Gleneagles - Queens', 'https://pursuits.gleneagles.com/reservations/template/22052/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'gleneagles', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.280540, -3.750691, 160451, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000593673486a010ec0249c16bce8234c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'While the Kings is grand and the PGA Centenary is formidable, many regular visitors to Gleneagles consider the Queen\'s Course to be the most beautiful of the three. Another James Braid masterpiece, the Queen\'s is shorter and more sheltered than its \"royal\" sibling, winding its way through woodland, past natural lochans, and along the base of the hills. It is the epitome of \"bijou\" golf-small, perfectly formed, and utterly charming. However, do not let its beauty fool you; its defense lies in its tricky, small greens and the strategic requirement to place your ball on the correct side of the fairway.\r\n\r\nThe Queen\'s has hosted many notable figures over the decades, from Sean Connery to world leaders who appreciated its more tranquil, private feel. It is a course that emphasizes the \"joy of the game.\" Following recent renovations to restore Braid\'s original bunker shapes and fairway widths, the course plays as a true heathland gem. It is the perfect choice for a morning round where the focus is on the spectacular Highland scenery and the pure satisfaction of a well-struck iron shot into a secluded, pine-fringed green.', ''),
('gleneagleswee', 'Gleneagles - Wee', 'https://gleneagles.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.280564, -3.750537, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000ed80eb8a19010ec0ac376a85e9234c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Wee Course at Gleneagles proves that great things come in small packages. Originally a 9-hole layout designed by George Alexander and later refined by the resort\'s professional staff, it serves as the perfect \"nursery\" for the championship courses. However, it is far more than just a beginner\'s track. It is a beautifully maintained par-three and par-four layout that features the same manicured turf and high-quality greens as its world-famous neighbors. It provides a relaxed environment for families, juniors, and those looking to sharpen their short game.\r\n\r\nThe course is located right in the heart of the resort, making it an easy addition to a golf-heavy itinerary. It has become a vital part of the Gleneagles Golf Academy, helping to introduce the next generation to the traditions of the game. For the seasoned golfer, the Wee Course offers a delightful challenge of wedge play and putting, all while enjoying the same crisp mountain air and luxury atmosphere of the wider estate. It is a testament to the club\'s philosophy that every golfer, regardless of age or ability, deserves a world-class experience.', ''),
('glengolfclub', 'Glen North Berwick', 'https://www.glengolfclub.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 56.057260, -2.702740, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.glengolfclub.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000073ba2c26369f05c03aafb14b54074c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Glen Golf Club, also known as the \"East Links\" of North Berwick, offers a dramatic contrast to the town\'s famous West Links. While the West is a traditional low-lying links, the Glen is perched atop the rugged cliffs, offering a \"clifftop links\" experience that provides some of the most stunning views in golf. Founded in 1894, the course was originally a 9-hole layout before being extended by James Braid and Ben Sayers. Every hole offers a different perspective of the iconic Bass Rock, which sits just offshore, teeming with gannets.\r\n\r\nThe signature hole, the par-three 13th \"Sea Hole\" is one of the most photographed in Scotland; it requires a blind shot from an elevated tee toward a green tucked against a beach and a rock wall. The course has a vibrant history and a famously friendly membership. It provides a rugged, adventurous alternative to the more formal East Lothian courses. The wind here is a constant factor, and the elevation changes make for a physically engaging round. It is a must-play for anyone visiting the area who wants to experience the raw, natural beauty of the Firth of Forth.', ''),
('glenisla9', 'Glen Isla', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/glenisla9#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/glenisla9#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.621310, -3.205200, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'glenisla9', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000151dc9e53fa409c0c1560916874f4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in the heart of the \"Valleys of Angus\" Glen Isla is a modern parkland course that was opened in 1994. Designed by Tony Wardle, who worked with the Robert Trent Jones design group, the course has a spacious, contemporary feel that makes great use of the Perthshire countryside. Unlike the tight, tree-lined corridors of older inland courses, Glen Isla offers wide, rolling fairways that encourage a more expansive style of play. The course is built on the site of an old farm, and many of the original drystone dykes have been incorporated into the design.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its excellent drainage and year-round playability, making it a popular choice for local golfers during the wetter months. While it may not have the ancient history of other clubs, it has built a strong reputation for its relaxed atmosphere and high-quality greens. The layout features several significant water hazards, particularly the burn that meanders through the back nine, requiring careful strategy. It is a peaceful, scenic retreat that offers a high-quality \"modern Scottish\" golfing experience at a very accessible price point.', ''),
('glenrothes', 'Glenrothes', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/glenrothes#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/glenrothes#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.186977, -3.211678, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'glenrothes', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000f2423a3c84b109c0560dc2dcee174c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Glenrothes Golf Club is a premier municipal course located in the heart of Fife. Established in 1967 to serve the \"New Town\" of Glenrothes, the course was designed by the esteemed J.R. Stutt. It is a sprawling, 18-hole parkland layout that offers a sense of space and tranquility rarely found in an urban setting. The course is characterized by its significant undulations and large, well-protected greens. Because it was designed as part of a modern urban plan, the routing is excellent, providing a smooth and logical flow from hole to hole.\r\n\r\nThe club is a hub of competitive amateur golf in Fife, regularly hosting county events and regional qualifying. It is particularly known for its challenging closing stretch, where a series of long par-fours can make or break a scorecard. The course is maintained to a high standard, reflecting the town\'s pride in its sporting facilities. For visitors, Glenrothes offers a welcoming, \"no-frills\" golfing experience that focuses on the quality of the layout and the warmth of the local community. It is a fantastic example of the high-quality public golf that makes Scotland the envy of the world.', ''),
('gogarburn', 'Gogarburn', 'https://gogarburn.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://gogarburn.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.932691, -3.343357, 0, 0, '', '', 'gogarburn', 1908, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000046d26ef431bf0ac003232f6b62f74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Gogarburn Golf Club is a unique 12-hole course located on the western fringes of Edinburgh, near the airport. It is a club with a fascinating history, having originally been the private course for the staff of the nearby Gogarburn Hospital. Today, it is a thriving independent club that provides a vital service for golfers looking for a high-quality, \"quick\" round. The 12-hole format is increasingly popular for modern lifestyles, allowing for a satisfying game of golf that fits into a busy schedule.\r\n\r\nThe course is a lush parkland layout, featuring mature trees and remarkably well-kept greens. Despite its proximity to the city and the airport, it feels surprisingly secluded and peaceful. The layout is relatively flat, making it an easy walk for golfers of all ages. Gogarburn has a reputation for being one of the friendliest clubs in the Lothians, with a compact but lively clubhouse that serves as the heart of the community. It is a perfect example of how the game is adapting to the 21st century while maintaining the traditional values of Scottish golf.', ''),
('golfit', 'Golf It', 'https://www.golf-it.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.877123, -4.176904, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000058207a5226b510c0e2c8039145f04b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Golf It! is the newest and most revolutionary addition to the list, representing the cutting edge of golf development. Located on the banks of Hogganfield Loch in Glasgow, this is a community-focused \"hub\" rather than a traditional golf club. Opened by The R&A in 2023, the facility includes a redesigned 9-hole course, adventure golf, a double-decker driving range, and padel courts. The goal of Golf It! is to make golf accessible to everyone, regardless of background or experience, in a fun, non-intimidating environment.\r\n\r\nThe 9-hole course was designed to be \"short but sharp\" offering a fun challenge for experienced players while remaining playable for beginners. There is no dress code, and the focus is firmly on inclusivity and enjoyment. The facility also serves as a vocational center, providing jobs and training for local young people. While it doesn\'t have the \"Old Tom Morris\" pedigree, it is arguably one of the most important sites in modern Scottish golf, proving that the game can be a vibrant, accessible, and essential part of modern city life.', ''),
('golspie', 'Golspie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/golspie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/golspie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.964870, -3.990210, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'golspie', 1, 1, 'c', 0xe6100000010100000095607138f3eb0fc01d7233dc80fb4c40, 'links', 'No', 'Golspie Golf Club is a hidden gem of the Northern Highlands that offers one of the most varied and intereting rounds of golf in the country. Designed in 1889 by the local professional and later refined by James Braid, the course is a unique \"triple threat\": it begins as a pure links, moves into a stretch of heathland, and then finishes in a lush parkland setting. This variety means that in a single round, you will encounter sand dunes, gorse-lined fairways, and mature woodland.\r\n\r\nThe course sits in the shadow of Ben Bhraggie and offers spectacular views across the Dornoch Firth. It is often overshadowed by its famous neighbor, Royal Dornoch, but many connoisseurs of the game argue that Golspie is equally enjoyable due to its eclectic layout. The club has a warm, traditional feel and is a regular host of the Highland Golf Week. One of the most famous features is the 16th hole, a par-three played toward the sea that requires a steady nerve. Golspie is the quintessential \"hidden gem\" that rewards the traveler who ventures further north.\r\n', ''),
('gourock', 'Gourock', 'https://www.gourockgolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.gourockgolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.946340, -4.843449, 0, 2294, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000028603b18b15f13c0c5724bab21f94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Gourock Golf Club, perched on the hills above the Firth of Clyde, offers views that are frequently described as the best in Scottish golf. From the clubhouse and the higher holes, you can see the gateway to the Highlands, the Argyll Hills, and the Holy Loch. Founded in 1896, the course moved to its current location in 1925, with a layout that utilizes the rugged, sloping moorland to create a physically demanding and visually spectacular test of golf.\r\n\r\nThe club is a pioneer in modern technology, being one of the first in Scotland to install a full-scale Toptracer driving range alongside its traditional course. The layout itself is characterized by its narrow fairways and undulating terrain, requiring players to be creative with their shot-making. Gourock has a strong local membership and is known for its social atmosphere. While the climb can be steep, the exhilaration of hitting a drive from one of the elevated tees into the valley belowwith the Clyde shimmering in the distanceis a feeling that every golfer should experience.', ''),
('Grangemouth', 'Grangemouth', 'https://www.grangemouthgolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 55.996225, -3.686666, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000007b336abe4a7e0dc0933a014d84ff4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Grangemouth Golf Club is a polished parkland course that serves as a testament to the high standards of public golf in Scotland. While the club\'s history dates back to 1909, the current layout was designed in 1974 by the esteemed F.W. Hawtree, a member of the oldest golf course design firm in the world. Hawtree brought a sense of modern championship scale to the site, creating a par-71 course that is famously long and testing. The fairways are broad and inviting, but the strategic placement of mature trees and large, undulating greens ensures that a low score is never guaranteed.\r\n\r\nThe course is widely recognized for its exceptional drainage and year-round conditioning, often remaining open when other local courses are closed due to rain. This reliability has made it a popular venue for regional PGA events and amateur tournaments alike. While the town is known for its industrial heritage, the course itself is a peaceful, green sanctuary. Its signature hole, the 14th, requires a precise approach to a green guarded by significant bunkering. It is a friendly, accessible club that prides itself on offering a high-quality \"touring professional\" experience to the local community and visitors.', ''),
('grantownonspey', 'Grantown on Spey', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/grantownonspey#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/grantownonspey#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.333724, -3.594991, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'grantownonspey', 1, 1, 'e', 0xe610000001010000008f5033a48ac20cc0f5f1d077b7aa4c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'Set within the heart of the Cairngorms National Park, Grantown-on-Spey Golf Club is a masterclass in Highland golf design. Established in 1890, the course was originally the work of Willie Park Jr., with later refinements made by the legendary James Braid in 1921. This \"double-architect\" pedigree is evident in the clever routing, which takes players through a diverse mix of lush parkland and rugged woodland. The backdrop of the Cromdale Hills and the Cairngorm mountains provides a cinematic setting that has captivated golfers for over a century.\r\n\r\nThe course is particularly famous for its spectacular closing holes. The 16th, \"Murdie\'s View\" offers a panoramic vista that is frequently cited as one of the best in the Highlands. The club has a long history of tourism, attracting many notable visitors who seek the tranquility of the Speyside region. Grantown has also produced numerous high-level amateurs, reflecting the quality of the challenge. It is a course that rewards strategy over brute force, with Braid\'s signature bunkering requiring careful thought. For any golfer touring the whisky-rich Spey Valley, this course is an essential stop that blends historic design with natural grandeur.', ''),
('greenburn', 'Greenburn', 'https://greenburn.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://greenburn.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'central', 'Yes', 55.821238, -3.704642, 0, 0, '', '', 'greenburn', 1765, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000b11a4b581ba30dc0c11da8531ee94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Greenburn Golf Club, located near the village of Fauldhouse in West Lothian, is a charming moorland-style course with a history rooted in the local coal-mining community. The club was instituted in 1894 and has moved several times before settling into its current, well-established layout. The course sits on high ground, offering sweeping views of the surrounding hills and the central belt. Its character is defined by its firm, springy turf and the ever-present Highland breeze, which makes the relatively modest yardage play much longer than it appears on the scorecard.\r\n\r\nWhile it may not have a \"celebrity\" architect attached to its modern iteration, the course is a model of traditional Scottish golf. It features natural hazards like ditches and patches of rushes that require accurate ball-striking to avoid. The club is known for its resilient, competitive membership and a clubhouse that radiates local hospitality. It is a course that demands respect, particularly on the par-threes, which are often cited as the layout\'s strongest defense. For those looking for an authentic, unpretentious round of golf in a rugged landscape, Greenburn offers a high-value experience that captures the true spirit of the Scottish game.', ''),
('greenock', 'Greenock', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/greenock#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.950728, -4.779566, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'greenock', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000004d4bac8c461e13c01cb28174b1f94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Perched in a commanding position high above the town, Greenock Golf Club offers some of the most stunning vistas in the country, looking across the Clyde Estuary toward the Argyll hills. Founded in 1890, the club made a significant move in 1924 when they invited the \"busiest of all architects\" James Braid, to redesign the layout. Braid recommended purchasing the leased farmland to create a truly permanent and professional facility. The result was a majestic 18-hole moorland course that remains one of the premier tests in the West of Scotland.\r\n\r\nThe course is characterized by its wide, wind-swept fairways and large, undulating greens that Braid designed to be both fair and challenging. Over the decades, the club has hosted many prestigious events, including regional qualifying for the Open Championship. Its most famous member in the modern era is likely the professional Stephen Gallacher, who has often praised the course\'s strategic depth. With its dramatic elevation changes and the sound of the wind through the trees, playing Greenock is an atmospheric experience that combines championship-standard architecture with the raw beauty of the Renfrewshire hills.', ''),
('greenockwee', 'Greenock - Wee', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/greenock#/course/3', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.950728, -4.779566, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'greenock', 3, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000004d4bac8c461e13c01cb28174b1f94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The \"Wee Course\" at Greenock is a delightful 9-hole layout that shares the same spectacular hillside site as its larger 18-hole sibling. Also part of the 1924 James Braid redesign, this course was intended to provide a high-quality alternative for those with limited time or those looking to hone their short game. Despite its name, the Wee Course is built to the same exacting standards as the championship layout, featuring Braid\'s signature strategic bunkering and undulating green complexes that demand a sharp touch with the putter.\r\n\r\nThe layout is a par-32 and measures just over 2,100 yards, but its defense lies in its free-draining nature and the natural hazards of the parkland terrain. The stretch from the 4th to the 8th hole is particularly acclaimed, featuring elevated tees that provide \"eye-level\" views of the River Clyde. It is a popular choice for juniors and seniors, serving as a vital nursery for the club\'s talent. Playing the Wee Course allows golfers to experience the genius of Braid on a smaller canvas, making it a perfect addition to a day of golf at Greenock for those who simply can\'t get enough of the view.', ''),
('greenockwhinhill', 'Greenock Whinhill', 'https://greenockwhinhill.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.935805, -4.762385, 0, 0, '', '', 'greenockwhinhill', 9755, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000006d847a7ae0c13c076374f75c8f74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Established in 1911, Greenock Whinhill Golf Club is a rugged and charismatic 18-hole moorland course that sits adjacent to the Greenock club. The course was designed by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie, whose philosophy of working with the natural \"lie of the land\" is evident in every hole. While it is a relatively short par-68, the Whinhill is famously difficult to \"master\" due to its unpredictable lies and the natural gorse and heather that line the fairways. It offers a raw, traditional golfing experience that contrasts with the more manicured parkland courses nearby.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for having one of the most unusual starts in golf: a challenging par-three opening hole that immediately tests the player\'s nerves. Whinhill has a loyal and fiercely competitive membership, often producing strong results in local Renfrewshire county tournaments. The panoramic views over the Clyde and the surrounding mountains are as dramatic as those of any course in the region. It is a \"working man\'s\" course in the best sensehonest, tough, and full of character. For golfers who enjoy the challenge of navigating natural obstacles in a windswept environment, Whinhill is a true hidden gem.', ''),
('gullane', 'Gullane - 1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/gullane', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 56.034281, -2.837353, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'gullane', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000efa83121e6b206c0e5efde5163044c40, 'links', 'No', 'Gullane No. 1 is the flagship of the three courses at Gullane and is a titan of world golf. While golf has been played on this site since the mid-17th century, the course reached its current form in 1884. Its architect is officially unknown, though it has been refined by many hands over the years. It is a championship links that has hosted almost every major event in the game, including Final Qualifying for the Open and the Scottish Open in 2015 and 2018 (won by Rickie Fowler and Brandon Stone, respectively).\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for the \"King\'s Chair\" a natural stone formation on the 7th hole that offers what is widely considered the best view in golf-a 360-degree panorama of East Lothian, the Firth of Forth, and Fife. Notable members have included legends like Babe Zaharias and Peter Thomson. The turf here is the gold standard of links golf: firm, fast, and remarkably free-draining. With its deep revetted bunkers and \"perfect\" greens, Gullane No. 1 is an uncompromising test of skill that requires every shot in the bag, all played out on some of the most historic links land in existence.', ''),
('gullane2', 'Gullane - 2', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/gullane', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 56.034281, -2.837353, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'gullane', 3, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000efa83121e6b206c0e5efde5163044c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Laid out in 1898 by the two-time Open Champion Willie Park Jr., Gullane No. 2 runs alongside its older sibling for the first few holes before sweeping down toward the Aberlady Bay nature reserve. Park, who also designed Sunningdale, brought a refined architectural eye to the links, creating a layout that many members actually prefer to No. 1 for its variety and flow. At over 6,300 yards, it is a formidable championship course in its own right and has frequently been used for Final Qualifying for the Open Championship.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its collection of par-threes, particularly the 11th, which features a long carry to a green framed by breathtaking coastal views. Champions from Babe Zaharias to Peter Thomson have triumphed here, cementing its reputation as a high-caliber venue. The transition from the high ridges of the hill to the lower coastal land provides a fascinating tactical shift mid-round. Gullane No. 2 offers all the charm and challenge of the Gullane hill-including the same impeccable conditioning-but with a unique character that emphasizes the beauty of the East Lothian coastline.', ''),
('gullane3', 'Gullane - 3', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/gullane', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 56.034281, -2.837353, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'gullane', 5, 1, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000efa83121e6b206c0e5efde5163044c40, 'links', 'No', 'Gullane No. 3 may be the shortest of the trio, but it is often described as the most \"fun\" course on the hill. Another Willie Park Jr. masterpiece, opened in 1910, No. 3 was designed to emphasize shot-making and accuracy over raw power. Despite its modest yardage, it is maintained to the exact same championship standards as the other two courses, offering the same firm links turf and lightning-fast greens. It is the perfect venue for those who appreciate the strategic \"short game\" side of golf.\r\n\r\nThe course offers some of the most intimate views of the village and the Firth of Forth. Because it is less physically demanding than No. 1 and No. 2, it is a favorite for those playing 36 holes in a day. However, the small, tricky greens and the 100-plus bunkers ensure that it is no soft option. It celebrated its centenary in 2010 and remains a beloved part of the Gullane landscape. For many visitors, No. 3 is the \"secret favorite\"-a course that proves you don\'t need 7,000 yards to have a world-class golfing experience in the heart of East Lothian.', ''),
('haddington', 'Haddington', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/haddington#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/haddington#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 55.957044, -2.758470, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'haddington', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000001afa27b8581106c0a16af46a80fa4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Haddington Golf Club claims a remarkable place in the history of the game as the 19th oldest golf course in the world. Founded in 1865, the club eventually settled at its current home, Amisfield Park, in 1960. The land was formerly a grand 18th-century estate, and while the mansion was demolished in 1928, the historic stable block and walled garden still remain, providing a stately atmosphere. The course is a lush, mature parkland layout that offers a peaceful alternative to the nearby windswept links of the East Lothian coast.\r\n\r\nThe layout is known for its wide, inviting fairways and the River Tyne, which meanders along the boundary and comes into play on several holes. One of the highlights is the \"Quarry Hole\" a challenging par-three played uphill over a cliff face. While it hasn\'t hosted the professional majors of its coastal neighbors, Haddington is a pillar of the local community and a frequent host of Lothians county championships. It is a traditional, friendly club where history and nature combine to provide a relaxed but testing round of golf in one of Scotland\'s most beautiful market towns.', ''),
('haggscastle', 'Haggs Castle', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/haggscastle#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.834630, -4.319715, 0, 0, '', '', '', 1594, 'haggscastle', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000009e29745e634711c05721e527d5ea4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Haggs Castle Golf Club is widely regarded as one of the premier parkland courses in the West of Scotland. Set within the lush, wooded grounds of Pollok Country Park on the outskirts of Glasgow, the course was designed in 1910 by the prolific James Braid. Braid\'s genius is on full display here, as he utilized the rolling terrain and mature oaks to create a layout that feels both grand and intimate. The course famously hosted the Scottish Open in 1986, which saw David Feherty claim victory, as well as several other European Tour events throughout the 1980s.\r\n\r\nThe club takes its name from the historic Haggs Castle, built in 1585, which stands near the entrance. Notable members have included some of Glasgow\'s most prominent industrial and sporting figures. The course is known for its impeccably fast greens and its challenging closing stretch, where the tree-lined fairways demand absolute precision. Despite being located just minutes from the city center, Haggs Castle provides a serene, high-caliber golfing experience that maintains a championship standard of conditioning year-round. It remains a \"must-play\" for those who value the strategic depth of a classic Braid parkland design.', ''),
('hamilton', 'Hamilton', 'https://www.hamiltongolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.761277, -4.007059, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000e29178793a0710c03719558671e14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Hamilton Golf Club is an aristocratic parkland gem situated in the historic town of Hamilton. Founded in 1892, the course was significantly redesigned by James Braid in 1925, who transformed it into the challenging and scenic layout that exists today. The course is characterized by its dramatic elevation changes and a series of deep ravines that come into play on several of the most memorable holes. The fairways are lined with a diverse range of mature trees, including majestic copper beeches, which provide a stunning color palette throughout the seasons.\r\n\r\nThe club has a storied history of hosting top-tier amateur and professional events, including the Scottish Professional Championship. It has produced many talented golfers over the years, most notably Belle Robertson, one of the most decorated female amateur golfers in history and a member of the World Golf Hall of Fame. The signature \"ravine holes\" require both nerve and accuracy, as any wayward shot is likely to disappear into the lush undergrowth. With its grand clubhouse and a reputation for providing a stern test of ball-striking, Hamilton is a quintessential example of high-end Scottish inland golf.', ''),
('harburn', 'Harburn', 'https://harburn.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://harburn.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.830085, -3.543056, 0, 0, '', '', 'harburn', 93, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000302c7fbe2d580cc038f3ab3940ea4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Harburn Golf Club, located in West Lothian, is an atmospheric moorland-parkland hybrid that sits on the northern slopes of the Pentland Hills. Founded in 1925, the course was originally a 9-hole layout before being extended to 18 holes in the 1930s. At an elevation of over 800 feet, Harburn offers a refreshing \"mountain air\" experience and panoramic views that stretch across the central belt. The course is famously well-wooded, with thousands of trees planted over the decades to create a sheltered, forest-like environment on many of the holes.\r\n\r\nWhile Harburn may not have a \"famous name\" architect attached to its origins, the members themselves have refined the layout into a clever and testing course. It is known for its excellent drainage and high standard of maintenance. The club has a strong reputation for its inclusive and friendly social scene, making it a popular choice for visitors. The signature hole is the par-five 18th, which requires a climb back toward the clubhouse and provides a challenging finish to a round. It is a course that rewards the thinking golfer, as the narrow, tree-lined corridors punish those who try to overpower the layout.', ''),
('hawick', 'Hawick', 'https://www.hawickgolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.hawickgolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.411913, -2.799938, 0, 2311, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000069fe6e4456606c00ce6af90b9b44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Hawick Golf Club is the oldest club in the Scottish Borders, founded in 1877. The course is situated on the Vertish Hill, a location that provides some of the most spectacular views in the region, overlooking the historic town and the surrounding Cheviot Hills. The layout was refined by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie, who maximized the natural slopes of the hill to create a challenging and varied test of golf. The course is characterized by its undulating fairways, small greens, and the \"whins\" (gorse) that add a traditional Scottish bite to the round.\r\n\r\nThe club\'s most famous member is undoubtedly the legendary rugby commentator Bill McLaren, who was a lifelong supporter and frequent visitor to the fairways. Hawick is also known for producing high-quality amateur golfers who have excelled in the Borders circuit. The course is a physically demanding walk, but the reward is a series of elevated tees that allow for heroic drives into the valleys below. It is a traditional, unpretentious club that prides itself on its history and its warm Borders hospitality, making it a favorite for those touring the south of Scotland.', ''),
('hayston', 'Hayston', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hayston#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hayston#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.942564, -4.182918, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'hayston', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000001f662fdb4ebb10c08731e9efa5f84b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in Kirkintilloch, Hayston Golf Club is a beautiful parkland course that sits in the shadow of the Campsie Fells. Founded in 1922, the course was designed by the esteemed James Braid, who was a master at creating challenging green complexes. Hayston is known for its lush, mature woodland and the Kelvinside Burn, which meanders through the property and provides a natural hazard on several holes. The course has a \"championship\" feel, with well-placed bunkers and narrow fairways that require careful navigation.\r\n\r\nThe club has a proud history of hosting regional qualifying for the Open Championship and has been a frequent venue for the Glasgow Open. It is often cited as having some of the best-conditioned greens in the Dunbartonshire area. The layout is relatively flat, making it an enjoyable walk, but the strategic placement of Braid\'s hazards ensures that it remains a formidable test for low handicappers. Hayston is a traditional \"member-focused\" club that offers a professional and welcoming environment, perfectly blending historic design with the natural beauty of the Stirlingshire countryside.', '');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('hazlehead', 'Hazlehead - MacKenzie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hazlehead#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hazlehead#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 56.487305, -3.015692, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'hazlehead', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000007d789620232008c0b1169f02603e4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The MacKenzie Course at Hazlehead is the \"Crown Jewel\" of Aberdeen\'s municipal golf offering. Designed in 1920 by the legendary Dr. Alister MacKenziethe man responsible for Augusta National and Cypress Pointit is one of the few places in the world where you can play a MacKenzie masterpiece for a public green fee. The course is a classic heathland-parkland hybrid, winding through dense pine forests and over rolling hills. MacKenzie\'s signature style is evident in the large, undulating greens and the strategic use of natural contours to defend par.\r\n\r\nThe course has a rich professional history, having hosted the Aberdeen City Open and many prestigious amateur championships. It is famously long and testing, particularly when the wind blows through the trees. Despite its municipal status, the course is maintained to a very high standard, reflecting the city\'s pride in its MacKenzie heritage. Playing here offers a fascinating glimpse into the early design philosophy of one of golf\'s greatest architects. It is a rugged, beautiful, and intellectually stimulating course that provides a world-class experience without the high price tag of a private club.', ''),
('hazlehead9', 'Hazlehead 9 Holer', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hazlehead#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hazlehead#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.137760, -2.181710, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'hazlehead9', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000006ad95a5f247401c03659a31ea2914c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The 9-hole course at Hazlehead serves as the perfect entry point for beginners and a vital practice facility for the more experienced golfers of Aberdeen. While it lacks the international pedigree of its \"MacKenzie\" sibling, it is built on the same high-quality parkland terrain and offers a fun, relaxed environment. The layout is relatively short, but it features several challenging par-threes and narrow fairways that require a respectable level of accuracy. It is the quintessential \"nursery\" course, fostering a love for the game in generations of local Aberdonians.\r\n\r\nThe course is frequently used for \"Quick Golf\" and by families who want to enjoy the spectacular scenery of the Hazlehead estate without committing to a full four-hour round. It is remarkably well-maintained and provides a scenic escape from the urban hustle of the city. Because it shares the same clubhouse and facilities as the two 18-hole courses on the site, it benefits from a lively and professional atmosphere. It is a shining example of how public golf facilities can cater to every level of the game, ensuring that golf remains an accessible and central part of Scottish community life.', ''),
('hazleheadpines', 'Hazlehead - Pines', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hazlehead#/course/3', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 56.487305, -3.015692, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'hazlehead', 3, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000007d789620232008c0b1169f02603e4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Pines Course at Hazlehead is the perfect \"middle ground\" between the championship MacKenzie Course and the beginner-friendly 9-hole layout. Opened in the early 1970s and designed by John Stutt, the course was created to alleviate the pressure on the increasingly popular MacKenzie course. As its name suggests, the Pines is a heavily wooded parkland layout where the fairways are framed by magnificent corridors of Scots pine and larch. It offers a slightly more modern challenge, with wider fairways but smaller, more target-oriented greens.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its excellent drainage and for being a slightly easier walk than the hilly MacKenzie. However, don\'t let its \"second course\" status fool you; it is a stern test of golf in its own right and is a favorite for local society outings and corporate days. The Pines offers a sense of total seclusion, as the dense forest separates each hole from the next. It is a beautifully peaceful environment where the only sound is the wind through the needles and the occasional chatter of a red squirrel, providing a tranquil and high-quality round of Aberdeen parkland golf.', ''),
('helensburgh', 'Helensburgh', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/helensburgh#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/helensburgh#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 56.013645, -4.707896, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'helensburgh', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000007ae063b0e2d412c080608e1ebf014c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Helensburgh Golf Club, situated on the hills overlooking the Firth of Clyde and the Gare Loch, offers a dramatic moorland golfing experience. Founded in 1893, the course was redesigned by the legendary James Braid in the early 20th century. Braid\'s layout makes full use of the rugged, undulating terrain, requiring golfers to navigate natural gullies, heather-clad slopes, and the occasional rocky outcrop. The panoramic views from the higher holes, stretching toward the mountains of Loch Lomond and the Trossachs, are among the finest in the West of Scotland.\r\n\r\nThe club has a strong connection to the local community and has produced many fine golfers who have excelled in Dunbartonshire county events. The course is known for its fast, true greens and its challenging \"out and back\" routing. While the wind is a frequent and formidable defender of the course, the springy moorland turf ensures that the playing conditions remain excellent throughout the year. It is a traditional, friendly club with a lively social atmosphere, offering a rugged and authentic Highland-edge golfing experience just a short train ride from the center of Glasgow.', ''),
('Helmsdale', 'Helmsdale', 'http://www.helmsdale.org/golf.html', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 58.121058, -3.657729, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000d80b056c07430dc0a7751bd47e0f4d40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Helmsdale Golf Club is a stunning and remote 9-hole course located on the east coast of Sutherland, far into the Northern Highlands. Originally established in 1923, the course is a \"hidden gem\" in the truest sense, offering a raw and natural golfing experience that has remained largely unchanged for a century. The layout is a hybrid of links and hill-land, featuring massive elevation changes and views over the North Sea and the village of Helmsdale that are simply breathtaking. The course is maintained by a small team of dedicated local volunteers.\r\n\r\nThe most famous feature of Helmsdale is the climb to the higher holes, which requires a fair degree of fitness but rewards the golfer with a spectacular descent back toward the sea. The layout is quirky and charismatic, with small greens perched on natural plateaus. It is a \"honesty box\" club where the focus is on the sheer enjoyment of the game in a wild and beautiful setting. For golfers exploring the North Coast 500, a stop at Helmsdale is a mandatory pilgrimage to experience the soul of Highland golfunpretentious, incredibly scenic, and deeply rooted in the local landscape.', ''),
('hiltonpark', 'Hilton Park - Hilton', 'https://hiltonpark.net/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.968482, -4.361614, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000005d1abff04a7211c0e161da37f7fb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Situated just ten miles from Glasgow but feeling worlds apart, Hilton Park is home to two of the finest moorland courses in Scotland. The Hilton Course, the longer of the two, was designed in 1927 by the five-time Open Champion James Braid. It is a majestic layout that offers sweeping views of the Campsie Fells to the north and the city of Glasgow to the south. The course is famous for its strategic demand; Braid\'s original vision was so challenging that he actually had to return to soften it slightly for the membership.\r\n\r\nThe club was the home course for PGA Tour winner Martin Laird during his formative years. One of its most distinctive features is the 17th hole, known as the \"Muckle Drap\" a dramatic par-three that plays from an elevated tee to a green far below. Legend also has it that an unexploded WWII shell remains buried beneath the 1st green, adding a unique (if quiet) bit of history to your opening shot.', ''),
('hiltonparkallander', 'Hilton Park - Allander', 'https://hiltonpark.net/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.968482, -4.361614, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000005d1abff04a7211c0e161da37f7fb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Allander Course, also designed by James Braid, is shorter than its sibling but arguably tighter and more demanding of accuracy. While the Hilton Course allows for a few wayward drives, the Allander rewards the golfer who can shape shots through mature woodland and navigate the natural moorland hazards. It is named after the River Allander, which flows nearby, and it shares the same spectacular views of the Highland fringe.\r\n\r\nBecause both courses are maintained to a high standard, the Allander is often used for prestigious regional tournaments and serves as a vital part of the club\'s vibrant competitive scene. It is a favorite for those who enjoy \"thinking\" their way around a course rather than relying on power. The two courses together make Hilton Park one of the most substantial and high-quality golfing complexes in the West of Scotland.', ''),
('HoddomCastle', 'Hoddom Castle', 'https://www.hoddomcastle.co.uk/activities', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'south', '', 55.041556, -3.310412, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000a1496249b97b0ac0ee79feb451854b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Set within the historic grounds of a 16th-century tower house near Annan, Hoddom Castle Golf Club offers a 9-hole parkland experience steeped in character. The course winds through ancient woodland and along the banks of the River Annan. It is a quintessential \"country estate\" course, where the focus is on natural beauty and a relaxed atmosphere. The castle itself provides a stunning backdrop to several holes.\r\n\r\nThe layout is known for its peaceful environment and its ability to challenge golfers of all levels with its variety of shots. It is a popular spot for visitors staying in the local caravan park and estate cottages, offering a high-quality \"holiday golf\" experience. While it doesn\'t host professional tour events, its charm lies in its simplicity and the historic weight of its surroundings.', ''),
('hollandbush', 'Hollandbush', 'https://hollandbush.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.613276, -3.885465, 0, 0, '', '', 'hollandbush', 306, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000680586ac6e150fc0fab5f5d37fce4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Hollandbush Golf Club, located in South Lanarkshire, is an 18-hole course that sits on the edge of the moorland, offering a distinct \"inland links\" feel. The club has its roots in the 1920s but was formally established in 1954 through the dedication of local miners and residents. The course was originally a 9-hole layout designed by James Lawson before being expanded by the local council to its current 18-hole form.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its panoramic views of the Southern Uplandson clear days, you can see as far as Ben More and Ben Vorlich. It is a rugged, honest course that emphasizes the community spirit of Scottish golf. The club recently named its lounge after Jim Hamilton, a founding member who served the club for 50 years, reflecting the deep personal history embedded in the fairways.', ''),
('hopemangolf', 'Hopeman', 'https://www.hopemangolf.club/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.709953, -3.419223, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.hopemangolf.club', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000001bd99596915a0bc03a596abddfda4c40, 'links', 'No', 'Hopeman Golf Club is home to one of the most famous par-threes in Scotland. Located on the Moray Firth coast, this links course was originally a 9-hole design from 1909, later expanded to 18 holes in 1985. The legendary Paul Lawrie, the 1999 Open Champion, is an Honorary President and has described the signature 12th hole, \"The Prieshach\" as the best par-three he has ever played. The tee sits over 100 feet above a green nestled in a cove by the sea.\r\n\r\nThe course is a visual masterpiece, with gorse-lined fairways and the chance to spot dolphins playing in the Firth during your round. It is a rugged, windswept test that rewards accuracy over length. The club also counts former Prime Minister Ramsay MacDonald among its past honorary members, cementing its status as a cornerstone of Moray\'s golfing heritage.', ''),
('huntly', 'Huntly', 'https://huntly.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://huntly.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.454266, -2.774880, 0, 0, '', '', 'huntly', 1743, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000089981249f43206c0a5d7666325ba4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Huntly Golf Club is a beautiful parkland course in Aberdeenshire with a history that involves a consultation with Old Tom Morris himself. Established in 1892, the course sits between the River Bogie and the River Deveron. While it began as a 9-hole course, it was extended to 18 holes in the 1930s. The layout is undulating and tree-lined, providing a classic inland challenge.\r\n\r\nThe club has a reputation for producing high-caliber professional talent, including John and David Chillas, both of whom went on to play on the European Tour. Huntly is known for its warm welcome and its remarkably consistent playing surfaces. The signature holes along the rivers require a steady hand and precise club selection, making it one of the most respected parkland tests in the North East.', ''),
('inbereshieestate', 'Invereshie Estate', 'https://invereshieestate.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.121485, -3.914198, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000828c800a47500fc02ffa0ad28c8f4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Invereshie is a unique entrya private 9-hole course located within the historic Invereshie Estate in the heart of the Cairngorms National Park. The course is primarily available to guests staying in the estate\'s cottages. Set amongst Douglas Firs planted in the 1830s, it offers a serene, \"secret garden\" golfing experience where you are more likely to see red squirrels and roe deer than other golfers.\r\n\r\nThe course is natural and unpretentious, reflecting the wild beauty of Speyside. It isn\'t a championship venue in the traditional sense, but it represents the \"soul\" of Scottish estate golfa private playground carved out of a majestic Highland landscape. It is the perfect retreat for those who want to practice their game in total isolation surrounded by mountains.', ''),
('inchmarlo', 'Inchmarlo', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/inchmarlo#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/inchmarlo#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.058692, -2.531822, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'inchmarlo', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000b4588ae42b4104c0b7442e3883874c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in Banchory in the heart of Royal Deeside, the Queen\'s Course at Inchmarlo is a high-quality 9-hole layout designed by Graeme Webster. Opened in 1997, it was built to USGA standards, offering greens and fairways of exceptional quality. The course is characterized by its strategic bunkering and the spectacular views of the surrounding hills.\r\n\r\nInchmarlo is a premier training facility, featuring an extensive floodlit driving range and a short-game academy. The Queen\'s Course is designed to be \"fun but challenging\" making it a favorite for those looking to sharpen their skills before tackling the major courses of the North East. It provides a modern, professional resort atmosphere in one of Scotland\'s most scenic regions.', ''),
('Innellan', 'Innellan', 'https://www.innellangolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 55.898647, -4.955716, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000450e1137a7d213c002d369dd06f34b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Innellan Golf Club, perched on the hills above the Firth of Clyde near Dunoon, is a rugged 9-hole moorland course that offers what many call the best views in the West of Scotland. Founded in 1891, the course is a physical test, with steep climbs rewarded by panoramic vistas of the Cumbrae islands and the Ayrshire coast.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its Royal Hotel Trophy, a prestigious open competition that attracts players from across the region. The greens are small and tricky, often protected by the natural contours of the hill rather than artificial bunkers. It is a traditional \"village\" club where the atmosphere is as memorable as the elevation changes, embodying the grit and beauty of Argyll golf.', ''),
('innerleithen', 'Innerleithen', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/innerleithen#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/innerleithen#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.640109, -3.056931, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'innerleithen', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000005307793d987408c009707a17efd14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Innerleithen Golf Club is a delightful 9-hole course set in the Leithen Valley in the Scottish Borders. Designed by the three-time Open Champion Willie Park Jr. and established in 1886, it is a masterclass in utilizing a river as a natural hazard. The Leithen Water meanders through the course, coming into play on several holes and providing a soothing soundtrack to the round.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its \"Rockies\" feel, as it is surrounded by high hills on all sides. While it is a 9-hole layout, it features varying tee positions for the second nine to create an 18-hole experience. The opening par-three is notoriously difficult, requiring a shot over a road and a river. It is a friendly, scenic, and historic club that offers a tranquil escape in one of the most beautiful valleys in the Borders.', ''),
('insch', 'Insch', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/insch#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/insch#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.345883, -2.621639, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'insch', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000005c5837de1df904c0069fe6e445ac4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Insch Golf Club is a hidden treasure in the shadow of the spectacular Dunnideer Hill and its ancient hillfort. Founded in 1906 as a 9-hole course, it was extended to a full 18 holes in 1997, a project that transformed it into a modern parkland test with a distinct \"Highland edge.\" The layout is split between the older, flatter holes and the newer section, which climbs the hillside to offer panoramic views across the Garioch valley toward the peak of Bennachie.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its narrow, tree-lined fairways and exceptionally tricky greens. While it may not have a \"celebrity\" architect, the quality of the layout is a testament to the dedication of the local community who built it. Insch has gained a reputation for its conditioning, often described as a \"mini-Gleneagles\" by those who discover it. The signature 13th hole, \"Bennachie View\" requires a precise drive to a sloping fairway and provides one of the most photographed vistas in Aberdeenshire. It is a welcoming, traditional club where the spirit of the local village is as strong as the challenge on the course.', ''),
('inverallochygolfclub', 'Inverallochy', 'https://www.inverallochygolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.inverallochygolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.660228, -1.936152, 0, 2328, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000215c01857afafebfa5f3e15982d44c40, 'links', 'No', 'Inverallochy Golf Club is a pure, traditional links located on the rugged coast of the Buchan peninsula. This is a course where the sea is your constant companion; it is situated so close to the water that sea spray often coats the greens. Originally a 9-hole course, it was extended to 18 holes by the legendary James Braid in the 1920s. Braid utilized the natural sand dunes and the firm, sandy turf to create a layout that feels as though it was discovered rather than built.\r\n\r\nThe course has a unique \"out and back\" routing that is heavily influenced by the North Sea gales. It is a short par-63, but the lack of length is more than compensated for by the tight fairways and the encroaching gorse. Inverallochy is famous for its six par-threes, each playing in a different direction to ensure the wind never attacks the same way twice. Notable members have included several titans of the local fishing industry, and the club maintains a rugged, unpretentious atmosphere. For those seeking the rawest form of links golf in a remote, beautiful setting, Inverallochy is an absolute must-play.', ''),
('Inveraray', 'Inveraray', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 56.220870, -5.086394, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000524832ab775814c07155d977451c4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Inveraray Golf Club offers a truly regal setting on the shores of Loch Fyne. This 9-hole parkland course is located within the grounds of the historic Inveraray Castle, the ancestral home of the Duke of Argyll. Established in 1893, the course was redesigned in the 1920s by James Braid, who was invited by the Duke to create a layout worthy of the spectacular estate. The result is a course that winds through mature woodland and along the shoreline, offering views of the castle and the surrounding mountains that are second to none.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its peaceful, secluded atmosphere; you are more likely to hear the cry of an eagle or the splashing of a seal than any urban noise. While it is not a long course, Braid\'s strategic bunkering and the natural undulations of the estate land require a thoughtful approach. The 19th hole, located in the village, is a favorite for visitors who want to sample the world-famous local seafood after their round. It is a quintessential Highland estate course that blends high-level architecture with the timeless elegance of one of Scotland\'s most famous historical landmarks.', ''),
('invergordon', 'Invergordon', 'https://www.invergordongolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.invergordongolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.694398, -4.191557, 0, 2330, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000008d47a98427c410c033349e08e2d84c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Invergordon Golf Club is a lush parkland course situated on the shores of the Cromarty Firth. The club\'s history is inextricably linked to the military; the land was formerly used as a naval base during both World Wars, and the clubhouse was once a naval officer\'s mess. The 18-hole course was designed by the prolific J.R. Stutt, who was a close associate of James Braid. Stutt took advantage of the mild coastal climate to create a course that features an extraordinary array of mature trees and rhododendrons, making it a spectacular sight in the spring.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its wide fairways and large, receptive greens, which are often cited as some of the best-conditioned in the Highlands. It has a \"resort\" feel, offering a more relaxed challenge than the punishing links of the nearby Moray Firth. One of the highlights is the view of the massive oil rigs being refurbished in the Firth, a unique industrial backdrop that contrasts with the natural beauty of the course. Invergordon is a friendly, community-focused club that provides a high-quality, scenic round of golf for players of all abilities.', ''),
('inverness', 'Inverness', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/inverness#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/inverness#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.471974, -4.204219, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'inverness', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000026e318c91ed110c0fa47dfa469bc4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Inverness Golf Club is the premier parkland venue in the capital of the Highlands. Established in 1883, the course was significantly redesigned by George Smith and later refined by James Braid in the 1930s. Braid\'s influence is clear in the strategic bunkering and the clever routing that makes the course feel remarkably secluded despite its proximity to the city center. It is a classic parkland layout, characterized by its narrow, tree-lined fairways and the Culcabock Burn, which comes into play on several of the most challenging holes.\r\n\r\nThe club has a long history of hosting top-tier amateur and professional events, including the Northern Open and the Scottish North District Championships. Notable members have included several Scottish internationalists, and the club maintains a high standard of etiquette and tradition. The signature hole, the par-four 14th, requires a precise drive to avoid the trees and a nerve-wracking approach over the burn. With its magnificent clubhouse and a reputation for fast, true greens, Inverness Golf Club offers a polished and professional golfing experience that serves as the perfect centerpiece for a Highland golf tour.', ''),
('inverurie', 'Inverurie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/inverurie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/inverurie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.278666, -2.394214, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'inverurie', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000b4006dab592703c0ea40d653aba34c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in the heart of the \"Garioch\" Inverurie Golf Club is a scenic parkland course that offers spectacular views of the Don Valley and the peaks of the Grampian Mountains. Originally established as a 9-hole course in 1902, it was expanded to 18 holes in the 1920s with input from the legendary James Braid. The course is built on a hillside, providing a variety of lies and a physical test that requires a fair degree of fitness. The fairways are lined with a mix of broom, gorse, and mature woodland, giving the course a colorful and natural feel.\r\n\r\nInverurie is known for its firm, well-draining turf and its remarkably consistent greens. The club has produced many talented golfers over the decades and remains a competitive hub in the Aberdeenshire region. The signature hole is the 18th, a challenging par-four that requires a climb back toward the elevated clubhouse, offering a dramatic finish to the round. It is a traditional, friendly club that prides itself on its accessibility and its warm \"North East\" welcome. For those who enjoy the challenge of undulating terrain and the beauty of the Highland foothills, Inverurie is an essential stop.', ''),
('irvine', 'Irvine', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/irvine#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'clubv1', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.626590, -4.685650, 0, 0, '', '', '', 2689, 'irvine', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe6100000010100000075029a081bbe12c01500e31934d04b40, 'links', 'No', 'The Irvine Golf Club, commonly known as Bogside, is a heavyweight of Scottish golf. This is a traditional links course that has served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship on numerous occasions. Originally founded in 1887, the course was redesigned in 1926 by the great James Braid. Unlike many coastal links that are flat, Bogside is characterized by its massive ridges and deep hollows, which were created by the retreating sea centuries ago. The course is famously divided by a railway line, adding a unique industrial aesthetic to the rugged coastal landscape.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history, hosting the Scottish Amateur Championship and the Scottish Professional Championship. Its most famous member is likely the former Ryder Cup player Bernhard Langer, who won the European Open here in 1980. The turf at Bogside is the quintessence of links golf-firm, sandy, and fast-running. With its deep pot bunkers and the ever-present gorse, it is an uncompromising test of ball-striking. The traditional clubhouse is a treasure trove of golfing history, reflecting Irvine\'s status as one of the most respected and challenging links in the country.', ''),
('IrvineRavenspark', 'Irvine Ravenspark', 'https://www.irgc.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.631399, -4.680627, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000002f19c748f6b812c012ddb3aed1d04b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located just inland from the famous Bogside links, Irvine Ravenspark is a high-quality municipal course that offers a fascinating hybrid of links and parkland golf. Opened in 1907 to provide accessible golf to the local community, the course was refined by the esteemed architect J.R. Stutt. It features the same sandy, free-draining soil as its illustrious neighbor, ensuring excellent playing conditions year-round. While the front nine has a more open, links-like feel, the back nine moves into a more wooded environment with several challenging water hazards.\r\n\r\nRavenspark has a strong reputation for producing high-caliber amateur talent, including several Scottish internationalists. The course has frequently hosted regional qualifying for the Open Championship and the Scottish Public Courses Championship. One of the highlights of the round is the stretch of holes that run alongside the River Irvine, requiring precise club selection and a steady nerve. It is a friendly, inclusive club that prides itself on offering a championship-standard test at a public price point. For many local golfers, Ravenspark is the \"people\'s favorite\" providing a varied and engaging round of golf in the heart of Ayrshire.', ''),
('IsleofGigha', 'Isle of Gigha', 'https://www.visitgigha.co.uk/Golf', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 55.684323, -5.741755, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000f3936a9f8ef716c0477364e597d74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Isle of Gigha Golf Club offers one of the most unique and remote golfing experiences in the world. This 9-hole course is situated on a community-owned island off the Kintyre peninsula. Established in the early 20th century, the course is a \"natural links\" in the truest sense, with the routing dictated by the rugged shoreline and the ancient rocky outcrops of the island. The views from the coursestretching across the Atlantic to the Isles of Islay and Juraare simply breathtaking and often distract golfers from their game.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its lack of formality; there are no tee times, and the \"honesty box\" for green fees reflects the island\'s relaxed and trusting atmosphere. The layout is quirky and challenging, featuring blind shots and small greens that are perched on natural plateaus. It is a place where you can find total peace, with the only sounds being the waves and the wind. For the \"golfing adventurer\" a trip to Gigha is a mandatory pilgrimage to play a course that has remained unchanged by modern design, offering a pure and atmospheric connection to the origins of the game.', ''),
('IsleofHarris', 'Isle of Harris', 'https://www.harrisgolf.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 57.831904, -7.035926, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ec4d0cc9c9241cc0afb48cd47bea4c40, 'links', 'No', 'The Isle of Harris Golf Club, situated at Scarista, is often cited as the most beautiful 9-hole course in the world. Originally laid out in 1912 by Alick Marling, the course famously overlooks the turquoise waters of the Atlantic and the white sands of the Hebrides. It lay dormant for decades after the war until a group of determined locals revived it in 1985. The \"Links of Harris\" is a raw, natural experience where the fairways are grazed by sheep and the hazards are dictated by the rugged shoreline.\r\n\r\nThe club gained global fame when Sir Nick Faldo played here in the early 1990s as a quiet retreat to sharpen his game for the Masters. He was so charmed by the place that he left a signed 5 note in the \"honesty box\" for his green fee; that same fiver is now framed in the clubhouse and serves as the trophy for the annual \"Faldo Fiver\" competition. Without a single bunker to speak of, the course relies on the wind and the punishing Atlantic surf to defend its par. It is a spiritual home for golfers who prefer the elements and the \"honesty\" of the game over manicured perfection.', ''),
('isleofseilgolfclub', 'Isle of Seil', 'https://www.isleofseilgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 56.290632, -5.607163, 0, 2339, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000705d3123bc6d16c0e695eb6d33254c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located just over the famous \"Bridge Over the Atlantic\" the Isle of Seil Golf Club is a quirky and charming 9-hole course that defines community-led golf. Formed in 1995 after residents realized the island\'s potential for a local track, it was built primarily through the manual labor of its members. The course occupies the site of a 1910 layout that had been lost to time. It is a parkland-style course set on a working farm, meaning players must often negotiate the local livestock alongside the undulating fairways.\r\n\r\nWhile it does not have a \"celebrity\" architect, the routing was cleverly devised by the founding committee to maximize the views of the Slate Islands. The club is a pioneer in modern golf governance, having been one of the first in Scotland to consistently elect female captains based purely on merit. Its most notable tournament is the Highland Arts Burns Crystal, an 18-hole open that draws players from across Argyll. It is a \"social\" club in the best sense, where the 19th hole is often as important as the first, making it a favorite for those touring the Inner Hebrides.', ''),
('isleofskye', 'Isle of Skye', 'https://isleofskye.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://isleofskye.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'islands', 'No', 57.310196, -6.094685, 0, 0, '', '', 'isleofskye', 2975, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e2afc91af56018c0cdaca580b4a74c40, 'links', 'No', 'The Isle of Skye Golf Club, originally known as Sconser, sits in the dramatic shadow of the Cuillin Mountains. The course was designed in 1964 by the esteemed Dr. Frank Deighton, a former Walker Cup player and one of Scotland\'s most talented amateur golfers. Deighton\'s layout is a masterful use of a narrow strip of coastal land, offering a 9-hole experience with eighteen different tee positions that completely change the angle of attack for the second loop.\r\n\r\nThe club has a rugged history; for years, electric fences were required around the greens to keep the local sheep at bay. In 1987, the club rebranded to its current name to better reflect its status as the island\'s premier golfing destination. Famous for its \"Sea Hole\" where a wayward slice will see your ball vanish into the Raasay Sound, the course is a visual masterpiece. Deighton was so fond of his creation that his ashes were scattered on the fairways following his passing in 2018. It is a course that requires a low ball flight and a steady nerve, particularly when the Highland mist rolls off the peaks.', ''),
('jedburgh', 'Jedburgh', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/jedburgh#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/jedburgh#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'borders', 'No', 55.470625, -2.584005, 0, 0, 'no data', '', '', 0, 'jedburgh', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000959a3dd00aac04c00ad7a3703dbc4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Jedburgh Golf Club is a scenic parkland course that embodies the quiet dignity of the Scottish Borders. Founded in 1893, the course was significantly improved in the early 20th century with input from the legendary Willie Park Jr., a two-time Open Champion. Park\'s influence is seen in the clever use of the natural slopes of the Dunion hill, ensuring that very few lies are ever truly flat. The course is famously divided by the Jed Water, which provides a serene soundtrack to a round that is often quite taxing on the legs.\r\n\r\nThe club has long been a pillar of the Borders golfing community, producing numerous regional champions. It is known for its \"Lothian\" greensslick, undulating surfaces that require a soft touch. While it may not host the massive professional events of the coast, it is a regular venue for the Borders Golfers\' Association championships. The clubhouse, overlooking the historic abbey town, offers a warm, traditional welcome. For those who enjoy the \"mountain goat\" style of golf where elevation change is the primary hazard, Jedburgh is a classic example of late-Victorian inland design.', ''),
('keith', 'Keith', 'http://www.keithgolfclub.co.uk/', 'https://keith.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'No', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'No', 57.542279, -2.971117, 0, 0, 'no opens', '', 'keith', 840, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000091b75cfdd8c407c05f27f56569c54c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Keith Golf Club in Banffshire has a history of resilience. The original 1901 course was lost to the \"Dig for Victory\" campaign during World War II, but the club was resurrected in the 1960s thanks to a generous land donation from Colonel G.B. Kynoch. The current 18-hole layout was designed by Roy Phimister, the professional at Nairn, who created a parkland course that feels significantly more mature than its years. It is characterized by the Drum Burn, which snakes through the property and creates several \"do or die\" approach shots.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point for the local distilling community, with many members hailing from the world-famous Strathisla and Glenkeith distilleries. The layout is relatively short but notoriously tight, with gorse and broom punishing any lack of discipline off the tee. One of its most famous features is the 6th hole, which requires a blind shot over a corner of \"Out of Bounds\" territory to reach a green perched on a steep bank. It is an honest, welcoming Highland club that rewards accuracy and strategic play over raw distance, making it a favorite for local society outings.', ''),
('kelso', 'Kelso', 'https://kelso.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://kelso.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.612753, -2.431062, 0, 0, '', '', 'kelso', 1322, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000066344a2d07203c050c3b7b06ece4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kelso Golf Club offers one of the most unique settings in Scotland, as much of the course is situated within the perimeter of the Kelso Racecourse. Established in 1893, the course was significantly refined by James Braid, who managed to weave a challenging 18-hole parkland layout around the jumps and the grandstands. This proximity to the \"sport of kings\" gives the course a grand, expansive feel, with the flat racecourse land providing a fast-playing surface that stays remarkably dry even in the winter.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious reputation in the Borders and has hosted the Scottish Seniors\' Championship. Because the course is largely flat, it is an easy walk, but Braid\'s signature \"crater\" bunkers and the occasional racecourse rail provide plenty of strategic obstacles. Famous visitors over the years have included many of the UK\'s leading jockeys and trainers, who often squeeze in a round between races. It is a course of two halves: the holes inside the track are wide and inviting, while those outside the rails are tighter and more technical. Kelso is a masterclass in sharing space, offering a refined and historic golfing experience.', ''),
('kemnay', 'Kemnay', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kemnay#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kemnay#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.138475, -2.159094, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kemnay', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000029eb3713d34501c024287e8cb9914c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kemnay Golf Club is a lush, expansive parkland course in Aberdeenshire that has evolved significantly since its founding in 1908. While it began as a modest 9-hole track, it was transformed into a premier 18-hole venue in the 1990s under the guidance of architect Graeme Webster. Webster\'s design philosophy\"playability for all\"is evident here, with generous fairways that allow for a fun round while still incorporating enough bunkers and water to challenge the low handicapper.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its \"Amen Corner\" stretch near the end of the round, where the 16th, 17th, and 18th holes can ruin a good scorecard. The 18th in particular, a par-four with a daunting approach over a pond to a green in front of the clubhouse, was a later addition by Webster that provided the course with a truly dramatic finish. Kemnay is a frequent host of the Aberdeenshire County Championships and is widely regarded as having some of the most consistent greens in the North East. It is a friendly, modern club that manages to feel like a private estate, offering a high-quality, polished parkland experience.', ''),
('kilbirnieplace', 'Kilbirnie Place', 'https://www.kilbirnieplacegc.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.753457, -4.694477, 0, 2351, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000f94b8bfa24c712c09cf86a4771e04b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kilbirnie Place Golf Club, situated in the hills of North Ayrshire, is a course built on industrial pride. Founded in 1923, the course was established largely by and for the workers of the local steelworks. Originally a 9-hole course on the site of an old estate, it was extended to 18 holes by the members themselves, who hand-cleared the land to ensure the club\'s survival. This \"DIY\" history has resulted in a course with a rugged, honest character that follows the natural, rolling contours of the Garnock Valley.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its spectacular views toward the Firth of Clyde and the mountains of Arran. While it lacks a \"famous name\" architect, the layout is highly respected for its natural defense; the \"Place\" burn comes into play on several holes, requiring precise iron play. The club maintains a fiercely loyal membership and a reputation for being one of the most welcoming in the West of Scotland. It is the perfect example of a \"working man\'s\" course that has matured into a scenic and testing parkland gem, proving that great golf is often born from the passion of its players.', ''),
('killermont', 'Killermont', 'https://www.glasgowgolfclub.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.908421, -4.301579, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000003ca41820d13411c0f3ffaa2347f44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Killermont is the historic home of the Glasgow Golf Club, the 9th oldest in the world. The course was laid out in 1903 by the legendary Old Tom Morris and was famously his final full course design before his passing. Set within the grounds of a magnificent B-listed Georgian mansion that serves as the clubhouse, Killermont is a sanctuary of traditionalism. It is a pure parkland experience, characterized by massive, ancient trees and the winding River Kelvin, which guards several of the greens.\r\n\r\nThe club has hosted the Scottish PGA Championship and the Scottish Amateur, and its membership roll is a \"who\'s who\" of Glasgow\'s professional history. Unlike the club\'s other course at Gailes, which is a links, Killermont is a tactical, refined test that emphasizes placement over power. One of its most daunting features is the 2nd hole, a par-three of over 240 yards that remains one of the toughest one-shotters in the country. To play Killermont is to walk in the footsteps of the \"Grand Old Man of Golf\" on a canvas that has remained largely untouched for over a century.', ''),
('killin', 'Killin', 'https://www.killingolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 56.478979, -4.320978, 0, 2353, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000024f1f274ae4811c0433c122f4f3d4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Killin Golf Club is widely considered one of the most scenic 9-hole courses in the British Isles. Established in 1911 and situated at the heart of the Breadalbane region, the course was laid out with advice from John Duncan, the professional at Stirling. The course is a Highland parkland masterpiece, featuring dramatic elevation changes and views of the Falls of Dochart and the surrounding peaks of Ben Lawers. It is a course that doesn\'t just ask you to play golf; it asks you to admire the landscape.\r\n\r\nThe club has a rich community history, having been founded by a diverse group that included the local schoolmaster, the gamekeeper, and the minister. The signature hole is the par-three 9th, \"The Chasm\" where players must hit from an elevated tee over a deep, wooded ravine to a green perched on the hillside. While it hasn\'t hosted international professional tours, it is a favorite for visitors and was famously a haunt of the novelist Sir Walter Scott\'s descendants. It is an atmospheric, rugged, and intensely beautiful course that embodies the wild heart of Perthshire golf.', ''),
('kilmacolm', 'Kilmacolm', 'https://kilmacolm.hub.clubv1.com/visitors/TeeSheet', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.889688, -4.617044, 0, 0, '', '', 'kilmacolm', 1610, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000a8c5e061da7712c063d2df4be1f14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kilmacolm Golf Club is a stunning moorland course that feels like a Highland escape just half an hour from Glasgow. Established in 1891, the layout was refined by the prolific James Braid, who capitalized on the rugged, undulating terrain of the Knapps. The course is a riot of color in the summer, with purple heather and yellow gorse framing the fairways. Because it sits on high ground, it offers expansive views across the Clyde Valley to the peaks of Ben Lomond and the southern Highlands.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and has produced many fine players, including the 1935 Scottish Amateur champion Jack McLean. The course is notoriously difficult to play to your handicap, as the springy turf and natural hollows create unpredictable lies. One of its most famous features is the \"Valley of the Shadow\" a deep natural ravine that must be negotiated on the back nine. It is a traditional, friendly club that prides itself on maintaining Braid\'s strategic vision, offering a \"pure\" golfing experience where the wind and the terrain are the primary defenders.', ''),
('kilmarnockbarassie', 'Kilmarnock Barassie', 'https://www.kbgc.co.uk/visitor-booking-form', 'https://www.kbgc.co.uk/visitor-booking-form', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.562570, -4.650210, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000ef2076a6d09912c0f9da334b02c84b40, 'links', 'No', 'Kilmarnock (Barassie) Golf Club is a heavyweight of Scottish links golf. Founded in 1887, the course underwent a significant redesign in the 1930s by James Braid, creating a layout that is often mentioned in the same breath as Troon and Prestwick. It is a classic links, characterized by deep bunkers, firm fairways, and a constant, shifting sea breeze. The club has an immense tournament pedigree, having served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship and hosting the Scottish Amateur on multiple occasions.\r\n\r\nFamous members have included several Walker Cup players, and the club\'s professional tradition is strong. The course is unique for having 27 holes, with the main 18-hole championship layout known for its brutal closing stretch. The railway line runs parallel to several holes, adding to the traditional Ayrshire links atmosphere. Barassie is a true ball-striker\'s course; it doesn\'t rely on gimmicks, only on the quality of its turf and the strategic placement of its hazards. For any golfer touring the Ayrshire coast, it is an essential and historically significant stop.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/jZBFUlXRoXc?si=msR5aFCztII5cN8_');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('kilmarnockbarassie9', 'Kilmarnock Barassie - Hillhouse', 'https://www.kbgc.co.uk/visitor-booking-form', 'https://www.kbgc.co.uk/visitor-booking-form', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.562570, -4.650210, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000ef2076a6d09912c0f9da334b02c84b40, 'links', 'No', 'The Hillhouse course at Barassie consists of nine holes that, when combined with the nine holes of the \"new\" loop, create a second full 18-hole experience at this prestigious club. Despite being the \"secondary\" layout, Hillhouse is maintained to the same exacting championship standards as the main links. It offers a slightly different character, blending traditional links turf with areas that feel more like a sheltered heathland course, providing a varied and engaging round for those who have already tackled the main championship track.\r\n\r\nHillhouse is particularly popular with members for a quick, competitive game and serves as an excellent venue for junior development. It shares the same sandy, free-draining soil that makes Barassie playable throughout the year. While it may lack the international spotlight of the Open Qualifying holes, it features several tricky par-threes and tight fairways that demand precision. It is the perfect example of the \"depth of quality\" found at Scotland\'s premier golf clubs, ensuring that every golferfrom the high handicapper to the elite amateurhas a world-class surface to play on.', ''),
('kilspindie', 'Kilspindie', 'https://www.kilspindiegolfclub.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 56.010189, -2.879093, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.kilspindiegolfclub.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000e62329e9610807c0b4e386df4d014c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Kilspindie Golf Club is a \"hidden gem\" in the truest sense of the word. Tucked away on the Aberlady Bay in East Lothian, this 18th-oldest club in the world offers a pure, traditional links experience that is almost entirely unchanged since the 19th century. Originally a 9-hole course, it was extended to 18 in 1898 by the local professional Ben Sayers and Willie Park Jr. It is a short, par-69 course, but what it lacks in length, it makes up for in sheer charm and coastal beauty.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its intimacy; the first hole starts right beside the clubhouse wall, and the sea is in view on almost every shot. Notable members have included legends like Babe Zaharias, who reportedly loved the course for its fun and accessibility. Kilspindie is the perfect antidote to the \"modern championship\" course; it is a walking-friendly links where a creative short game is far more valuable than a 300-yard drive. With its hidden bunkers, stone walls, and proximity to the bird sanctuary, it is one of the most atmospheric and enjoyable rounds of golf in the \"Cradle of Golf.\"', ''),
('kilsythlennox', 'Kilsyth Lennox', 'https://www.kilsythlennox.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 55.985964, -4.047780, 0, 0, 'scottish golf app', '', '', 0, '', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000008d9c853ded3010c045847f1134fe4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kilsyth Lennox Golf Club is a rugged and scenic parkland-moorland hybrid that sits at the foot of the Kilsyth Hills. Founded in 1905, the course was redesigned and extended to its current 18-hole form in the 1970s. The layout is characterized by significant elevation changes, offering spectacular views across the Kelvin Valley toward the city of Glasgow and beyond. The course is built on a series of natural terraces, meaning you will often find yourself hitting from elevated tees to greens tucked into the folds of the hills.\r\n\r\nWhile it hasn\'t hosted the major professional tours, Kilsyth Lennox has a reputation for producing tough, resilient golfers who excel in the Stirlingshire county circuits. The course is known for its \"Burn holes\" where the local water system creates natural hazards that require careful management. It is a traditional, community-focused club that offers a warm welcome to visitors. The 13th hole, \"The Spectacles\" is a highlight, requiring a blind shot over twin mounds to reach the green. It is a course that rewards local knowledge and a steady nerve, offering a high-value, authentic Scottish golfing experience.', ''),
('kingarrockhickory', 'Kingarrock Hickory', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kingarrockhickory#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kingarrockhickory#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.294680, -3.002980, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kingarrockhickory', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000002e56d4601a0608c084640113b8254c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kingarrock Hickory Golf is a unique time-capsule and the only course of its kind in Europe. Located at Hill of Tarvit Mansion in Fife, this 9-hole course is played exclusively with original wooden-shafted hickory clubs and authentic low-compression balls from the 1920s. The course was originally the private plaything of the Sharp family, who owned the estate, but it was lost to farming during the war and only painstakingly restored in 2008 using the original 1924 plans.\r\n\r\nThere are no modern amenities hereno yardage markers, no graphite shafts, and no oversized heads. Golfers are provided with a heritage bag containing five clubs: a brassie, a mashie, a niblick, a mid-iron, and a putter. Playing Kingarrock is a masterclass in the \"art\" of the game over the \"science.\" Notable visitors have included golf historians from around the world seeking to experience the game as Bobby Jones or Walter Hagen would have played it. It is a peaceful, nostalgic experience that reminds every golfer that the heart of the game is about feel, creativity, and a touch of luck.', ''),
('kinghorn', 'Kinghorn', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kinghorn#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kinghorn#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.067432, -3.179766, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kinghorn', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000003e761728297009c0185a9d9ca1084c40, 'links', 'No', 'Kinghorn Golf Club is a delightful seaside links that offers one of the most enjoyable \"walks with a view\" in Fife. Founded in 1887, the course was originally designed by the legendary Old Tom Morris. It is a short but tricky layout that clings to the cliffs and hillsides overlooking the Firth of Forth. Because of its elevation, the wind is a constant and formidable opponent, often turning a modest par-four into a grueling struggle for par.\r\n\r\nThe course is municipal in nature, meaning it remains a vital part of the local community. While it lacks the length of championship tracks, it features some of the most memorable holes in the region, including several that require shots across deep coastal ravines. The view toward Edinburgh and the Bass Rock is a constant companion throughout the round. Kinghorn is proof that Old Tom Morris could create a challenging and engaging layout on any piece of land, regardless of size. It is a friendly, accessible course that provides a high-octane links experience without the high-octane green fee.', ''),
('kingjamesvi', 'King James VI', 'https://www.kingjamesvi.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.388760, -3.422660, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.kingjamesvi.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000006f9eea909b610bc019ff3ee3c2314c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'King James VI Golf Club holds the distinction of being the only golf course in the world situated on a river island. Located on Moncreiffe Island in the middle of the River Tay in Perth, the club was founded in 1858 and the course was designed by Old Tom Morris in 1897. Access to the course is via a narrow walkway attached to a railway bridge, which immediately sets the tone for a unique golfing adventure. The island setting means the course is perfectly flat, but it is surrounded by the rushing waters of the Tay and lined with mature trees.\r\n\r\nThe club is steeped in history and was named after the Scottish monarch who was a known enthusiast of the game. Because it is an island, the course has a unique microclimate and is famously lush and green throughout the summer. It has hosted many regional championships and is a favorite for those seeking a tranquil, \"secret\" golfing experience right in the heart of the city. While the river rarely comes directly into play, the psychological pressure of playing on an islandand the occasional sound of the trains overheadadds a fascinating layer of character to this historic Old Tom Morris gem.', ''),
('kings', 'Kings', 'https://kings.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://kings.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.463218, -4.262284, 0, 0, '', '', 'kings', 272, '', 0, 0, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000670e492d940c11c0927538ba4abb4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kings Golf Club in Inverness (formerly Torvean) is a relatively new addition to the Highland golf scene but one that has made a massive impact. Opened in 2019 to replace the old municipal course, the layout was designed by Stuart Rennie. It is a modern, championship-standard parkland course that was built to rival the quality of the famous links nearby. Rennie utilized the rolling terrain to create a \"stadium\" feel, with large, undulating greens and expansive white sand bunkers that give it a very high-end, professional look.\r\n\r\nDespite its young age, Kings has already hosted several prestigious amateur events and is a regular venue for the PGA Highlands Open. The course offers spectacular views over the city of Inverness and the Caledonian Canal. The signature hole is the par-three 14th, which plays across a valley to a well-guarded green. The modern clubhouse is a hub of activity and reflects the club\'s ambition to be a premier golfing destination. It is the perfect example of how modern design can create a challenging, visually stunning course that complements the traditional Highland landscape.', ''),
('kingsacre', 'Kings Acre', 'https://kingsacre.intelligentgolf.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.892600, -3.104520, 0, 0, '', 'https://kingsacre.intelligentgolf.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000002e39ee940ed608c06e3480b740f24b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located on the southern outskirts of Edinburgh, Kings Acre is a modern parkland course and academy that has become a center for golf development in the Lothians. Opened in the late 1990s, the course was designed by Graeme Webster and features a layout that is both challenging for the low-handicapper and accessible for the casual player. The design is characterized by large, USGA-spec greens and several significant water hazards that require strategic navigation.\r\n\r\nKings Acre is perhaps best known for its world-class academy and practice facilities, which have attracted many of Scotland\'s leading professionals for practice sessions. The course itself is beautifully manicured and offers views toward the Pentland Hills. It has a \"commercial\" feel in the best senseprofessional, well-organized, and focused on providing a high-quality experience. The par-five 18th is a fantastic finishing hole, requiring a brave approach over water to reach the green in two. It is a popular choice for corporate days and for golfers in the capital who want a polished, modern round of golf without the formality of an ancient private club.', ''),
('kingsbarns', 'Kingsbarns', 'https://www.kingsbarns.com/reservations', 'https://www.kingsbarns.com/reservations', 'No', 'No', '', '', 'mon,tue,wed,thu,fri,sat,sun', 'fife', '', 56.298953, -2.643927, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'a', 0xe610000001010000005517f032c32605c04205871744264c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Kingsbarns Golf Links is a modern masterpiece that feels as though it has been part of the Fife coastline for centuries. While golf was played here in the 1700s, the current course was designed by Kyle Phillips and opened in 2000. It is a man-made links of extraordinary scale, featuring wide, undulating fairways and tiered greens that offer spectacular views of the North Sea from every single hole. It is most famous as a co-host of the Alfred Dunhill Links Championship on the DP World Tour, where it consistently ranks as a favorite among the world\'s top professionals.\r\n\r\nThe course has hosted many of the game\'s greats, including Rory McIlroy. Its signature hole, the par-three 15th, requires a nerve-wracking carry over the surging Atlantic waves to a green perched on a rocky outcrop. Unlike the traditional \"out and back\" links, Kingsbarns is designed in two loops that maximize the dramatic elevation changes of the site. It is a high-end, world-class experience that combines the rugged beauty of traditional links golf with the polished service of a premier resort.', ''),
('kingsfield', 'Kingsfield', 'https://kingsfield.cw.sct.dotgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.982968, -3.553245, 0, 2365, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000007767edb60b6d0cc0dc813ae5d1fd4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kingsfield Golf & Leisure, located near Linlithgow, is a vibrant and modern facility designed to foster a love for the game. The 9-hole course was designed by Graeme Webster and serves as a high-quality \"short course\" that challenges experienced players while remaining accessible to beginners. The greens are built to USGA specifications, ensuring that the putting surfaces are among the truest in West Lothian. It is a parkland layout that emphasizes the \"fun\" aspect of golf, featuring wide fairways and clever bunkering.\r\n\r\nThe facility is particularly famous for its \"Ochil Course\" putting green, a massive, undulating 18-hole putting surface inspired by the Himalayas at St Andrews. Kingsfield is also home to a top-tier academy where several Scottish professionals, including Stephen Gallacher, have been known to practice. It is a community-focused hub that includes a TaylorMade performance center and high-tech driving range. For those looking for a relaxed yet high-quality golfing experience that fits into a busy schedule, Kingsfield is a pioneer of the modern Scottish golf model.', ''),
('kingsknowe', 'Kingsknowe', 'https://www.kingsknowe.com/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.914031, -3.262603, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.kingsknowe.com', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000e3a6069acf190ac0dd43c2f7fef44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kingsknowe Golf Club is a classic Edinburgh parkland course with a history dating back to 1908. The layout was originally designed by the legendary Alec Herd, the 1902 Open Champion, and later refined by the \"busiest man in golf\" James Braid. The course is characterized by its hilly terrain and mature woodland, providing a peaceful escape from the nearby city center. Its most distinctive feature is the railway line that runs parallel to several holes, adding a touch of Victorian industrial charm to the lush surroundings.\r\n\r\nThe club has a proud history of competitive amateur golf and has hosted numerous Lothians County events. Notable members have included prominent figures in Edinburgh\'s legal and medical professions, reflecting the club\'s traditional status. The greens at Kingsknowe are notoriously tricky, often sloping significantly and requiring a precise read. The signature 12th hole offers a stunning view across the city toward the Pentland Hills. It is a friendly, well-established club that rewards accuracy and stamina, offering a quintessential \"city parkland\" round with a historic pedigree.', ''),
('kingslinks', 'Kings Links', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kingslinks#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kingslinks#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.166720, -2.082972, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kingslinks', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000a4de5339eda900c068cbb91457954c40, 'links', 'No', 'Kings Links is a historic coastal course that provides the city of Aberdeen with a pure links experience right on its doorstep. As one of the oldest sites of golf in the worldwith records of the game being played here as far back as 1625it is a place of immense heritage. The current 18-hole layout is a traditional \"out and back\" links, running parallel to the North Sea beach. It is a flat, walking-friendly course characterized by firm turf, hidden pot bunkers, and the ever-present, biting coastal wind.\r\n\r\nThe course is municipal in nature, meaning it has served generations of Aberdonians as a training ground for the more famous links nearby. While it may not host the professional tours, its defense lies in its exposure to the elements; on a calm day, it is a delight, but in a gale, it is a formidable test of low-ball flight. It is famously free-draining, making it a popular choice for year-round golf. For visitors, Kings Links offers an authentic, \"no-frills\" connection to the origins of the game, played on land that has seen over 400 years of golfing history.', ''),
('kingussie', 'Kingussie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kingussie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kingussie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.091834, -4.053811, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kingussie', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000004a9143b1a3710c097546d37c18b4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Founded in 1891, Kingussie Golf Club is a spectacular Highland moorland course that sits high above the Spey Valley. The layout was refined by both Old Tom Morris and Harry Vardon, two of the most iconic figures in the history of the sport. Their influence is evident in the way the course works harmoniously with the natural peat hags, heather, and birch woodland. It is a physically demanding course, but the reward is a series of panoramic views of the Cairngorm Mountains that are among the best in Scotland.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its warm, traditional Highland hospitality and its small, tricky greens. Kingussie has long been a favorite for visiting societies who appreciate the \"raw\" nature of the terrain. The Gynack Burn meanders through the course, providing a natural hazard on several holes. It is a course that requires creativity rather than brute force, as the undulating fairways and mountain breezes demand a variety of shot shapes. To play Kingussie is to experience the \"Golden Age\" of golf architecture in one of the most breathtaking natural settings in the country.', ''),
('kinross', 'Kinross - Montgomery', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kinross#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kinross#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'perthshire', 'No', 56.210740, -3.414141, 0, 0, 'no data', '', '', 0, 'kinross', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000003e76172829500bc0c2fa3f87f91a4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Montgomery Course at the Green Hotel in Kinross is a premier parkland test that offers a \"championship\" feel. Designed by Colton & Co. and opened in the early 20th century, it was significantly updated by Donald Steel to meet modern standards. The course is named after the local estate and is characterized by its large, undulating greens and significant water hazards. It has a reputations for being the more challenging of the two courses at the resort, often used for regional qualifying and high-level amateur tournaments.\r\n\r\nThe layout is lush and well-wooded, providing a sheltered environment that contrasts with the windswept links of the coast. Famous visitors over the decades have included many of Scotland\'s leading political and business figures who frequent the hotel. The signature par-three 16th, played over a pond to a well-guarded green, is a notorious \"card-wrecker.\" The Montgomery offers a polished, professional golfing experience with manicured fairways and fast, true greens, making it a staple for those touring the heart of Scotland.\r\n', ''),
('kinrossbruce', 'Kinross - Bruce', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kinross#/course/3', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.209096, -3.421079, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kinross', 3, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000005342b0aa5e5e0bc0badc60a8c31a4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Bruce Course, the Montgomery\'s sibling at the Green Hotel, is often perceived as the more relaxed and \"fun\" of the two Kinross layouts, but it is certainly no pushover. Named after the legendary Scottish King, the course features a unique par-73 layout that includes four par-fives on the back nine. This makes it a favorite for long hitters and those looking to improve their birdie count. The design is more open than the Montgomery, allowing for a bit more freedom off the tee while still requiring a sharp short game.\r\n\r\nThe Bruce is particularly popular for society outings and corporate days due to its playability and scenic views over Loch Leven. Despite its more \"user-friendly\" reputation, it features several tricky dog-legs and well-placed bunkers that require strategic thinking. The course shares the same high maintenance standards as its sister, ensuring a quality playing surface year-round. It is a delightful, walking-friendly parkland course that provides a perfect complement to the tougher Montgomery, making the Kinross resort a comprehensive destination for any golfing group.', ''),
('kintore', 'Kintore', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kintore#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kintore#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.243763, -2.319758, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kintore', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000030134548dd8e02c0c87c40a0339f4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kintore Golf Club, located in Aberdeenshire, is a fascinating hybrid course that has evolved from a 9-hole layout founded in 1911 into a premier 18-hole parkland venue. The \"original\" nine holes are characterized by their hilly, moorland nature, while the newer nine, added in the 1990s and designed by Graeme Webster, offer a more modern, flatter parkland experience. This contrast makes for a varied and engaging round, as the player must adapt their strategy as they move between the two distinct sections of the course.\r\n\r\nThe club is a hub of the local community and is known for its friendly, inclusive atmosphere. The views from the higher holes stretch across the Don Valley toward the peak of Bennachie, providing a classic Highland backdrop. Kintore has hosted various North East District championships and is highly regarded for the quality of its greens. The signature 13th hole, \"The Tuach\" is a challenging par-four that requires a precise drive to a narrowing fairway. It is a course that perfectly blends the old and the new, offering a high-value and scenic round of golf in the heart of the \"Garioch.\"', ''),
('kirkcaldy', 'Kirkcaldy', 'https://kirkcaldygolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://kirkcaldygolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.099280, -3.193263, 0, 2372, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000fc36c478cd8b09c0cd920035b50c4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kirkcaldy Golf Club, known locally as \"Balwearie\" is a magnificent parkland course that was famously designed by Tom Morris Jr. (Young Tom Morris) in 1904. To play a course designed by the four-time Open Champion is a rare privilege, and the layout still retains much of its original character. The course is set in a secluded valley and is characterized by its lush, mature woodland and the Raith Burn, which meanders through the property and comes into play on several of the most challenging holes.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and has produced many fine amateur players who have represented Fife and Scotland. It is a regular host of the Fife County Championships. The layout is known for its fast, sloping greens and its \"stadium\" finish in front of the clubhouse. While it is located near the town center, the dense tree-lining provides a sense of total isolation. Kirkcaldy is a \"pure\" golf club that prides itself on its traditions and its challenging, high-quality playing surface. It is a must-play for anyone interested in the history of the Morris family and the development of parkland golf in Fife.', ''),
('Kirkcudbright', 'Kirkcudbright', 'https://www.kirkcudbrightgolf.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'south', '', 54.841017, -4.041712, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000002c67ef8cb62a10c0a530ef71a66b4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Established in 1893, Kirkcudbright Golf Club (pronounced \"Kir-coo-bree\") is a beautiful parkland course that offers spectacular views over the Dee Estuary and the historic \"Artists\' Town.\" The course was originally a 9-hole layout but was extended to 18 holes in the early 20th century with input from the legendary James Braid. Braid\'s influence is evident in the strategic use of the naturally undulating terrain and the well-protected greens. The course is famously lush, featuring a wide variety of mature trees and vibrant gorse.\r\n\r\nThe club has long been a favorite of the artistic community that made the town famous, and the clubhouse features several works by local artists. Notable tournaments held here include the South of Scotland Championship. The layout is relatively compact, requiring accuracy and a delicate touch around the greens rather than brute force. The 13th hole, \"The Pulpit\" offers a panoramic view that is often cited as the best in Dumfries and Galloway. It is a friendly, scenic, and historic club that provides a tranquil and refined golfing experience in one of the most beautiful corners of the country.', ''),
('kirkhill', 'Kirkhill', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kirkhill#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kirkhill#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.800443, -4.167457, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kirkhill', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000f1f109d979ab10c0f4a78dea74e64b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kirkhill Golf Club, located on the southern fringes of Glasgow, is a prestigious parkland course that celebrated its centenary in 2010. The layout was designed by the legendary James Braid, who masterfully utilized the rolling terrain to create a course that tests every facet of a player\'s game. It is characterized by its lush, tree-lined fairways and exceptionally fast, undulating greens. Because of its elevated position, the course offers panoramic views across the Clyde Valley toward the Campsie Fells.\r\n\r\nThe club has a storied history of competitive success, with its members frequently featuring in the final stages of the Lanarkshire County Championships. Notable members have included several professional footballers and prominent local businessmen, contributing to a vibrant and social atmosphere. The signature 13th hole, a par-three known as \"The Dell\" requires a precise shot to a green nestled in a natural hollow. Kirkhill remains a \"pure\" golf club that prioritizes the quality of its playing surface, offering a challenging and traditional Braid experience just a stone\'s throw from the city.', ''),
('kirkintilloch', 'Kirkintilloch', 'https://kirkintilloch.intelligentgolf.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.948759, -4.170037, 0, 0, '', 'https://kirkintilloch.intelligentgolf.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000009770e82d1eae10c0916456ef70f94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Established in 1895, Kirkintilloch Golf Club is a beautiful parkland gem situated at the foot of the Campsie Fells. The course reached its modern 18-hole form in the 1920s under the guidance of James Braid. Braid\'s signature strategic bunkering is evident throughout, forcing golfers to think their way around the course rather than simply relying on distance. The layout is divided by the Antonine Wall, providing a unique historical backdrop to several holes.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its \"Amen Corner\" stretch near the end of the round, where water hazards and tight fairways can quickly derail a good score. It has hosted various Dunbartonshire County events and is a regular venue for the PGA Scotland regional circuit. The clubhouse is known for its warm hospitality and overlooks a fantastic finishing hole that requires an approach over a burn. It is a traditional, friendly club that offers a varied and engaging test of golf, perfectly blending the tranquility of the countryside with a historic architectural pedigree.', ''),
('kirriemuir', 'Kirriemuir', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kirriemuir#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kirriemuir#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.689962, -2.998286, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kirriemuir', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ef6fd05e7dfc07c0cbbdc0ac50584c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kirriemuir Golf Club, located in the \"Gateway to the Glens\" is a scenic parkland course with a design history involving the great James Braid. Established in 1908, the course sits on the edge of the Angus glens, offering views of the Grampian Mountains that are nothing short of spectacular. The layout is characterized by its wide fairways and a diverse range of mature trees, including silver birch and pine. It is the birthplace of Sir J.M. Barrie, the creator of Peter Pan, and the club embraces this heritage with several holes named in honor of the \"Boy Who Never Grew Up.\"\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its immaculate conditioning and its remarkably true greens. While it is not an overly long course, the subtle undulations and the local breezes provide a constant challenge. Notable tournaments held here include the Scottish Seniors\' Championship. It is a welcoming, community-focused club where the focus is on the sheer enjoyment of the game in a beautiful Highland setting. For those looking for a tranquil and historic round of golf in the heart of Angus, Kirriemuir offers a refined and charming experience.', ''),
('knightswood', 'Knightswood', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/knightswood#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 55.894479, -4.351611, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'knightswood', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000caa7c7b60c6811c0b9fab1497ef24b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Knightswood Golf Course is one of Glasgow\'s most popular municipal 9-hole layouts, providing an essential gateway to the game for the city\'s residents. Originally part of a larger estate, the course was opened to the public in the mid-20th century to meet the rising demand for accessible sport. It is a flat, easy-to-walk parkland course that features surprisingly large greens and well-placed bunkering. Despite its urban location, the course is remarkably peaceful, acting as a green lung for the West End of Glasgow.\r\n\r\nThe course is a vital \"nursery\" for the local golfing community, where many of Glasgow\'s club golfers first learned their swing. While it does not host professional tours, it is a hub for the Glasgow Municipal Golf Clubs\' Association and hosts regular amateur competitions. The layout is designed to be forgiving for beginners while still providing enough of a challenge to keep experienced players coming back for a quick afternoon round. It is a shining example of public-sector golf, proving that high-quality, fun, and affordable golf can thrive in the heart of a major city.', ''),
('krtb', 'Turnberry - King Robert the Bruce', 'https://www.turnberry.co.uk/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'turnberry', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.315405, -4.833056, 24433, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe6100000010100000041f2cea10c5513c058ffe7305fa84b40, 'links', 'No', 'The King Robert the Bruce course at the world-famous Turnberry resort is a spectacular links that underwent a total transformation in 2017. Designed by Martin Ebert (who also handled the Ailsa redesign), it was named in honor of the Scottish King who was born in the adjacent Turnberry Castle in 1274. The course utilizes the dramatic, rugged coastline of Ayrshire, offering views of the Ailsa Craig and the lighthouse that rival those of its world-ranking sibling.\r\n\r\nWhile it shares the same hallowed turf as the Ailsa, the King Robert the Bruce course has its own distinct personality, with several holes playing across high ridges and deep coastal ravines. It has hosted the AIG Women\'s Open and remains a favorite for high-end corporate events. Famous visitors include every major name in modern golf, from Tiger Woods to Jack Nicklaus. It is an uncompromising and visually stunning test of links golf, featuring \"infinity\" greens and deep, revetted bunkers that demand total commitment from the tee to the cup.', ''),
('KylesofBute', 'Kyles of Bute', 'https://www.kylesofbutegolfclub.co.uk/visitors', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 55.887552, -5.250987, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000076e272bc020115c0ecbfce4d9bf14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', '', ''),
('ladybank', 'Ladybank', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/ladybank#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'clubv1', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.282370, -3.124200, 0, 0, '', '', '', 1058, 'ladybank', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000003c4ed1915cfe08c08eaf3db324244c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Ladybank Golf Club in Fife is one of the most prestigious and historic heathland courses in the world. Originally a 6-hole course designed by Old Tom Morris in 1879, it was eventually expanded to 18 holes, with the layout we see today largely being the work of J.R. Stutt. Ladybank is a premier Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship and has hosted some of the greatest names in the game during their quest to reach the world\'s oldest major.\r\n\r\nThe course is a sanctuary of Scots pine, heather, and silver birch. Famous members include Dale Reid, the legendary Solheim Cup captain, and the club has a reputation for producing elite amateur talent. Unlike the nearby links, Ladybank offers a sheltered, tactical test where a driver is often best left in the bag in favor of a well-placed iron shot. The greens are famously fast and true, requiring a delicate touch. It is a refined, aristocratic club that offers a pure and uncompromising test of golf, representing the very pinnacle of Scottish inland course design.', ''),
('lamlash', 'Lamlash', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lamlash#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lamlash#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 55.545452, -5.129485, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'lamlash', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000004d4a41b7978414c0d6c4025fd1c54b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', '', ''),
('lanark', 'Lanark', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lanark#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lanark#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.672256, -3.745194, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'lanark', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000004567994528f60dc017450f7c0cd64b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lanark Golf Club is the 25th oldest golf club in the world and a true heavyweight of the Scottish moorland game. Founded in 1851, the course was originally laid out by Old Tom Morris and later refined by James Braid. It sits on high ground overlooking the Clyde Valley and is characterized by its firm, sandy, and fast-draining soil-giving it the playing characteristics of a links course despite being miles from the sea. It is a perennial Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship.\r\n\r\nThe course is a masterclass in strategic design, with deep bunkers and thick heather punishing any wayward shots. Famous members have included titans of the Scottish textile industry and champion amateurs like Charlie Green. Lanark is known for its impeccable conditioning and its sense of history; the clubhouse is a treasure trove of early golfing artifacts. The layout is a stern but fair test that requires every club in the bag and a creative approach to shot-making. It is one of the most respected courses in the country, offering a world-class experience in a peaceful and historic setting.', ''),
