('minto', 'Minto', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/minto#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/minto#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.947673, -3.189284, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'minto', 1, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000009e3f6d54a78309c0af264f594df94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', '', ''),
('moffat', 'Moffat', 'https://www.moffatgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.moffatgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'south', 'Yes', 55.328152, -3.460673, 0, 2448, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000a033695375af0bc0fa0e7ee200aa4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', '', ''),
('monifieth', 'Monifieth - Medal', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/monifieth#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/monifieth#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.485781, -2.797341, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'monifieth', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe6100000010100000059147651f46006c0540262122e3e4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'The Medal Course at Monifieth Links is a titan of Angus golf and a frequent Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship. This traditional links land has a history of golf dating back to at least 1639. The course was originally designed by Old Tom Morris and later refined by James Braid, creating a layout that is both historic and uncompromising. It is famously the place where Tom Watson played his first-ever round of links golf before going on to win the Open at nearby Carnoustie in 1975.\r\n\r\nThe course is characterized by its deep bunkers, firm fairways, and the railway line that runs parallel to the early holes. Notable for its difficulty when the wind blows off the Tay Estuary, the Medal Course requires a wide variety of shot-making. It has hosted every major amateur championship in Scotland and remains a favorite for low-handicappers seeking a pure links test. The turf is of the highest quality, and the sense of history is palpable from the first tee to the final green. Monifieth Medal is an essential stop for any serious golfer visiting the Dundee area.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/km4AgpynF18?si=J5ynCGz-4LmZZZYq'),
('monifiethashludie', 'Monifieth - Ashludie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/monifieth#/course/3', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.485781, -2.797341, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'monifieth', 3, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000059147651f46006c0540262122e3e4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'The Ashludie Course is the Medal\'s shorter, quirkier, and arguably more fun younger sibling at Monifieth Links. While it measures just over 5,000 yards, it is no \"pushover\"; the small, undulating greens and tight fairways require a high degree of precision and a sharp short game. It was designed to provide a more accessible alternative to the championship course, but it has become a favorite in its own right for those looking for a fast, engaging round of links golf.\r\n\r\nThe Ashludie is often used for junior development and senior tournaments, but it also serves as a tactical warm-up for those heading to the Medal. It shares the same sandy, free-draining soil that makes Monifieth a year-round destination. Notable for its many par-threes and narrow corridors through the gorse, the course rewards the \"thinking\" golfer over the long hitter. It is a beautifully maintained track that offers all the traditional links challenges on a more compact scale. For many visitors, a day at Monifieth isn\'t complete without \"taking on the Ashludie\" after lunch.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/ZTUJzwSMtbo?si=moQFs5MMMAGYn18p'),
('montrosegolflinks', 'Montrose - 1562', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/montrosegolflinks#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/montrosegolflinks#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.709265, -2.462915, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'montrosegolflinks', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000006b9f8ec70cb403c046990d32c95a4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Montrose Golf Links is the fifth oldest golf course in the world, with the game having been played on this site since 1562. The \"Medal\" course was originally laid out by Willie Park Jr. and later refined by James Braid, creating a masterpiece of traditional links design. It is unique for its \"T-shaped\" routing, which ensures that the wind affects the golfer from every possible angle during the round. It has served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship and remains one of the most respected links in Scotland.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its proximity to the North Sea, with several holes hugging the cliff edge. This beauty comes with a challenge, as coastal erosion is a constant battle for the club. Notable members have included legends of the local community and figures from Scotland\'s early golfing history. The 1562 course is a sanctuary of deep bunkers, natural dunes, and fast-running turf. To play here is to walk in the footsteps of over four centuries of golfers, offering a historic and spiritually moving connection to the origins of the game.', ''),
('montrosegolflinksbroomfield', 'Montrose - Broomfield', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/montrosegolflinks#/course/3', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.709265, -2.462915, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'montrosegolflinks', 3, 0, 'e', 0xe610000001010000006b9f8ec70cb403c046990d32c95a4c40, 'links', 'No', '', ''),
('moray', 'Moray - Old', 'https://www.brsgolf.com/moray/visitor_home.php', 'https://www.brsgolf.com/moray/visitor_home.php', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.719109, -3.315948, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'moray', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe6100000010100000093e4b9be0f870ac030a182c30bdc4c40, 'links', 'No', 'The Old Course at Moray Golf Club in Lossiemouth is a legendary links designed in 1889 by the \"Grand Old Man of Golf\" Old Tom Morris. It is a pure, traditional layout that starts and finishes within the town, much like the Old Course at St Andrews. The course is famous for its deep, revetted bunkers, gorse-lined fairways, and its signature finishing hole-a par-four that requires an approach over a steep bank to a green overlooked by the magnificent clubhouse.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and has hosted many of the game\'s greats, including Sir Henry Cotton, who reportedly loved the challenge of the Moray turf. It has served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship and regularly hosts the Scottish Amateur Championship. One of its most unique features is the proximity to the RAF Lossiemouth airbase; the sight and sound of fighter jets soaring overhead provides a dramatic and modern contrast to the ancient links. Moray Old is a masterclass in classic design, offering a rugged, honest, and intensely atmospheric round of golf.', ''),
('moraynew', 'Moray - New', 'https://www.moraygolf.co.uk/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.719109, -3.315948, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'moray', 3, 1, 'c', 0xe6100000010100000093e4b9be0f870ac030a182c30bdc4c40, 'links', 'No', 'The New Course at Moray Golf Club is far from a secondary consideration; it is a championship-standard links in its own right. Designed by the legendary Henry Cotton and opened in 1970, it offers a distinct contrast to the Old Tom Morris layout next door. While the Old Course is wide and grand, Cotton\'s \"New\" is tighter, more intricate, and arguably more punishing for the wayward driver. It winds through the dense gorse of the Lossiemouth dunes, requiring a strategic \"iron-off-the-tee\" approach on several holes.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its par-threes, which are often cited as some of the most difficult in the North East, especially when the wind whips off the Moray Firth. Notable for its impeccably fast greens, the New Course frequently hosts the Scottish Ladies\' Championship and regional pro-ams. It shares the same dramatic backdrop of RAF Lossiemouth, where the roar of Typhoon jets provides a modern soundtrack to a very traditional links challenge. For many members, the New is the preferred \"daily\" test because of its relentless demand for accuracy and its beautifully secluded atmosphere within the gorse.', ''),
