('muirfield', 'Muirfield', 'https://www.muirfield.org.uk/visitors-new/', 'https://www.muirfield.org.uk/visitors-new/', 'No', 'No', '', '', 'tue,thu', 'eastlothian', '', 56.045209, -2.822420, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'a', 0xe610000001010000004e9cdcef509406c0103e9468c9054c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Muirfield, the home of The Honourable Company of Edinburgh Golfers, is arguably the most respected and strategically perfect links in the world. Founded in 1744 (though moving to Muirfield in 1891), the course was designed by Old Tom Morris and later refined by Harry Colt. It is unique for its \"two-loop\" design: the front nine travels clockwise around the perimeter, while the back nine travels counter-clockwise in the center. This ensures the wind attacks the golfer from every possible direction.\r\n\r\nMuirfield has hosted The Open Championship 16 times, with winners including Jack Nicklaus (who named his own course, Muirfield Village, after it), Gary Player, Tom Watson, and Phil Mickelson. It is a sanctuary of deep, revetted bunkers and perfectly manicured fairways. The clubhouse is a cathedral of golfing history, and the legendary \"Muirfield Lunch\" is as famous as the course itself. While it is a private and traditional club, a round at Muirfield is the ultimate bucket-list item for any serious golfer-a masterclass in design, history, and the highest standards of the game.', ''),
