('Orkney', 'Orkney', 'https://orkneygolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 58.987713, -2.982313, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe61000000101000000357c0bebc6db07c0c26a2c616d7e4d40, 'nonlinks', 'No', '', ''),
('paisley', 'Paisley', 'https://paisley.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.812064, -4.444690, 0, 0, '', '', 'paisley', 164, '', 0, 0, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000d66ebbd05cc711c0252191b6f1e74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Paisley Golf Club, often referred to locally as \"Bushes\" is a magnificent moorland course located within the Gleniffer Braes Country Park. Founded in 1894, the course was redesigned in the 1950s by Philip Mackenzie Ross, the architect responsible for the post-war restoration of the Ailsa course at Turnberry. The layout is perched high above the town of Paisley, offering views that, on a clear day, extend all the way to the southern Highlands and the Cumbrae Isles.\r\n\r\nThe club has a strong competitive pedigree and has hosted the Scottish Youths\' Championship and numerous PGA Scotland regional events. It is characterized by its narrow fairways, thick heather, and strategic bunkering that punishes the wayward driver. Notable for its lush conditioning and challenging par-threes, Paisley is a \"thinking man\'s\" course where local knowledge is key to navigating the rolling terrain. It is a friendly, vibrant club that provides a high-quality, championship-standard test of golf in a stunningly scenic and elevated setting.', ''),
('Palacerigg', 'Palacerigg', 'http://palacerigggolfclub.co.uk/index.html', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'edinburgh', '', 55.936273, -3.942072, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'e', 0xe6100000010100000089d1730b5d890fc05c902dcbd7f74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', '', ''),
('panmure', 'Panmure', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/panmure#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/panmure#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.490343, -2.772167, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'panmure', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000496760e4652d06c04969368fc33e4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Panmure Golf Club is a world-class links located in Carnoustie, often cited as one of the most underrated courses in Scotland. Established in 1845, the current layout at Barry Links was designed with input from Old Tom Morris and James Braid. It is famously the place where Ben Hogan spent two weeks practicing before his legendary 1953 Open victory at Carnoustie. Hogan suggested several changes to the 6th hole, which the club adopted and still carries his name today.\r\n\r\nThe course is a \"hidden\" links, with many holes winding through dunes and corridors of Scots pine, giving it a unique character compared to the more exposed local tracks. It has served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship and is a regular host for the Scottish Amateur Championship. The greens are notoriously firm and fast, and the bunkering is among the most strategic in the country. Panmure is a refined, private club that offers a pure and historic links experience, where the ghost of Hogan seems to linger on every fairway.', ''),
