('prestwick', 'Prestwick', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/prestwick#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/prestwick#/course/1', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.501550, -4.614830, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'prestwick', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000001366dafe957512c087a757ca32c04b40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Prestwick Golf Club is a hallowed site and the birthplace of The Open Championship, having hosted the very first tournament in 1860. Originally designed by Old Tom Morris, who also served as the club\'s first keeper of the green, the course is a raw and uncompromising links. It is famous for its eccentricities, including massive dunes, blind shots, and the \"Alps\" hole-the oldest and most famous blind approach in the world. Prestwick hosted The Open 24 times before the tournament grew too large for the site.\r\n\r\nThe club remains one of the most traditional and exclusive in the world, yet it offers a warm welcome to visitors looking to walk in the footsteps of the giants of the game. Notable members have historically included the pioneers of modern golf. To play Prestwick is to experience a time capsule of 19th-century links architecture; it is creative, unpredictable, and spiritually moving. Every hole tells a story, from the \"Cardinal\" bunker to the \"Sea Heugh.\" It is a mandatory pilgrimage for any serious student of the game\'s history.', ''),
('prestwickstcuthbert', 'Prestwick St Cuthbert', 'https://prestwickstcuthbert.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://prestwickstcuthbert.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.490131, -4.595566, 0, 0, '', '', 'prestwickstcuthbert', 1303, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002a70b20ddc6112c0bde0d39cbcbe4b40, 'links', 'No', 'Prestwick St Cuthbert is a premier parkland course that offers a distinct contrast to the famous links neighbors in the town. Established in 1899, the current layout was designed in the 1960s by the respected architect P.M. Ross. The course is characterized by its lush, manicured fairways and its over 1,000 mature trees, creating a parkland oasis in the heart of the \"Ayrshire Golf Coast.\" It is a relatively flat course, making it an easy and enjoyable walk for all ages.\r\n\r\nThe club has a vibrant and competitive membership, frequently hosting the Ayrshire Strokeplay Championship and regional PGA Scotland events. Notable for its impeccably true greens and strategic bunkering, St Cuthbert is a \"fair\" test that rewards accuracy and a sharp short game. The traditional clubhouse is known for its excellent hospitality and views over the 18th green. It is a friendly, professional club that provides a high-quality, polished parkland experience, making it a favorite for those looking for a break from the punishing coastal gorse.', '');
